<1ST_LINE>r i PM-APArts:Caron     09-01 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Caron,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leslie Caron Revels In Gigi's Other Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She was a waif-like but winsome coquette whose
delicious romantic romps added a touch of whimsy to the 1950s and
early '60s. Today, Leslie Caron, the ``Gigi'' of yesteryear, is a
grandmother who's about to portray the matriarch of fashion Coco
Chanel in a TV movie.
   She's also written a book of short stories called ``Vengeance,''
and a screenplay she describes as a ``parable of war.''
   ``I suppose I have two sides to my nature,'' Caron said in an
interview. ``But I'm not cute. Whatever I am, cute is not the
word.''
   Caron retains a place in film history, a time when the musical
embodied the spirit and romance of an era. Beginning in 1951 with
Gene Kelly in ``An American in Paris,'' through ``Daddy Longlegs''
with Fred Astaire in 1955 to 1958's Academy Award-winning ``Gigi,''
she won the hearts of audiences around the world.
   But now, more than three decades later at the age of 57, she is
remembered mainly as America's French gamine-in-residence.
   While still a teen-ager, Caron was plucked from a Paris ballet
by Kelly, who took her to Hollywood where she went under contract
for MGM.
   ``I was stereotyped after `An American in Paris,''' she said.
``And I think Americans a long, long time ago decided that I was
cute, a gamine and all those things. Actually, I'm a very serious
person.''
   Caron credits much of her artistic bent to the legacy left by
her American-born mother, a dancer whose own dreams went
unfulfilled. ``My mother protected me and helped me fulfill my
wishes. But I think they were the expression of her wishes.''
   Her mother's suicide in 1967 stoked her determination and left
``a feeling of unfinished business.'' As she approached 40, she
took up writing and refuge in Paris, her hometown.
   A word processer sits on a table i her living room. Caron had
just returned from the printer with the script of the film she
wrote and plans to direct.
   ``It's a moral tale. It's about the incapacity of people to get
along. In other words, it's a parable of war on a family scale,''
she said.
   The screenplay, whose title she refuses to divulge, is to be a
family affair. She hopes her children, Christopher and
actress-daughter, Jennifer, who has given her a grandchild, will
participate in the project. Both are the children of her second
marriage to Peter Hall, director of Britain's National Theater.
Caron has been married three times.
   She has written what she calls a ``good part'' for herself,
meaning neither cute nor guileless. ``I might have been innocent
and guileless when I was 18,'' she said. ``But, my God, the years
have passed and I've lived quite a lot of drama. And the public
keeps seeing the same films on the television.''
   In 1984, Doubleday and Co. published a collection of her short
stories, ``Vengeance.''
   ``They are sort of brutal,'' she said. ``No, cruel is the better
word. I do have a sharp eye and a wicked sense of humor.''
   As a one-time star still at work, Caron is finally able to
stretch herself as an actress in a variety of roles.
   ``For the last 10 years, the spectrum of parts I'm offered just
swings widely,'' she said.
   Most recently, she portrays Chanel in a syndicated TV miniseries
for the fall season, ``The Man Who Lived at the Ritz.'' Based on
the best-selling novel by A.E. Hotchner, it is the story of an
American artist, played by Perry King, caught in wartime Paris
between the Resistance and the Nazis.
   Last year, Caron played the submissive wife of Lenin, portrayed
by Ben Kingsley in the movie, ``The Train,'' which recounted the
exiled Lenin's journey home to start the Russian Revolution. She
also appeared in an episode last year on TV's ``Falcon Crest.''
   Caron thinks of herself as a survivor.
   ``I remember a rather cruel producer, cruel and rude, who said
as she hired me that she so admired (Brigitte) Bardot for retiring
when she was losing her looks,'' Caron recalled. ``I think it's so
against everything I believe because so long as there is life,
there's a contribution you can make. ... I think one must not just
be banking on one's looks.''
</TEXT>
