<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--ToxicAlgae     09-01 0113</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Toxic Algae,0113</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Ban Shellfish Collection On Section Of Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREST, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toxic algae have been detected off the
northwestern edge of Brittany, forcing officials to prohibit the
harvest or sales of any shellfish along a section of the coast.
   An order issued by the district prefecture this week forbids any
commercial distribution of shellfish from the Abers coast, a
stretch of about 12 miles at the northwestern tip of France.
   Scientists from the French Institute for Research and
Exploitation of the Sea were called to determine the extent of the
infestation by the microscopic protogonyaulax algae, which can
cause minor paralysis and blurred vision if eaten by humans.
</TEXT>
