<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-01 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Cleveland Quartet left the United States
for a tour of Europe and the Soviet Union, cellist Paul Katz bought
the usual two airplane seats: one for himself and one for his 1736
Stradivarius cello.
   As part of its ticket privileges, the Rochester, N.Y.-based
quartet received hotel accommodations before continuing Tuesday to
Turin, Italy.
   The hotel clerk proudly informed Katz that he had the largest
room, a double with a queen-size bed, for Paul Katz and Cello Katz.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The by-product of the elephants featured in
``The Greatest Show On Earth'' is, as one might expect, mammoth.
   Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus officials were willing
to give away manure from King Tusk and his pachyderm pals during
the show's two-day stay here.
   However, few showed up to take advantage of the super-rich
fertilizer. The circus claims the manure is high in nitrates and
calcium, making it perfect for the backyard or window box gardener.
   There's one catch. Circus manure must dry for at least 90 days
before being spread or it will burn up the plants and soil.
   That didn't deter painter John Ellick, who scooped up 2{
20-gallon trash bags of elephant dung from a garbage bin full of
manure.
   Ellick said he can't wait to see what crops will pop up next
year from his 50-by-150-foot garden in Douglas about 50 miles
southeast of Lincoln.
   ``I might grow humongous tomatoes,'' he said. ``I could have
eggplants the size of footballs, cucumbers the size of tusks. I can
only imagine what next year's garden will be like.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Richard Stammler was flying an Air
Force transport to a refueling rendezvous five miles over Scotland
when a familiar voice crackled over the radio.
   His younger brother, Capt. Robert Stammler, was calling from the
air tanker where he was evaluating the maneuver as part of his
assignment with the Strategic Air Command to train U.S. crews
stationed in Europe.
   ``When I heard his voice, I said, `Gosh, it's him,''' Richard
Stammler, 44, told his his hometown newspaper, the Erie News.
   As the two C-135s hurtled at 700 mph only 30 feet apart, the
brothers, who hadn't seen each other for two years, chatted briefly.
   The two had to keep their conversation official during the
15-minute refueling July 19, but got a chance two days later for a
longer reunion on the ground.
   Richard Stammler, commander of the Royal Air Force's 10th
Airborne Command and Control Squadron based in Mildenhall, England,
was flying an EC-135, a four-engine jet equipped with
communications and command electronics.
   His brother was on temporary assignment from the 46th Air
Refueling Squadron, Sawyer Air Force Base, Mich. He was aboard a
KC-135 from the RAF base at Fairford.
   Richard Stammler said that when he learned the refueling was to
be evaluated, he suspected his brother might be aboard the tanker.
Robert Stammler is one of only a few Air Force navigators assigned
to monitor the maneuver and had recently been assigned to Fairford.
</TEXT>
