<HEAD>Wave Of Strikes Led To Walesa-Government Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the two weeks of
labor unrest leading up to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa's first
meeting with top government officials since 1982:
   Aug. 16 _ Angry miners declare occupation strike at Manifest
Lipcowy mine in Jasztrebie after they were disappointed by
paychecks.
   Aug. 17 _ Miners at Morcinek mine near Jastrzebie and port
workers in Szczecin declare solidarity strikes with Manifest
Lipcowy.
   Aug. 18 _ Five mines in southwestern Poland and port and dock
workers in Szczecin are now on strike.
   Aug. 19 _ The government's Council of Ministers issues
communique saying it will not recognize banned Solidarity union
federation, chief demand of the strikers.
   Aug. 21 _ Twelve mines and port and dock workers in Szczecin on
strike. Lenin shipyard in Gdansk announces strike for Monday Aug.
22.
   Aug. 22 _ Strike begins at Lenin shipyard in Gdansk. Police
storm striking bus depot in Gdansk.
   Aug. 25 _ Police clear strikers from three mines.
   Aug. 26 _ Poland's Roman Catholic bishops issue appeal for
peaceful end to strikes. Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak
proposes roundtable talks with representatives of workers.
   Aug. 27 _ Plenum of Communist Party Central Committee opens in
Warsaw.
   Sunday _ Plenum endorses roundtable idea.
   Monday _ Strikes intensify at Stalowa Wola steel mill in
southern Poland.
   Tuesday _ Walesa announces he will travel to Warsaw for first
meeting with Polish authorities in six years.
   Wednesday _ Walesa meets with Kiszczak on eighth anniversary of
signing of Gdansk agreements that legalized Solidarity and calls
for Polish workers to return to work.
</TEXT>
