<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SexResearchersWed     09-01 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Researchers Wed,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sex Researchers To Get Married</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   June Reinisch and Leonard A. Rosenblum, two
noted sex researchers, feel no pressure to establish the perfect
marriage. In fact, they're not even planning to live together.
   Because their home cities of New York and Indianapolis are so
far apart, the two have even decided on two marriage ceremonies,
and Reinisch says their long-distance relationship will continue
after the weddings.
   ``The marriage will not affect our careers,'' she said recently.
   The first ceremony will be Saturday at Sammy's Rumanian
Restaurant in New York. The second will be Sept. 10 at the
Indianapolis home of mutual friends.
   Reinisch, 45, is director of the famed Kinsey Institute for
Research in Sex, Gender and Reproduction at Indiana University,
founded in the 1940s by Dr. Alfred C. Kinsey, one of the first
scientists to study human sexual behavior.
   Rosenblum, 52, is a professor in the Department of Psychiatry of
the State University of New York's Health Sciences Center in
Brooklyn. He is a founding member of the International Academy of
Sex Research.
   The two have collaborated, delivering papers at conferences and
editing a Kinsey Institute volume entitled,
``Masculinity-Feminity,'' published by the Oxford University Press
in 1987.
   Reinisch and Rosenblum, both divorced, have been engaged a long
time, according to Reinisch. ``But it has been kept quiet until
now.''
   She says Rosenblum's work occasionally brings him to the
Midwest. They both attend many of the same professional meetings,
and have the same book publisher in New York.
   ``But we hope someday to live in the same city,'' she said.
</TEXT>
