<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EndangeredWoodpecker     09-01 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Endangered Woodpecker,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politicians Side with Loggers, not Birds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge's order to protect a
little-known species of woodpecker is at the heart of a tug-of-war
between environmentalists and loggers over clear-cutting in the
national forests of Texas.
   Naturalists estimate there are only about 180 to 190
red-cockaded woodpecker colonies left in Texas, with about two
birds to a colony, compared to the 500 or so needed to maintain a
viable population.
   At issue is U.S. District Judge Robert M. Parker's ruling that
seeks to protect the endangered bird by barring U.S. Forest Service
contractors from cutting down entire stands of trees within
three-fourths of a mile of a woodpecker colony, restricting the
harvest of trees near nests, and limiting the use of roads near
where the woodpeckers live or forage.
   Politicians have been quick to denounce the decision, saying the
restrictions could eliminate hundreds of jobs for truckers,
saw-millers and lumberjacks.
   Rep. Jim Chapman, D-Texas, says he doesn't care if the
woodpecker becomes extinct. ``Humankind and the biological order
can get along just fine without this bird,'' he says.
   Environmentalists say the selective harvesting they advocate
would require more _ not fewer _ loggers than clear-cutting, which
is heavily mechanized.
   But Chapman says he is concerned that the Forest Service will
overreact and fail to harvest as much as it still can in the
Sabine, Davy Crockett, Angelina and Sam Houston National Forests.
   Forest Service spokesman Carl Gidlund said the judge's ruling
covers 473 miles of roads _ almost a fourth of the 2,000 total
miles of roads in the four East Texas forests.
   ``I'm encouraging them to cut in as close as they can, because
we're talking about jobs,'' says Chapman. ``By taking the
conservative approach, they're not selling the timber under the
court order I suspect they could sell.''
   Environmentalists contend that clear-cutting caused a
precipitous 10 percent drop in the bird's population over the past
five years, and said such timbering practices were violating the
Endangered Species Act.
   Parker in his June 17 ruling agreed and told the Forest Service
to alter its harvesting practices to ``uneven-age'' or ``selection
management.''
   Parker ordered the agency to file a plan to comply with his
order, but the Forest Service has responded by proposing a
compromise between clear-cutting and selection management that
environmentalists oppose. A Sept. 28 hearing is scheduled.
   Ned Fritz of the Texas Committee for Natural Resources accuses
the Forest Service of intransigence. ``They are sullenly refusing
to abide by the order of the court,'' he said.
   In selection management, only certain trees are removed at a
time so a perpetual forest is maintained, Fritz said, creating the
best habitat for the bird while also reducing the chances of insect
infestations. Additional jobs would be created because more
foresters are needed to keep track of what trees can be harvested,
he said.
   That argument fails to sway Chapman.
   ``The real argument is not over the woodpecker, but is basically
environmentalists disagreeing with clear-cutting. We're talking
about 500 woodpeckers. They're ugly, they don't have a particularly
melodious song, and they perform no useful service to either nature
or man,'' he said.
   Adds a spokesman for Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas: ``Clearly, one
side is winning, and it seems to be the woodpecker.''
   Gramm, Chapman and other opponents of the judge's order also say
it will cost local counties money. A dozen counties in Texas
receive a fourth of the gross sales from timber harvested in
federal forests, with a total of $3.7 million last year going into
local school districts and county road and bridge funds, according
to Gramm's office.
   But Fritz, an attorney with the environmental group, said claims
that revenues will drop are smoke screens.
   ``The misrepresentations have gone wild,'' he said. ``Selection
management is more cost-effective and produces just as much if not
more timber and leaves the forest ever-better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Boeing727 730   09-01 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing 727, 730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workhorse Boeing 727s Given High Marks for Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing 727 is the backbone of many
airlines in the United States and abroad, and draws little but
accolades from aviation experts despite the crash of one of the
airliners at Dallas-Forth Worth International Airport.
   ``There is no more reliable plane in the world,'' says Gary
Reich, aerospace analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton, the New York
investment firm. ``It has flown through storms and turbulence, and
it's performed beautifully and reliably.''
   ``They've been a highly reliable aircraft,'' says Roger Fleming,
technical chief for the Air Transport Association, the trade group
for the airline industry.
   The Boeing Co. manufactured 1,831 of the jets between 1962 and
1984, of which 1,770 are still in use worldwide, Boeing spokesman
Jack Gamble said Wednesday at company headquarters in Renton, Wash.
   Boeing estimates that 727s have flown 27.6 billion miles and
carried 3.1 billion passengers.
   It is the most commonly used plane in the U.S. commercial fleet.
According to airline consultant George James, of 3,476 passenger
and cargo aircraft used by American carriers, 1,148 are 727s. The
second most commonly used craft is the Boeing 737, with 634 in use.
   The Delta Air Lines 727-200 that crashed Wednesday at
Dallas-Fort Worth Airport had made 38,629 takeoffs and landings,
Boeing spokesman David Jimenez said. Gamble said the plane's 44,000
hours of flight time were average for its age. It was built in 1973.
   Gamble said that since the first 727 went into service in 1964,
53 have been lost after accidents. That includes Wednesday's crash,
and four other 727s that have been destroyed in attacks by
terrorists or shot down.
   The aircraft's early years, however, revealed some problems that
had to be dealt with.
   Reich said that in the early years of the 727 _ when the
nation's airline fleets were just entering the jet age _ several of
the planes crashed because pilots were unaccustomed to the rapidity
with which the aircraft descended during landings.
   Pilots had to be retrained to cope with the so-called high sink
rate.
   In the course of those accidents, another problem came to light,
Reich said. In the early models, lines brought fuel along the top
of the fuselage from the wings to the three engines at the rear,
which meant that in accidents, coach passenges would be doused with
burning fuel. Within a few years, the lines were repositioned to
the bottom portion of the fuselage.
   ``They had some difficulties in the early years, but those go
back to the mid- to late '60s,'' said Fleming of the Air Transport
Association.
   Over the years, the Federal Aviation Administration has issued
122 ``air worthiness directives'' ordering the owners of 727s to
make specific adjustments to the planes, said FAA spokesman Mitch
Barker in Seattle. He said that represents ``a normal number for an
aircraft that old.''
   Of those, however, only 12 applied to the model 200, the longer,
modernized version of the plane that Boeing began delivering to its
customers in December 1967. In all, 1,260 of the 727s manufactured
were model 200s, including the jet that crashed Wednesday. The
earlier versions were model 100s.
   One recurring problem was with the aircraft's landing gear,
which Barker said were complex and had been ``kind of a headache.''
He said he did not have details on what the problem was.
   Regarding the plane that crashed Wednesday, FAA records show a
wing flap control mechanism was replaced in July 1987 after an
aileron flap jammed on the right wing; and inspectors in August
1983 found two small cracks in the fuselage skin, measuring
one-half inch and three-quarters inch.
   FAA spokeswoman Bobbie Mardis described the problems as very
minor.
   Gamble said the first crash involving a 727 occurred in August
1965, when a United Airlines 727 plummeted into Lake Michigan. The
next involving a 727 was an American Airlines flight that crashed
in Cincinnati in November 1965, followed three days later by
another United accident at Salt Lake City. The Cincinnati and Salt
Lake City incidents were caused by the pilots' unfamiliarity with
aircraft's rapid rate of descent, he said.
   Among the craft's more recent accidents, a Pan American 727
crashed after takeoff in Kenner, La., on July 9, 1982, and 153
people were killed.
   The 727 is being phased out in favor of more economical planes
that use just two engines and require only two pilots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
