<DOCNO> AP880901-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bromine-Ozone     09-01 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bromine-Ozone,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Extinguisher Chemical Causing Concern for Protective Ozone
Layer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New measurements have confirmed rapid growth
in the atmosphere of man-made bromine compounds from fire
extinguishers that scientists believe help destroy the earth's
protective ozone layer.
   Bromine has received much less attention than the
chlorofluorocarbon or CFC compounds in discussions of how to save
the stratospheric chemical layer that blocks the sun's
cancer-causing ultraviolet rays.
   But bromine was covered by last year's treaty calling for a
halving of CFC production by 1998. Production of the fire-fighting
bromine compounds, called Halons, is to be frozen at 1986 levels in
1992.
   A chemical cousin of chlorine, bromine by itself can destroy
little ozone. But many chemists believe it amplifies the
ozone-destroying ability of chlorine liberated from both Halons and
the CFC compounds used as refrigeration fluids, solvents, foam
blowing agents and, outside the United States, as aerosol
propellants.
   Other compounds, some arising naturally from the ocean, are
important sources of atmospheric bromine. There is no consensus on
the importance of each source, and industry appears divided on the
importance of the new findings.
   The fire-fighting compounds are valuable because they snuff out
flames while leaving no residue that would disable valuable
equipment like computers. Only about 5 percent of emissions is
believed to come from actual fire-fighting, with most emissions
coming from equipment testing.
   Professional groups already have revised codes to eliminate
requirements that Halons be used to test equipment.
   The latest Halon measurements were made by a team of West German
and Indian scientists based at Germany's Max Planck Institute.
   In the Aug. 18 issue of Nature, the British scientific weekly,
the team reported atmospheric concentrations of the two main Halons
seem to be growing at 12 percent per year and 5 percent per year.
   The faster-growing compound is Halon 12, used in portable
extinguishers, whose concentration was measured in balloon flights
over France and India at 1.9 parts per trillion at 33,000 and
37,000 feet. The slower growth is for Halon 13, used in
room-flooding installations, whose concentration was about 1.3
parts per trillion.
   The major CFCs are present at a few hundred parts per trillion,
but the two bromine compounds are far more powerful _ three and 11
times as destructive of ozone than the most important CFC compound.
   The Halon 12 concentrations, when compared with measurements
made in 1982, 1983 and 1984, yield growth rates of 12 percent to 20
percent per year. The researchers said 12 percent ``seems to be the
more realistic.'' There have been no previous growth rates reported
for Halon 13.
   ``The measurements are in the range we have been considering in
our models,'' said Ross Salawitch, a postdoctoral researcher in the
Harvard University group headed by Michael McElroy studying bromine
reactions in the atmosphere.
   The McElroy group believes bromine is responsible for about 20
percent of the annual loss of ozone over Antarctica that produces
the well-known September ``hole'' which last year saw ozone
concentrations fall to 50 percent of normal.
   Some studies also show a small ozone loss over the Arctic.
   ``If there is any chemically driven ozone loss over the Arctic,
it is more likely to be driven by the chlorine-bromine reactions,''
Salawitch said.
   Three companies make Halon compounds in the United States: Du
Pont Co., ICI Americas and Great Lakes Chemical Corp.
   At Great Lakes in West Lafayette, Ind., Dave Bouchard, a
chemical engineer who is director of investor relations, said the
company was ``not confident at all'' that bromine enhances the
ability of chlorine to destroy ozone, and was sponsoring and
conducting research to try to prove or disprove it.
   At Du Pont, spokeswoman Cathy Forte said the Nature article was
``generally consistent with our understanding of the effects of
bromine in the atmosphere,'' and would not affect the company's
plans to end production of all its ozone-depleting products before
the turn of the century, including Halon compounds.
   The company has ended equipment testing with Halons, she said.
   Dan Dudek, an atmospheric scientist with the Environmental
Defense Fund, said he believed Halon production should be reduced
just like CFC production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DetroitNewspapers     09-01 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit Newspapers Argue for End to Newspaper War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit Free Press and The Detroit News
are urging a federal judge to ignore ``Alice in Wonderland''
arguments and lift a court order blocking partial merger of the two
money-losing newspapers.
   A brief filed by the Free Press on Wednesday said opponents of
the joint operating agreement had mischaracterized the record in a
last-ditch attempt to forestall the partial merger.
   The brief was supported by the News and two unions, the
Newspaper Guild and Graphic Communications International Union.
   The newspapers rank in circulation among the 10 largest in the
nation.
   On Aug. 8, then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved the
combination of the newspapers' business and production operations.
The Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., and the News, owned by
Gannett Co. Inc., would retain separate news and editorial
departments.
   Meese approved the exemption to federal antitrust laws under the
Newspaper Preservation Act, which allows such exemptions when one
of the competing newspapers is in danger of failing.
   In winning a court-ordered delay in the merger, opponents argued
that the evidence showed the Free Press, far from failing, was a
healthy newspaper with some competitive advantages over the News.
   Attorneys for the Free Press, however, said, ``This `Alice in
Wonderland' assertion ignores over $80 million in operating losses
by the Free Press and $176 million in subsidies by its parent,
Knight-Ridder.''
   ``In the final analysis, plaintiffs' argument is that the owners
of the Free Press poured $176 million into the paper from 1977
through 1986 in an effort to generate artificial losses in the hope
that a JOA might some day be successfully negotiated,'' the brief
said. ``This proposition on its face is preposterous and
self-defeating.''
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green, at the request of a group
of Detroit advertisers and newspaper readers, issued an emergency
order Aug. 17 delaying the partial merger for a month. The order
came the day before the agreement was due to go into effect.
   The Free Press urged the court to deny the opponents' request
that the partial merger be blocked permanently and to force them to
pay court costs.
   The brief argued that the attorney general was correct in
overruling an administrative law judge's recommendation the
agreement be denied.
   ``The attorney general is the federal officer charged by
Congress with responsibility for applying and construing the
Newspaper Preservation Act,'' the brief said. ``It is the findings
and legal conclusions of the attorney general, not the
recommendations of the (administrative law judge) or the antitrust
division, to which the courts, therefore, defer.''
   The long and fierce circulation battle between the Free Press
and the News has kept advertising rates and newsstand prices lower
than in many large cities. The News has a newsstand price on
weekdays and Saturdays of 15 cents a copy in the Detroit area; the
Free Press sells for 20 cents.
   After the first five years of the 100-year agreement, the
newspapers would share profits or losses equally.
   The joint operating agreement would cause the loss of about 500
jobs, the newspapers have said. Should the agreement be blocked,
Knight-Ridder has said, the Free Press will be closed, with a loss
of 1,500 jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
