<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-Library     09-01 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Library,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opponents of Planned Reagan Library Cite Air Pollution, Landscape
Damage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Questions about possible traffic jams,
air pollution and damage to sensitive plants are delaying approval
of plans for a library to house President Reagan's White House
papers.
   The Ventura County Environmental Report Review Commission
recessed a hearing on the project Wednesday without taking action
after concerns were raised by the California Department of Fish and
Game, the Sierra Club, the city of Thousand Oaks and others.
   The commission will meet again next week and could approve
construction of the library or order preparation of an
environmental impact report. That could take a year or more.
   The Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation, which has been
raising money for the library, hopes to break ground this fall and
complete construction in 1991.
   The facility, like the eight existing presidential libraries,
would be operated by the National Archives. In addition to housing
the Reagan papers for scholarly study, it would contain museum
exhibits about the president and his administration.
   Chuck Thomas, who represents Ventura County's air pollution
control agency on the seven-member technical commission, requested
the week's delay in order to get more information.
   If he had to vote on it without delay, he said, ``I think I
would have to come down against it.'' Thomas said the Air Pollution
Control District had found that the project would violate county
air quality standards because of the amount of automobile traffic
it would generate.
   Carroll McDonald, chairman of the Reagan Presidential Library
Committee of the Ventura-based organization Environmental
Coalition, told county officials that more than 425,000 people
annually are expected to visit the library, located northwest of
Los Angeles.
   ``Given the popularity of President Reagan, and the controversy
concerning portions of his presidency, it would seem reasonable to
assume that this will be a popular attraction for tourists as well
as a research library for historians,'' added Russ Baggerly,
representing a group called Citizen Interest in Ventura County.
   The library site, in a hilly area near the communities of
Thousand Oaks, Simi Valley and Moorpark, is served by a dusty road
used by jeeps and horses. To reach this road, however, traffic
would travel over a public road serving the three communities.
   Philip E. Gatch, director of planning and community development
for Thousand Oaks, said a portion of this road, approaching the
adjoining city limits of Thousand Oaks and Simi Valley, ``remains a
two-lane roadway operating at a level of service beyond its current
capacity.''
   However, Frank W. Brutt, the planning and community development
director for Simi Valley, said the Simi Valley staff ``can make the
findings that the additional traffic that would be generated by the
library project would not have a significant impact on nearby
intersections under projected cumulative traffic conditions.''
   Fred Worthley, regional manager of the California Fish and Game
Department, said an undetermined number of three ``sensitive
plants'' would be uprooted or damaged by construction. In a letter
to county officials May 12, Worthley asked that the project be
redesigned to avoid the areas where the plants grow after a
detailed survey was made ``at the appropriate time of year when
these plants can be readily identified.''
   Cynthia Leake, conservation chairman of the Sierra Club chapter
in nearby Camarillo, asked that an environmental impact study be
made of both the effects on plant life and air quality.
   ``The size of the structure, the hours of operation, the
expected number of visitors per day all indicate serious
degradation of the air quality in the area,'' she said.
   The 153,000 square-foot library would operate from 9 a.m. to
4:45 p.m., seven days a week, and foundation officials say it is
expected to receive an average of 1,238 visitors per day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
