<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrownPresident     09-01 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown President,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Public Library Head Gregorian Named Brown President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brown University on Wednesday named
Vartan Gregorian, head of the New York Public Library, to be the
16th president of the Ivy League college, the university chancellor
said.
   ``I come not to preside but to build,'' Gregorian said. ``The
institution is full of potential, full of greatness. Some of it has
been acheived, some of it still has to be achieved.''
   When asked at a news conference where he would like to see the
7,000-student university in five or 10 years, Gregorian replied,
``forward.''
   Gregorian's presidency was announced by Chancellor A.O. Way,
following a meeting of the Brown Corp., the university's governing
body.
   ``Vartan Gregorian comes to the presidency with superb
credentials as scholar and administrator,'' said Way, who was also
chairman of the selection committee. ``He has an uncommon degree of
energy and good humor, ingredients vital to all successful
presidencies.''
   Gregorian, 54, who was born to Armenian parents in Iran, went to
the New York library in 1981 from the University of Pennsylvania,
where he was provost. He used various fund-raising devices,
including society parties, to raise nearly $500 million during his
tenure.
   Gregorian admitted his fundraising ability did not hurt his
candidacy for the Brown position, but said his ``primary obligation
will be to the academic welfare of the institution _ if that
requires organization of fundraising'' so be it.
   Way's announcement concluded a nearly yearlong search, which
involved interviews with more than 200 candidates. Gregorian
replaces Howard R. Swearer, 56, who announced his resignation for
personal reasons last October after 11 years as Brown's president.
</TEXT>
