<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Angola     09-01 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Angola,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Troop Withdrawal Seen Aiding Peace Prospects in
Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pullout of South African troops from
Angola should increase the prospects for peace talks in the region,
U.S. officials say.
   ``This is a significant milestone in the process of achieving a
peaceful solution to the conflict in southwestern Africa,'' State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Wednesday.
   U.S.-mediated negotiations on further steps in the peace process
between South Africa, Angola and Cuba will resume next week in the
Congo capital of Brazzaville, Mrs. Oakley said.
   The Washington Post, meanwhile, reported today that Cuba held
secret talks last weekend with the U.S.-backed UNITA rebels in
Angola.
   U.S. officials whom the Post did not identify said they did not
know whether the talks were an indication that Cuban President
Fidel Castro was seeking a reconciliation agreement between the
Cuban-backed Angolan government and UNITA.
   It was not immediately known whether Angolan officials were
aware of the talks, which the Post said took place in the Ivory
Coast capital of Abidjan between UNITA and a Cuban delegation
headed by Cuba's ambassador to the United Nations, Oscar Oramas.
   The U.S.-mediated talks between South Africa, Angola and Cuba,
which were suspended last week for consultations by the parties
with their governments, are aimed partly at achieving agreement on
a timetable for the pullout of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops
from Angola.
   The last contingent of South African soldiers, who supported
Angola's anti-Marxist guerrillas, crossed into South-West Africa on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
