<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland-Walesa     09-01 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Walesa,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader, Once Discredited By Government, Now Invited To
Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa walked with
a bounce in his step as he left his house for his first meeting
with senior officials of the communist government in more than six
years.
   Not only did his long-sought goal for talks with the government
come true Wednesday, but it came on the anniversary of his greatest
triumph _ the signing of the 1980 accords that legalized the Soviet
bloc's first independent union federation.
   For the 44-year-old shipyard electrician who won the Nobel Peace
Prize in 1983, it was a testament to his unswerving determination
not to give up on his vision of workers' solidarity.
   Walesa's vision was born in the December 1970 food price riots
in which dozens of workers were killed by security forces along the
Baltic coast.
   He was one of the workers who met later with the new Communist
Party first secretary, Edward Gierek. Gierek calmed the protest
with promises to improve national leadership and inspired workers
to chant: ``We will help! We will help!''
   But workers rose again in 1976 in a revolt brutally put down by
authorities, and Walesa and a handful of associates began
organizing illegal free trade unions along the coast.
   When new price increases raised tensions in 1980, it was Walesa
who returned to lead the fight. In two weeks that saw strikes
spread nationwide, he wrested from the government 22 concessions on
social and trade union issues, the most important guaranteeing the
right to independent self-governing trade unions.
   The accords were signed in the shipyard by Walesa and
then-Deputy Prime Minister Mieczyslaw Jagielski on Aug. 31, 1980,
and Solidarity was born.
   The triumph gave way to a euphoric but chaotic period that
lasted 15{ months before Polish authorities accused the union of
leading the country to anarchy, imposed martial law and locked up
Walesa and thousands of his followers on Dec. 13, 1981.
   Walesa was interned in a series of luxurious government homes
until Nov. 13, 1982. While locked up, he was approached by various
high officials in a bid to persuade him to endorse the government's
emergency actions. He refused.
   Solidarity was suspended and outlawed in October 1982. After
Walesa's release from internment, authorities did all in their
power to make him a non-person.
   His photo and name rarely appeared in newspapers and never in a
positive light. He was called a tool of foreign powers and the
``former head of a former union.'' One rather crude media campaign
accused him of embezzling union funds.
   But Walesa continued leading the shellshocked remnants of the
Solidarity movement.
   After martial law was lifted in July 1983 and most political
prisoners were released in late 1986, Solidarity began to function
more and more openly.
   Walesa consolidated its leadership last year into a national
executive commission with representatives from every region and
with himself as chairman.
   When strikes broke out on April 25, Walesa joined a walkout in
the shipyard despite his sense that the country wasn't ready. He
showed he still had the common touch, comforting and inspiring
young strikers half his age who sometimes lined up for his
autograph.
   The shipyard strike ended inconclusively May 10, but Walesa
vowed that next time it would be better prepared. The latest round
of strikes, which began Aug. 16, showed a high degree of
organization. Advisers fanned out around the country and a national
information network was set up.
   The strikes, at last, also resulted in an invitation from the
government to talk to Walesa, who just moved into a new house with
his wife, Danuta, and eight children.
   Lt. Colonel Wieslaw Gornicki, an aide to Polish leader Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski, said Walesa was invited as an ``eminent
personality,'' not as ``the chairman of a non-existent union.''
   Still, it was significant that the government chose Walesa to
try to open a dialogue that could help lead the country out of
economic despondency.
   Piotr Konopka, a Walesa aide and adviser in Gdansk, savored the
moment while Walesa talked with Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak
and alternate Politburo member Stanislaw Ciosek.
   ``This union managed to survive, managed not to lose its
authority, managed to keep its leader, who today begins again to be
a partner for talks, a very necessary partner as it turned out,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
