<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LengthyBarricade     09-01 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lengthy Barricade,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Batter Down Door During Three-Day Standoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used a battering ram late Wednesday to
crash into a home where a 65-year-old woman was believed barricaded
during a three-day standoff in which the police chief's brother was
wounded.
   Officers battered the house around 10:30 p.m, said Officer Ken
Axelrad. However, police did not immediately apprehend the woman,
he said.
   Capt. Stephen Gates, 51, brother of Police Chief Daryl Gates,
was in good condition at Daniel Freeman Hospital with a graze wound
to the head, said Detective Robert Iannessa.
   The unidentified woman allegedly fired through her window at
Gates as he attempted to talk her into coming out of the house
Wednesday, Iannessa said. A police officer was also fired on around
9:45 p.m. but was not hit, the detective said.
   Negotiators tried to reach the woman by telephone, but Iannessa
said, ``She's not talking to anybody.''
   The tank-like battering ram usually is reserved for cracking
fortified ``rock houses'' used in drug sales.
   The standoff began at 1 p.m. Monday when the woman threatened
her daughter with a gun, authorities said. The woman was believed
to be alone in the house where there were several weapons, her
husband told police.
