<1ST_LINE>r i rnbx     09-01 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>rnbx</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Today (BC)</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican Newspaper Editors Association on
Wednesday criticized a new law in Tamaulipas state that calls for
jury trials in cases involving ``crimes committed by the media
against the public order and security of the state.''
   The Federal Code already lists these crimes, but the new state
law subjects defendants to jury trial when committed by ``the
press.''
   The Association voiced its opposition to the law on the last day
an annual convention being held in Mexico City with the National
Association of Hispanic Publications of the United States.
   The Mexican association boasts 72 newspaper affiliates.
   The law calls for potential jurors to be selected by municipal
mayors to hear accusations against the media.
   Association president Jose Martinez Bastida said the law
``violates constitutional guarantees and constitutes an attempt
against freedom of expression and the right to information.''
   Luis Villareal Marroquin, director of the newspaper Diario in
Nuevo Laredo, received the association's Jose Vansconcelos award
for his efforts to stop enactment of the state law.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the leader of a
democratic reform movement, on Wednesday urged the ruling party to
negotiate publicly with the opposition over disputed returns from
1,000 polling places.
   He called on the ruling party's presidential candidate, Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, to personally undertake negotiations that would
``open wider spaces'' for democracy in Mexico.
   According to official returns, Salinas beat Cardenas in the July
6 general election with 50.36 percent of the vote.
   Cardenas and his leftist coalition said the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, cheated to maintain the power it has
held since 1929. The rightist opposition has leveled the same
charge.
   Before a crowd of about 10,000 gathered in a steady drizzle at
the Revolution Monument, Cardenas rejected an offer from the ruling
party Sunday for a dialogue with the opposition about future
political reform. The question of fraud must first be cleared up,
he insisted.
   ``To negotiate in any other terms would mean, for us, to break
our promise to the people,'' he said.
   Cardenas said his leftist coalition was cheated out of nine
Senate seats and at least 40 seats in the 500-person Chamber of
Deputies. Official, but disputed returns, give Cardenas' coalition
four Senate seats, the first the PRI has ever relinquished, and 139
in the chamber.
   On Tuesday, President Miguel de la Madrid warned the opposition
that the PRI will not give up power.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fernando Ortiz Arana was elected leader of
the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party delegation in the
Chamber of Deputies, which inaugurates its 54th session Thursday.
   Ortiz Arana is a deputy for the party known as PRI from the
Federal District of Mexico City. The PRI has 260 seats in the new
assembly, with 240 seats divided among the opposition parties.
   ``We ae going to the assembly ... united in the party, with our
triumphant candidate to the presidency of the republic, Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, to wage the dignified political fight the
citizens who elected us expect,'' Ortiz Arana said after his
election at party headquarters.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vote watchdog group on Wednesday reiterated
its charges the July 6 presidential election and the just-concluded
work of the Electoral College to constitute the Chamber of Deputies
were tainted by fraud.
   The Democratic Assembly for Effective Suffrage said that under
such conditions, the Chamber's work to certify the election of
Carlos Salinas de Gortari as president will be marred as well.
   ``Neither the Federal Election Commission nor the Electoral
Colleges of the Chamber of Deputies and the Senate fulfilled their
mission: to clean the electoral process,'' an Assembly statement
said.
   ``If the Chamber applies to the presidential qualification the
same arbitrary and injust procedures it used to constitute itself,
it will transmit its own illegitimacy to the head of the
executive,'' it said.
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari, presidential candidate of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, received 50.36 percent of the
vote according to official results. The Chamber of Deputies must
approve his election before inauguration day, Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department has authorized the
completion of all debt-for-equity swaps suspended in October 1987,
but does not plan to renew the swap program.
   Between $500 million and $600 million in authorized swap
transactions were frozen when the government called off the program
last year, according to the government newspaper El Nacional.
   The Commerce Department said the swaps were inflationary in
suspending the program. It had approved more than $2 billion worth
of swaps in the two years that the program was in effect.
   This week the department said all outstanding swaps would be
completed before President Miguel de la Madrid leaves office Nov.
30.
   Under the program, foreign investors cash in Mexican foreign
debt paper with the government, which issues peso equity for
investment purposes in Mexico.
   eoa-ch-ja
