<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaCrash-Records     09-01 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash-Records,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Problems in Plane's History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Delta Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a Delta jetliner that crashed
at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport had clean flying
records, and the plane had only minor problems recently, according
to Federal Aviation Administration records.
   A pump-like device known as a power controller actuator on a
wing flap had to be replaced in July 1987 after a flap on the Delta
Air Lines Boeing 727's right wing jammed, the documents filed in
the last five years said.
   The actuator, which is activated as part of the process of
operating the flaps during takeoffs and landings, was removed and
returned to the manufacturer, and a new one was installed,
according to the records at the agency's headquarters here.
   Inspectors in August 1983 found two small cracks in the fuselage
skin, the FAA records said. The first crack measured one-half inch
in length at the corner of the pilot's window. The other, found in
an inspection the same month, was three-quarters of an inch long at
the upper corner of the captain's windshield, the report said.
   Bobbie Mardis, a spokeswoman for the FAA, described the problems
as very minor.
   A report showed that on Nov. 13, 1986, at Raleigh, N.C., the
aircraft didn't stay at the altitude assigned by air traffic
controllers, Ms. Mardis said.
   The aircraft was built by Boeing in 1973 and delivered new to
Delta, the FAA said.
   None of the crew of Wednesday's flight _ pilot Larry Davis,
co-pilot Carey Wilson Kirkland Jr. and flight engineer Stephen Judd
_ had a previous record of accident, incident or violation, Ms.
Mardis said.
   The three were among the nearly 100 survivors of Wednesday's
crash, which occurred during take off. The cause of the crash was
not determined, federal investigators said. Davis, 48, has been a
Delta pilot since 1965 and a Boeing 727 captain for the last nine
years; Kirkland, 37, was hired by Delta in 1979; and Judd has been
with Delta since November, said airline spokesman Henry Conley in
Dallas.
   The jetliner was powered by JT8D engines manufactured by
Connecticut-based Pratt & Whitney, which sent two investigators to
the scene.
   The engines are a mainstay of the airline industry, according to
David M. Long, a Pratt & Whitney spokesman. Long said the company
routinely sends investigators to crashes in which aircraft are
powered by Pratt & Whitney engines.
   Long said it was ``way to early'' to speculate on the cause of
the crash.
   The JT8D received its initial certification from the FAA in 1967
and about 10,000 are now in use. It provides a thrust at takeoff of
14,000 to 18,000 pounds, according to Pratt & Whitney documents.
   Problems with JT8D engines were cited as factors in 1985 airline
crashes in London and Milwaukee.
</TEXT>
