<2ND_LINE>PM-Canal Drownings,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Drowns in Canal While Trying to Rescue Sister, Who Also Died</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl drowned in a golf course
water hazard along with her 11-year-old brother, who may have been
trying to save her despite being unable to swim, officials said.
   Bystanders and medical workers Tuesday evening were unable to
revive Rachel and Juan Silvia after they were pulled out of a canal
that forms a water hazard at the Ascarate Municipal Golf Course.
   The children were pronounced dead at Thomason Hospital two hours
after golfers plucked them from the 5-foot-deep canal, El Paso
County sheriff's deputies said.
   The children and a 7-year-old sister probably were playing in
the canal when Rachel fell in, said sheriff's Sgt. Marvin Ryals.
   ``The brother may have tried to save the girl,'' Ryals said.
   Michael Hutcherson of Pampa was playing golf when he noticed
Juan splashing around in the water. He asked the 7-year-old girl
whether her brother was in trouble, and she said she thought so.
   ``I knew he was in trouble then, and I hit the water,''
Hutcherson said.
   He pulled Juan out and tried to revive him while a fellow golfer
ran for help. The 7-year-old went for the children's mother,
Patricia Silva. When they came back, someone asked the little girl
where Rachel was.
   ``She said the other girl was the same place her brother had
been,'' Hutcherson said. ``I knew right then the boy I was trying
to save had been trying to save his sister.''
   An unidentified bystander jumped in, found the girl and pulled
her out.
   ``We got a lot of help from bystanders,'' said Kevin Hobin, an
Emergency Medical Services supervisor. ``Everyone there was really
pulling for those two.''
   Ms. Silva had taken the children to the park Tuesday afternoon,
Ryals said.
   ``They apparently were left unattended,'' Ryals said. ``They
didn't know how to swim at all.''
</TEXT>
