<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StreetRunway     09-01 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Street Runway,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Thinks Street Is Convenient Runway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When John Sawyer landed his
single-engine airplane on a street here recently to conduct some
business, he also landed in trouble.
   City officials are seeking a court injunction to make sure he
doesn't use streets for runways again.
   Sawyer landed his airplane on a street Aug. 24 in this city of
15,000 people 20 miles northwest of Denver to conduct business at
the nearby Colorado Tech Center.
   City Administrator Dave Stahl happened to glance out his
second-floor office window to see the small plane preparing to land.
   Since there was no airport in that direction, Stahl and police
officers investigated, ending up with a chat with Sawyer, who
couldn't understand what the fuss was about.
   Sawyer, a telecommunications consultant, said he routinely uses
his plane to make business calls in the area, and has flown in to
the Tech Center four times during the past four months to pick up
equipment or attend meetings.
   He said he doesn't leave the plane in the street. He parks it in
the company parking lot.
   ``I didn't even come within 500 feet of a building,'' Sawyer
said.
   ``That's like saying there's no buildings on U.S. 36, so you
could land there,'' Stahl said. ``When you land a plane on a public
street, you don't know ... if a pedestrian, car, bicyclist or
motorcyclist are in the area.''
   But Sawyer said, ``It's a city street in name only. There's not
even any light poles around. It's vacant land. There's zilch
traffic out there.
   ``It looks far more like a landing strip than a road.''
   Sawyer challenged city officials to cite a law forbidding planes
from landing on city streets. The city responded by pointing to its
zoning laws and seeking an injunction in Boulder District Court to
ban Sawyer from making runways out of Louisville streets.
   Mitch Baker, public affairs officer for the Federal Aviation
Administration in Seattle, said there is no federal law prohibiting
a plane from landing on a public street.
   But he said FAA regulations prohibit landings that endanger
people on the ground.
   ``I intend to fight it,'' Sawyer said of the city's court
action. ``I'm not doing this for fun. It's for convenience.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
