<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-01 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Plunge, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange on
Thursday, while the U.S. dollar rose sharply against the yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the Tokyo stock
market's main barometer, closed at 26,934.26 points, down 431.69
points, or 1.58 percent.
   In foreign exchange trading, the dollar, which opened at 136.20
yen, 1.23 yen higher than Wednesday's close, finished at 136.70
yen, up 1.73 yen.
   The dollar's rise was due to a sell-off of the yen by investors,
according to foreign exchange analysts. Sumio Fukushima of Sumitomo
Bank in Tokyo said one of the factors cited was the Bank of Japan's
announcement Wednesday that it would not raise interest rates.
   Toshiaki Kakimoto, chief economist at Sumitomo Bank, said
investors who had been selling West German marks now were targeting
the yen.
   ``After interest rates rose in Europe last week, the rate in
Japan has become the lowest and investors started selling the yen
to buy more dollars,'' he said.
   But Kakimoto speculated the fluctuating exchange rate was
temporary.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa dismissed concern over the
yen's downswing. ``Currency rates change every day,'' said Miyazawa.
   On the stock exchange, share prices were lower across the board,
according to an analyst with Nomura Securities in Tokyo.
   ``Almost nothing has been traded this morning, because investors
were shocked by the yen's downfall,'' he said.
   ``I almost jumped up when I found out the Bank of Japan had
announced they would not raise interest rates, because investors
certainly would lose interest in the yen,'' the analyst said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
