<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0524EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     09-01 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relief For Fire-Ravaged Northwest Predicted in October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Weather Service predicts the
Northwestern section of the country won't get any relief from the
unusually hot, dry weather that has contributed to fires ravaging
the area until well after Labor Day.
   Government broadcasters said Wednesday above-normal temperatures
will persist over much of the West during the next five days
through the Labor Day weekend, and a trend toward rain and cooler
temperatures won't begins until sometime in October.
   ``Only the longer outlook through November brings cool, wet
conditions to the Northwest,'' the service said. It should be
warmer in the Southwest and California and most areas of the East,
with rain extending up the Mississippi and Ohio valleys to the
Great Lakes and mid-Atlantic regions.
   The service added that streamflows are expected to remain below
average across much of the country, and water reserves at major
reservoirs remain average to below average for this time of year
across much of the country.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Library of Congress Gets Gift of Music</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Library of Congress has received what it
called the greatest composite gift in the history of its music
division.
   The library announced Wednesday that Hans Moldenhauer, a
Spokane, Wash., pianist, teacher and musicologist who died last
October, bequeathed to it several thousand documents written by
composers, musicians and literary figures dating to the 12th
century, including hand-written musical scores by Beethoven, Chopin
and Mendelssohn.
   The bequest, received in July, represents the overwhelming bulk
of the Moldenhauer collection, which the library described as ``one
of the greatest archives of musical primary source materials ever
assembled.''
   The oldest of the documents apparently is 18 lines of Latin text
on vellum, with musical notations, from a 12th century German
prayer book.
   Among the many composers represented in the collection is a copy
in Ludwig van Beethoven's handwriting of music from Mozart's opera,
``Don Giovanni,'' probably written as studies for portions of
Beethoven's only opera, ``Fidelio.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Postal Service, Union Sign Pact To Reduce Grievances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service has for the first time
ever signed an agreement concerning the labor-management climate
with a union representing its employees.
   The service and the National Association of Letter Carriers on
Wednesday signed a non-binding ``joint commitment'' to try to
reduce grievance appeals, arbitrations and employment
discrimination complaints against the service ually.
   According to Postal Service records, 19,543 grievances were
appealed beyond the local level by members of the Letter Carriers
union in the 12 months ending Aug. 1, and 10,766 individual
disputes were taken to arbitration.
   In addition, members of the union filed 2,128 complaints of age,
sex or race discrimination against the Postal Service with the
federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
   Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank, the first head of the
service to address a postal union convention, said last month in
Portland, Ore. ``These processes ... break down the old `them' and
`us' attitudes and promote a positive spirit of cooperation.''
</TEXT>
