<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaCrash-Numbers     09-01 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash-Numbers,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Several Factors Led To Fluctuating Casualty Counts In Delta Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Delta Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The confusing scene at the Dallas-Fort Worth
airport and Delta Air Lines' policy of not counting infants riding
its flights free contributed to erroneous reports of how many
people died aboard Flight 1141, airline officials said.
   At least one infant was among the 13 passengers known to have
died when the Boeing 727 crashed and caught fire seconds after
takeoff from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport on Wednesday.
   At least 94 passengers and crew escaped, although some
discrepancies remained early today between lists provided by
hospitals and Delta.
   The number of casualties fluctuated throughout the day
Wednesday, from seven to 15, down to nine, up to 11 and then to 13.
   Bill Berry, a Delta spokesman in Atlanta, said one reason for
the discrepancies was that officials weren't sure how many children
under age 2 were aboard.
   ``An infant does not buy a ticket, and if it does not buy a
ticket, so many times you are going to have a discrepancy in your
manifest count,'' Berry said.
   He said passengers don't normally notify ticket agents that they
plan to take an infant on board.
   At least three infants were aboard the jet, he said. One was
among the dead _ but the fates of the others weren't known.
   Part of the problem, Berry said, was that emergency personnel on
the scene requested 15 body bags initially _ leading Delta
officials to give out an erroneous casualty figure. Later some
victims died at hospitals.
   Victims were taken to eight hospitals.
   ``As you well know, in these types of situations, the numbers
often fluctuate until you can get various hospitals contacted,''
Berry said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-01 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Plunge, Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged as the U.S. dollar rose
sharply in Tokyo trading today.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues fell 431.69
points, or 1.58 percent to close at 26,934.26, the biggest one-day
decline since Aug. 10, when the market shed 615.49 points.
   The main index, which had its third-biggest one-day plunge this
year, was down 664 points at midmorning. The Nikkei finished below
the 27,000-point level for the first time since May 28, when it
closed at 26,962.50, losing 327.99 points.
   The U.S. dollar, which opened at 136.20 yen with a 1.23 yen jump
from Wednesday's close of 134.97 yen, was firmer toward the end of
the trading, to close at 136.70, up 1.73 yen. The currency ranged
between 136.05 yen and 136.80 yen, with spot volume estimated at
$7.98 billion.
   ``The dollar was getting stronger all day. Dollar-selling for
some investors' profit-taking could not outweigh the dollar-buying
drive in the market,'' said Hiroyuki Sekine of the Daiwa Bank in
Tokyo.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa earlier said, ``Currency rates
change every day,'' dismissing concern over the yen's downswing.
   Toshiaki Kakimoto, chief economist at Sumitomo Bank, said
investors who have been selling West German marks are now targeting
the Japanese yen.
   ``After interest rates rose in Europe last week, the rate in
Japan has become the lowest and investors started selling the yen
to buy more dollars,'' he said.
   But the spokesman for the Bank of Japan said Japan need not
raise interest rates just because other countries did.
   On the stock exchange, share prices were lower across the board
except a few issues bought in the afternoon session, said an
analyst with Nomura Securities in Tokyo. Among the losers were
steels, shipbuilding and chemical issues.
   Dealers said the downfall of the yen immediately following the
Bank of Japan's announcement Wednesday made investors stay away
from the stock trading.
</TEXT>
