<DOCNO> AP880901-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Honduras-Nicaragua     09-01 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Nicaragua,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Blames Rebel Exodus On Lack Of Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo blamed
the influx to his country of Nicaraguan rebels and their civilian
supporters on a lack of democracy under the Sandinista government.
   He said more than 24,0000 of the guerrillas, known as Contras,
have fled across the border into Honduran camps since April _ a
figure Honduran officials say includes 11,000 rebels and 13,000
civilians. An estimated 2,000 rebels remain inside Nicaragua.
   ``The lack of democracy by the Sandinistas is paid for by
Honduras, which is a victim of the Central American problem,''
Azcona Hoyo said Wednesday. ``It is necessary to strengthen the
struggle to democratize Nicaragua.''
   Azcona Hoyo said the leftist Sandinistas ``deliberately lifted
protection of their border to allow the Contras to move into
Honduras.''
   Other estimates say the number of Contras in Honduras who
receive food, medicine, clothing and other non-lethal U.S. aid
totals 14,000 _ including 9,000 rebels and 5,000 civilians. The
exodus began in April, after Nicaraguan government forces withdrew
from two northern border areas under a March 23 peace plan.
   The United States, which has supplied and trained the rebels
since 1981, cut off military aid to the Contras at the end of
February. Congress has refused to renew the funding, saying it
would violate a cease-fire the two sides have agreed to.
   However, Congress earmarked $17 million in non-lethal aid to the
rebels _ supplied on condition that it go to Honduras, not
Nicaragua. The supplies began arriving in April and are being
distributed by the Agency for International Development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0555EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaCrash-ReluctantRescuer     09-01 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash-Reluctant Rescuer,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good Samaritan Couldn't Turn Away From Second Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: note contents of 3rd graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Delta Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Weeks said he rushed to help at
the scene of the fiery crash of Delta Air Lines Flight 1141 because
he could not ignore another tragedy at Dallas-Forth Worth
International Airport.
   ``I just bit my lip and went,'' said Weeks, 45, who runs an
airport shuttle bus company and has long regretted not offering his
aid after the 1985 crash of Delta Flight 191, which killed 137
people and injured 25 others.
   ``When 191 occurred, I was driving trucks and had just seen a
terrible accident in which some girls were beheaded,'' he said.
``I'm tough and I've seen plenty of horrendous wrecks as a truck
driver. But I was near the airport when 191 crashed and I just
couldn't go.''
   It was a different story Wednesday when Weeks, who is married to
an American Airlines flight attendant, became one of the first to
arrive and offer assistance after the crash, which killed at least
13 people.
   At first, Weeks and an Irving policeman he was with assumed the
thick column of billowing black smoke was merely a ``controlled
burn,'' another of the frequent drills held at the airport to
prepare emergency workers for plane crashes.
   But Eusebio Padilla, who drives a bus for Weeks' airport shuttle
service, called in on the company radio to say he had just seen a
plane go down.
   Padilla, 31, said he was putting gas in his bus at a filling
station on the south side of the airport when the crash occurred.
   ``It got up to about 30 or 40 feet up in the air, then it veered
to one side, and went out of my sight,'' Padilla said. ``Two
seconds later, I hear a large explosion. I see smoke and flames,
probably 30 feet up in the air.''
   Weeks in turn called police to report that a plane had just
crashed on the southwest quadrant of the airport. Police already
had received a handful of similar reports.
   Weeks arrived at the crash site within 10 minutes, remembering
Flight 191 and figuring he would join a team in the grim task of
tramping through brush for remains. When the smoke cleared, he was
shocked at what he found.
   ``It wasn't a violent crash,'' he recalled. ``About a dozen
survivors were standing up and walking around. Nobody was terribly
distraught.''
   Weeks went from survivor to survivor, all waiting to be
transported to area hospitals, and asked if he could call anyone
for them. Five of them took advantage of his offer. He also offered
free transportation to relatives upon their arrival to Dallas.
   ``It could have been so much worse,'' Weeks said. ``If you look
at where this plane stopped, you'll notice if stopped a couple
hundred yards short of water tanks. When Delta 191 crashed, it hit
the same kind of tanks on the other side of the airport and look
what happened. It could have been worse.''
   Weeks, a pilot himself for 20 years, said his first thought was
that he didn't want to see an air crash in person. His wife had
been due to take off in Chicago in 1979 when an American Airlines
DC-10 crashed, killing 275. He suffered through a couple of hours
until he learned it was not her plane.
   It is a worry shared by anyone married to an airline crew
member, Weeks said.
   ``You can be tough as a boot, but your heart still stops when
you hear there's a plane down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
