<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UnisexInsurance     09-01 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unisex Insurance,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Judge Approves Massachusetts Unisex Insurance Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts joins Montana today as the only
states barring life insurance companies from their common practice
of charging men higher rates than women.
   Massachusetts' regulations became effective after a state
appellate judge refused Wednesday to delay the debut of the
so-called unisex rules. Women generally pay less than men for life
insurance because women statistically live longer than men and
therefore have more years to pay premiums.
   The ruling by state Appeals Judge Joseph Warner came in an
11th-hour appeal in a class-action suit filed by nine life
insurance policyholders. The lawsuit sought a temporary injunction
to block the regulations from taking effect until the case goes to
trial.
   ``We are disappointed, obviously, that the regulations have not
been enjoined,'' said Peter Lauriat, an attorney for the nine
plaintiffs. He predicted it will be at least three to six months
before the case is heard in Berkshire County, where it was filed.
   The plaintiffs contend that life insurance companies will raise
rates for women to comply with the regulations.
   But Assistant Attorney General Countess C. Williams argued that
it ``is not clear women will pay higher premiums'' under the new
regulations.
   Life insurance rates are unregulated in Massachusetts. Although
it is anticipated that insurers will ``blend'' their male and
female rates to reach a middle ground, there is no requirement to
do so, Lauriat said.
   Instead, Lauriat and some industry officials expect some
companies will simply raise women's rates to what men are charged _
which could add hundreds of dollars a year to some women's premiums.
   Under the regulations ordered by Insurance Commissioner Roger
Singer, life insurance companies are barred from using sex as a
basis for setting prmiums or benefits, just as the use of race,
color, religion, marital status and national origin are prohibited.
   Because the case hasn't been fully argued at the lower court
level, Warner's decision Wednesday was limited to affirming that
Berkshire Superior Court Judge John L. Moriarty committed ``no
error or abuse of discretion'' when he rejected the temporary
injunction request a week ago.
   Montana requires unisex insurance pricing under a state law
passed in 1985. A study indicated that after initial premium
increases of less than 10 percent for women, premiums were expected
to decrease and dividend returns were expected to increase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
