<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Pleasant Morning in America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation enjoyed clear skies and mild temperatures
this morning after thunderstorms in the Great Plains produced heavy
rain and hail as big as golf balls.
   Skies were mostly clear from New England to most of the Great
Lakes region, the Ohio Valley and the central Plains, and clear
skies prevailed in the Northwest and much of Texas and Arkansas.
   Thunderstorms moved across central Minnesota.
   The storms Wednesday night dropped golf ball-size hail near
Groton, S.D. Hail an inch in diameter covered the ground in Warner,
S.D.
   Scattered thunderstorms Wednesday night extended from southwest
Kansas to the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles and southwest Texas. In
the Oklahoma Panhandle, heavy rain fell for two to three hours,
leaving 4 to 6 inches of standing water on a highway in Texas
County.
   Widely scattered thunderstorms boomed Wednesday night over the
Gulf Coast states and near the south Atlantic Coast. Nearly 4
inches of rain fell at Meridian Naval Air Station, Miss.
   A few strong thunderstorms occurred around midnight in southern
Nevada and southeast California, generating winds gusting to 55 mph
at Nellis Air Force Base in Las Vegas, Nev.
   In Fresno, Calif., it was 106 degrees Wednesday, breaking the
105-degree record for the date set in 1950. The nation's high was
114 degrees in Palm Springs, Calif.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
across Gulf Coast and south Atlantic Coast states; widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms from Arkansas to Texas, western portions
of the central Plains and the southern Rockies to northern and
eastern Arizona; and scattered thunderstorms from the upper
Mississippi Valley to northern Michigan.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s and lower 90s across
most of the nation; the 90s to around 100 degrees in much of
Washington and Oregon; between 100 and 110 degrees in the desert
Southwest and interior valleys of California; the 70s in New
England, from northern Michigan to North Dakota and along the
Pacific Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 44
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo.; Bradford, Pa.; and
Houlton, Maine, to 92 degrees at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 cloudy; Boston 65 fair; Buffalo 56 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 69 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 56
fair; Detroit 60 fair; Miami 78 fair; New York 65 fair;
Philadelphia 60 fair; Pittsburgh 56 fair; Portland, Maine 58 fair;
Washington 64 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 53 fair; Chicago 67 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
72 fair; Denver 66 fair; Des Moines 66 partly cloudy; Indianapolis
60 fair; Kansas City 65 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 74 windy;
Nashville 67 fair; St. Louis 67 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 63 partly cloudy; Anchorage 50 rain; Las
Vegas 80 windy; Los Angeles 62 foggy; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt Lake
City 67 fair; San Diego 67 fair; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 63
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 fair; Toronto 61 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
