<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     09-01 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Jews,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emigration Highest Since May 1980, Armenian Emigration Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union reached a
new eight-year high in August, with a total of 1,864 Jews allowed
to leave the country, the agency helping them resettle said today.
   But the number of Armenians permitted to emigrate from the
Soviet Union dropped to 223 in August from 1,018 in the previous
month, the Intergovernmental Committee for Migration said.
   Spokeswoman Regina Boucault had no explanation for the drop. She
said that so far this year 8,241 Armenians have been allowed to
leave.
   The Jewish emigres represented the eighth straight monthly
increase in the number of arrivals at the Vienna, Austria, transit
center, Ms. Boucault said. Only 116 emigres opted to go to Israel.
   The August figure was the highest since May 1980, when 1,976
Soviet Jews were allowed to emigrate, Ms. Boucault said. The
eight-month total for 1988 is now at 9,560 emigres, of whom 1,046
went to Israel.
   The largest official exodus, 51,330, was recorded in 1979 before
the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan chilled East-West relations.
   Almost 270,000 Soviet Jews have emigrated since the resettlement
program started in 1971.
</TEXT>
