<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zimbabwe-US     09-01 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zimbabwe-US,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Resumes Aid To Zimbabwe After Years Of Feuding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States resumed economic aid
to this African nation after a two-year break with a $17 million
package for agricultural development.
   The three-year agreement was signed in Harare Wednesday by
American Ambassador James W. Rawlings.
   Zimbabwe Finance Minister Bernard Chidzero called the aid ``a
giant step'' in strengthening relations between the two nations,
which for years have been plagued by political and ideological
feuds.
   U.S. aid was stopped in 1986 after a Zimbabwean Cabinet minister
attacked American policy toward South Africa while then-President
Jimmy Carter was vising Zimbabwe. Washington cut $13.5 million of
$20.5 million pledged for that year and subsequently did not renew
assistance.
   This southeast African nation has been one of the most strident
critics of President Reagan's refusal to support economic sanctions
against white-ruled South Africa. Zimbabwe has also criticized U.S.
aid to right-wing guerrillas in Afghanistan, Angola and Nicaragua.
   Black-led Zimbabwe was known as the British colony of Rhodesia
until it won its independence in 1980.
   Rawlings, who was appointed U.S. ambassador in 1986, said
Wednesday that the resumption of aid signaled American confidence
in Zimbabwe's economic potential and good will between the two
nations.
   Under the aid agreement, the U.S. government will sell American
farming equipment and spare parts to farmers and help to develop
agricultural programs.
</TEXT>
