<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vincennes     09-01 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vincennes,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Cruiser Ends Tragedy-Marred Persian Gulf Assignment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. warship Vincennes begins its
13,000 journey home Sunday, ending a Persian Gulf assignment marred
by tragedy.
   The departure will represent the first cutback in American
forces in the gulf since the Iran-Iraq cease-fire.
   The 9,600-ton missile cruiser officially will be detached Sunday
from the Navy's Joint Task Force Middle East, Navy sources said.
Allowing for a month's sailing time and at least one port call en
route, the Vincennes should reach San Diego in mid-October.
   The departure ends the Vincennes' first combat zone assignment
since being christened at a Mississippi shipyard in 1984 by Marilyn
Quayle, wife of Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, the Republican nominee for
vice president.
   On July 3, the Vincennes crew shot down an Iranian civilian
jetliner over the Strait of Hormuz, killing all 290 aboard, after
mistaking the A300 Airbus for an attacking F-14 fighter.
   Pentagon officials attributed the blunder to crew stress in
combat but ruled out punitive action and said Iran shared the blame
by allowing the jetliner to fly over a skirmish between the
Vincennes and Iranian gunboats.
   While in the gulf region, the Vincennes also rescued five
Iranian fishermen adrift for eight days after their boat sank.
   Its withdrawal from the carrier battle group in the Arabian Sea
trims the American naval force in the region from 27 to 26 warships.
   The Pentagon says the U.S. fleet will be scaled back further if
the cease-fire between Iran and Iraq, which took effect Aug. 20,
holds.
   But it has given no timetable, and other ships in the force are
still being replaced on schedule.
   U.S. officials said withdrawing the Vincennes was a gesture
toward reducing tensions.
   The Vincennes entered the gulf May 27, the first of the Navy's
billion-dollar Aegis cruisers assigned to the waterway.
   Some critics questioned the deployment of a floating powerhouse,
designed for long-range fleet defense, to the tight, congested
gulf. Even some of the ship's officers admitted they were less than
clear about their assignment.
   Senior U.S. officials said the Vincennes would greatly expand
air surveillance capability and offset an Iranian missile threat.
   Shortly after arriving, the cruiser was out of action for radar
system repairs. U.S. officials said the problem was unrelated to
the Airbus incident.
   The Vincennes later idled at anchor in Manama for another two
weeks while a U.S. team investigated the jetliner downing. It then
was reassigned to the Navy's carrier group in the Arabian Sea, and
did not return to the gulf.
   It also made a port visit to the Seychelles islands off the
African coast, the 385-member crew's first real liberty since the
Airbus tragedy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
