<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-01 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Thin Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady in thin European trading
this morning as dealers predicted further improvement for the
American currency against the Japanese yen.
   Gold drifted higher in quiet trading.
   The yen has fallen since Bank of Japan officials hinted
Wednesday they would not raise their discount rate despite recent
interest rate hikes in the United States and Europe.
   A senior Bank of Japan official said today the Japanese
currency's movements since Wednesday were ``not a development that
requires immediate action.'' He described the yen's weakness as
``temporary.'' But he also said the bank may act to stop the yen's
fall if the bearish market persists.
   Dealers in Frankfurt said European traders were straining to
guess what the Bank of Japan would do about its falling currency.
   ``People are waiting for the Bank of Japan to step in anytime
soon but all they get is confusing messages,'' complained a dealer
at a major West German bank.
   One trader in Milan said he doubted the Bank of Japan would
raise its discount rate as long as the dollar was under 140 yen.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.73 yen to a closing 136.70 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 136.67 yen.
   But another Milan trader said dealers were slightly wary of
pushing the dollar too high against the yen for fear of central
bank intervention.
   ``The Japanese appear in no hurry for the moment to break the
dollar's rise against the yen,'' he said.
   The dealer stressed that market sentiment was still positive on
the dollar and said he expected dealers to buy dollars ahead of
Friday's release of the U.S. August employment figures.
   Other dollar rates in Europe at mid-morning, compared with late
Wednesday's rates:
   _1.8783 West German marks, up from 1.8780
   _1.5845 Swiss francs, up from 1.5828
   _6.3785 French francs, up from 6.3755
   _2.11905 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1230
   _1,394.75 Italian lire, down from 1,395.75
   _1.2380 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.681, from $1.683 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $429.50 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Wednesday's bid. At mid-morning Wednesday, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price
of $430.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $430.20, up from a $429.50 bid late
Wednesday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.65 to close at a bid
of $432.61.
   Silver was quoted in London Thursday at a bid price of $6.56 a
troy ounce, up from Thursday's $6.52.
</TEXT>
