<HEAD>Text Of Statement From Walesa After His Meeting With Authorities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a text of the statement Lech
Walesa released after his meeting with government officials:
   Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak met with Lech Walesa in Warsaw on Aug. 31,
1988. The talk was attended by Bishop Jerzy Dabrowski and Stanislaw
Ciosek (a secretary of the official national unity organization
PRON). Discussed were the premises for organizing a `roundtable'
meeting and the procedure of holding it.
   In the course of that meeting I raised the presently most
important problem of paths leading to the realization of union
pluralism including Solidarity's place.
   The partners (in the discussion) stated that all problems
connected with union movement will be discussed at the roundtable.
   The discussions of the roundtable will cover a broad range of
subjects of cooperation for the economic, social and political
reforms for the good of the country.
   In accordance with authorizations received from the striking
work crews I took over the issue of legalization of Solidarity, put
forward in strike postulates, for further talks with the central
authorities.
   I have thus decided that we now stop the strike actions. I
appeal to the inter-factory strike committees and factory strike
committees to appropriately end negotiations on other postulates
and to stop the strike.
   We remember about our slogan: there is no freedom without
Solidarity.
