<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrownPresident     09-01 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brown President,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Public Library Head Named President Of Brown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vartan Gregorian, a scholar renowned for
his fund-raising skills as director of the New York Public Library,
has been named president of Brown University, the Ivy League school
announced.
   ``I come not to preside but to build,'' Gregorian said
Wednesday. ``The institution is full of potential, full of
greatness. Some of it has been achieved, some of it still has to be
achieved.''
   Gregorian's appointment as Brown's 16th president was announced
by Chancellor A.O. Way after a meeting of the Brown Corp.,
governing body of the 7,000-student university founded in 1764.
   ``Vartan Gregorian comes to the presidency with superb
credentials as scholar and administrator,'' said Way, who headed
the selection committee. ``He has an uncommon degree of energy and
good humor, ingredients vital to all successful presidencies.''
   Howard R. Swearer is stepping down as president in December.
Swearer, 56, announced his resignation for personal reasons in
October after 11 years as president.
   Gregorian, 54, a native of Iran, went to the New York library in
1981 from the University of Pennsylvania, where he was provost. He
used various fund-raising devices, including society parties, to
raise nearly $500 million during his tenure at the library.
   Gregorian admitted his fund-raising ability did not hurt his
candidacy for the Brown position, but said his ``primary obligation
will be to the academic welfare of the institution _ if that
requires organization of fund-raising'' so be it.
   He reportedly was wooed by a number of institutions. ``Brown is
small enough that you can leave an immediate impact,'' he said in
explaining his choice.
</TEXT>
