<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CubanPrisoner     09-01 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuban Prisoner,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Celebrates Reunion With Freed Cuban Political Prisoner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban who was sentenced to death as a CIA spy and
spent 27 years in prison as one of Fidel Castro's top prizes has
been reunited with his family.
   But the last thing Jose Pujals Mederos wanted to talk about
Wednesday was his experience as a political prisoner.
   ``We're just trying to enjoy this tremendous moment in our
lives,'' said his daughter, as Pujals joined his three children and
the seven grandchildren he'd never met in a celebration at his
son's Coral Springs home. ``Relatives have been coming in in
droves. It's wall to wall in here. More are on the way.''
   Pujals, a 63-year-old former farm manager, flew here Wednesday
in a chartered jet with his wife, Gloria Lizama Pujals, after being
freed from prison by the Cuban government. His family fought for
years for his release.
   ``We found it incredible,'' said his daughter, Gloria Pullen, 36.
   Pujals was in solitary confinement during much of his
imprisonment, said Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, who worked with the
Human Rights Project to win Pujals' freedom and appealed personally
to Castro for Pujals' release during a 1987 visit to Cuba.
   ``Actually, he looks pretty good for 63,'' said Mrs. Pullen, who
said her father was 36 when she saw him last. ``He looks like a
brother and he talks like an uncle. There's no mistake it's him.''
   Pujals was imprisoned on charges of attempting to overthrow
Castro's government, Bryant's office said.
   He was tried by a military tribunal shortly before the Bay of
Pigs invasion of 1962 and sentenced to death. The sentence later
was commuted to 30 years' imprisonment. Bryant's office said Pujals
was the No. 1 political prisoner in Cuba.
   ``We wrote letters to just about every president, influential
congressmen and senators, presidents of different countries,
religious leaders _ anybody who we thought could help,'' Mrs.
Pullen said.
   The Cuban government notified Bryant and the Human Rights
Project in May that it would release 50 prisoners, including Pujals.
   ``It's like a dream come true,'' Mrs. Pullen said.
</TEXT>
