<1ST_LINE>u i PM-BusCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0463 09-01 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BELGRADE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bus Plunges Into Reservoir, 30 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JABLANICA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus carrying 50 workers home from
a seaside holiday hit a load of bricks dropped on the road and
plunged into a reservoir, the Tanjug news agency said today. Thirty
people were reported killed.
   Tanjug said 14 people were hospitalized in Wednesday's crash
near Sarajevo.
   Most of the bus passengers were textile workers and their
families returning home from the Adriatic resort of Gradac, the
state-run agency said.
   The reservoir supplies a hydro-electric plant near Jablanica, 50
miles west of Sarajevo.
   Witnesses said a tractor-trailer truck swerved to the left side
of the road in a curve and skidded into the path of the bus. The
sideboard of the trailer opened and bricks fell out onto the road,
they said.
   Witnesses said the bus swerved to avoid the bricks, but hit some
of them and turned over once before plunging 50 yards into the
reservoir, Tanjug said. The driver of the truck reportedly left the
scene and was detained by police in a nearby town, Tanjug said. It
did not elaborate.
   Divers had recovered 19 bodies from the 60-foot-deep water by
noon and were expected to pull out 11 more by the end of the day.
   ``I was asleep when I felt a terrible crash and fell between the
seats,'' a survivor, Zoran Dencic, told reporters. ``I saw light
and manged to swim to the surface, he said.
   Another passenger, Svetlana Mosovski, said she was also asleep
at the time of the accident. ``I do not remember how I swam to the
surface,'' she said. She said she sat on one of the tires, but then
the bus began to sink.
   Rescue workers planned to partly drain the reservoir to aid the
divers, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
