<DOCNO> AP880901-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InmateDeath     09-01 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inmate Death,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Dismisses Indictments In Jail Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYLER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court has thrown out murder
charges against three white lawmen in the death of a black inmate,
saying the indictments constituted double jeopardy.
   The three were acquitted in July of violating the civil rights
of Loyal Garner, who died in December of head injuries suffered in
the Sabine County Jail. Garner, 34, of Florien, La., had been
arrested on drunken driving charges.
   After the acquittal, prosecutors filed murder charges against
the three.
   Those charges, against Hemphill Police Chief Thomas Ladner, 41,
and Sabine County Sheriff's deputies Bill R. Horton, 58, and James
M. ``Bo'' Hyden, 35, were dismissed Wednesday, said Barbara Holman,
an appeals court clerk.
   The appeals court accepted arguments that the indictments
amounted to double jeopardy, or prosecuting a defendant for the
same offense more than once. Double jeopardy is prohibited by the
U.S. Constitution.
   During the civil rights trial, Ladner admitted striking Garner
on the head once with a stick but said he used only force necessary
to subdue Garner after the inmate struck him in the head and neck.
   John Hannah, who was special prosecutor in the civil rights
case, has said he will seek federal indictments against the three
on charges of conspiracy to violate Garner's civil rights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
