<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Flood     09-01 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Flood,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Toll Rises, Dhaka Residents Raft To Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Office workers in small boats and
banana-plant rafts sailed to work through flooded streets in the
capital today as the Buriganga River reached its highest level in
34 years.
   At least 680 people have died since the floods started in June
with the annual monsoon season, according to several Dhaka
newspapers.
   President Hussain Mohammad Ershad said on Wednesday the death
toll was 250, but the government's count usually is considered low.
   Dhaka, a city of 4 million, is virtually cut off from the rest
of the country. The Ministry of Communications said 18 highways
leading out of the capital were closed to traffic because of
flooding.
   One-fourth of the city was under water ranging from a few inches
to several feet. No deaths have been reported in Dhaka.
   Most of the flooding was in poor and middle-class neighborhoods,
but by today the water had started seeping into the districts of
Gulshan, Banani and Baridhara on Dhaka's northeast side, where
foreign diplomats and wealthy Bangladeshis live.
   The small Bengali-language Khabar newspaper said a boat carrying
100 flood refugees sank Wednesday in the Brahmaputra River 70 miles
north of Dhaka and all aboard were feared drowned. There was no
confirmation of the report.
   Police in Dhaka said they could not confirm the sinking, which
was reported by none of the major newspapers. Telephone lines were
out to Mymensingh, the town nearest the reported sinking.
   The Buriganga reached a danger level of 23 feet, 3 inches
Wednesday night, according to the Flood Forecast and Warning Center.
   The river, a tributary of the Ganges, has risen steadily as
waters from the already flooded north of the country surge
downstream toward the Bay of Bengal.
   ``I had to take a boat ride to come to work,'' Abdul Jabbar, a
government clerk said.
   He said his house in Swamibagh on Dhaka's southern outskirts was
under five feet of water. His family took refuge on the upper floor
of a nearby two-story building.
   Carpenters worked throughout the night building small boats to
transport people. Some people improvised rafts from banana plant
stalks and leaves.
   On Wednesday, Ershad issued an international appeal for aid,
including food, helicopters and rafts. He said his impoverished
nation, where the per capita income is $150 a year, needed 2
million tons of grain to face the emergency.
   Last year, floods killed more than 1,500 people in Bangladesh.
In 1985, more than 10,000 drowned when cyclones and tidal waves
swept over low-lying islands in the Bay of Bengal.
   ``The flooding has made me a pauper, and my shop is closed for
business,'' Abdul Ahad, a grocer, said. He said nearly all his
merchandise, including bags of rice stored in his home, was ruined
when flood waters entered the building overnight.
</TEXT>
