<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HeartAttack     09-01 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heart Attack,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Saves His Own Life After Diagnosing Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired surgeon saved his
life by diagnosing his own imminent heart attack and hurrying to a
hospital before his heart stopped, a newspaper reported today.
   The Star said Dr. Daniel du Plessis, former head of surgery at
the University of the Witwatersrand medical school, was given
life-saving shock treatment after his heart stopped while he was
being examined at Milpark Hospital in Johannesburg.
   The Star said du Plessis, 70, became convinced he was about to
have a heart attack when he felt twinges in his chest while driving
back to Johannesburg on Sunday after a weekend trip with his wife.
   Du Plessis reportedly rejected his wife's suggestion that he
relax and have a cup of tea. Instead, said The Star, he arranged to
meet a colleague at the hospital and was being examined in the
intensive care unit when his heart stopped.
   The hospital said today that du Plessis recovered well and has
been released.
</TEXT>
