<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Symphony-Redgrave     09-01 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Symphony-Redgrave,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Symphony's Cancellation of Vanessa Redgrave Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boston Symphony Orchestra didn't violate
Vanessa Redgrave's civil rights when it canceled her performances
after receiving threats of protest over the actress' pro-PLO views,
a U.S. appeals court ruled.
   The decision by the full 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
reversed an earlier finding by a three-member panel of the court
that the orchestra had violated the Massachusetts Civil Rights Act.
   The 3-2 ruling Wednesday upheld the First Amendment right of the
orchestra to cancel the performances because of concern over their
artistic integrity.
   ``We have no reason to think that the Massachusetts Legislature
enacted the MCRA in an attempt to have its courts, at the
insistence of private plaintiffs, oversee the editorial judgments
of newspapers, the speech-related activities of private
universities, or the aesthetic judgments of artists,'' said Judge
Frank M. Coffin, writing for the majority.
   However, the court reinstated an award of $12,000 that Ms.
Redgrave would have earned in a Broadway role she lost during the
suit against the symphony.
   Symphony officials were relieved by the ruling, said BSO
attorney Bob Sullivan. ``They can go back to doing what they're
best at _ making music,'' he said.
   Attorneys for Ms. Redgrave, Daniel J. Kornstein and Marvin
Wexler, did not immediately return calls.
   Ms. Redgrave was hired by the symphony in 1982 to narrate six
performances of Stravinsky's ``Oedipus Rex'' at Boston, at
Tanglewood in western Massachusetts and at New York's Carnegie Hall.
   The symphony canceled the contract after it received letters and
phone calls indicating there would be picketing and other protests
because of Ms. Redgrave's support of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   The symphony argued that Massachusetts law allowed it to cancel
performances because of concern that disruptions would mar their
artistic integrity.
   In 1984, a federal jury ruled the symphony breached its contract
with Ms. Redgrave and awarded her the $27,500 she was to have
received plus $100,000 for work Ms. Redgrave said she lost because
of the cancellation.
   A federal judge out the $100,000 award in 1985 and ruled the
symphony had not violated Ms. Redgrave's civil rights. In October,
the three-member appeals panel restored $12,000 of that award but
agreed that her rights had not been violated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
