<1ST_LINE>u p PM-MassachusettsPoll     09-01 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Massachusetts Poll,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Show Dukakis Slipping at Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new poll shows Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis running neck and neck in his home state with Republican
opponent George Bush, less than two years after Dukakis won
re-election by a landslide.
   The poll, published today in the Boston Herald, found the
Democratic and Republican presidential nominees tied at 42 percent
each with 15 percent undecided. The poll of 400 likely voters,
taken Wednesday, had a 5 percent margin of error.
   A poll taken in July for the Herald and WBZ-TV found Dukakis
leading Bush by 14 percentage points, 51 percent to 37 percent.
   ``One would have thought Dukakis would have held onto a big lead
in his home state,'' KRC pollster Gerry Chervinsky told the Herald.
   In the Herald poll, Dukakis was viewed favorably by 51 percent
of the respondents and unfavorably by 34 percent. Bush's
favorable-unfavorable ratio was 48-37 percent.
   Chervinsky said that last February, shortly after Dukakis won
the New Hampshire primary, Dukakis had a 79-14
favorable-unfavorable ratio.
   In the new Herald poll, 49 percent thought Dukakis should remain
in office pending the election, and 40 percent thought he should
resign now.
   That poll also found that 56 percent thought Dukakis had not
been an effective governor while campaigning for the presidency,
and 33 percent thought he had been.
</TEXT>
