<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleRehearsal     09-01 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Rehearsal,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts Continue Simulated Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronauts preparing for the first
post-Challenger shuttle mission adjusted a stuck piece of satellite
launch equipment and solved other simulated problems during a dress
rehearsal.
   The five astronauts were expected to confront about 150
simulated problems during the 56-hour rehearsal, which began
Tuesday and was to end this afternoon. The drill also involves
about 300 people at NASA's Johnson Space Center.
   ``They just keep throwing out one thing after another and they
(the astronauts and JSC employees) just keep solving them,''
spokeswoman Barbara Selby said.
   Commander Rick Hauck, pilot Richard Covey and mission
specialists David Hilmers, Mike Lounge and George ``Pinky'' Nelson
will fly aboard Discovery on a four-day mission.
   On Wednesday, Nelson and Lounge went outside the orbiter to fix
a stuck tilt-table needed to deploy a $100 million communications
satellite. That simulation was done in a water tank, Ms. Selby said.
   Discovery's mission will be the first shuttle flight since the
Challenger explosion 2{ years ago. The launch is slated for late
September or early October if sluggish oxygen valves and a hydrogen
leak are repaired in time.
</TEXT>
