<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AudiSuit     09-01 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Audi Suit,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Audi Will Not Settle in Acceleration Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audi of America Inc., having failed to reach a
settlement of a lawsuit alleging its Audi 5000 is prone to sudden,
unintended acceleration, says it has no choice now but to defend
itself in court.
   The class-action lawsuit was filed on behalf of some 390,000
Audi owners.
   In June, attorneys for both sides announced a settlement that
would have given each owner a credit of between $300 and $2,000
toward the purchase of a new Audi.
   But on Aug. 11, Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas R. Rakowski
rejected the settlement because it would have forced owners to buy
another Audi to benefit.
   On Wednesday, Audi attorneys informed the judge that the
automaker, a Troy, Mich.-based subsidiary of Volkswagen of America,
would fight the suit in court.
   ``We're kind of back to the wall. We have to defend (the car),''
Audi spokesman Joseph Bennett said in a telephone interview. ``We
were looking for possible solutions to this and couldn't come up
with anything.''
   The Audi 5000 owners contend the cars surge forward or backward
when shifted into gear. Audi vehemently denies there is anything
wrong with the cars.
   Mark Steinbach, a Washington attorney who represents an
organization of disgruntled Audi owners, said the rejected
settlement would not have cost Audi anything and ``would have
represented a bonanza in terms of sales.''
   The Center for Auto Safety in Washington contends 402 people
have been injured and five killed in at least 1,650 accidents
blamed on unintended acceleration by the Audi 5000.
</TEXT>
