<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq     09-01 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Trade Charges of Cease-Fire Violations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran accused Iraq today of taking 752
Iranian troops prisoner in the past 10 days, and Baghdad charged
Tehran with stalling peace talks in an effort to rebuild its
flagging army.
   As the two sides continued to trade accusations of numerous
cease-fire violations, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar said he was frustrated by the slow pace of peace talks in
Geneva.
   Official Tehran radio said the 752 Iranians were taken prisoner
since a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire went into effect Aug. 20. The
official Islamic Republic News Agency said Wednesday that 700
Iranians had been captured.
   In Baghdad, the government-run Ath-Thawra newspaper said Iran
was stalling peace talks to disguise its attempt to rebuild its
forces.
   The Iranian government ``is seeking to improve its international
stand and be in a better situation to renew the war, forgetting
that the decisive factor which prompted it to accept the
(cease-fire) was the final defeat that afflicted Iran,'' the paper
said in an editorial.
   Peace talks have hit a snag over Iraq's demand to have the
disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway immediately cleared of sunken
tankers. Iraq also has demanded sovereignty of the waterway, its
only outlet to the sea.
   Iran says a permanent cease-fire and troop withdrawal must come
before the waterway is cleared.
   Iraqi newspapers lashed out at Iran today for its insistence on
reviving the 1975 Algiers Treaty between the two countries as a
basis for a peace settlement. The treaty divided the disputed
waterway between the two sides.
   ``The (Algiers) agreement is an issue of history,'' said the
state-run Al-Jomhouriya. ``It has become meaningless and there is
no justification whatsoever to revive it.''
   In other reports of violations, Tehran radio said Iraq fired 20
artillery shells Wednesday into Oshnavieh in the north, and that
Iraqi troops later moved inside Iran from their bases across the
border. No casualties were reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, also charged Iraq with
capturing four villages, firing shots and operating military trucks
close to the warfront over the past three days.
   Iraq, meanwhile, charged Iran with setting up observation posts
and bunkers, moving troops close to the border and launching
gunboats into the Shatt-al-Arab.
   U.N. observers monitoring the truce have not reported any
serious violations by either side.
   In another development today, the Islamic Republic News Agency
said 900 Kurdish families fleeing Iraqi air raids had arrived in
northwestern Iran.
   The refugees _ elderly men, women and children _ were being
settled temporarily in the towns of Piranshahr and Orumieh in West
Azarbaijan province, said IRNA, monitored in Nicosia.
   The report said 300 of the families arrived from Turkey while
the rest came directly from Iraq, fleeing shelling and chemical
weapons. It did not specify the number of people involved.
   Diplomats in Baghdad say Iraq has taken advantage of the Aug. 20
cease-fire in the nearly 8-year-old Persian Gulf war to intensify
operations against the Kurds who want autonomy and who sided with
the Iranians in the war.
   In Ankara, Turkey, Premier Turgut Ozal said today that 60,000
Kurdish refugees had fled into the country since it opened its
border two weeks ago. He said preparations were under way for
housing the refugees.
</TEXT>
