<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Letterman,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letterman Apologizes For Joke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman apologized to the city of
Pittsburgh for a crack about the death of Pittsburgh Steelers
founder Art Rooney Sr.
   ``It's terribly sad, and there's a little controversy
surrounding this because he died during the exhibition season. So
does it count?'' the host of NBC's ``Late Night With David
Letterman'' said during Tuesday's show.
   Members of the studio audience groaned at the joke, said
Letterman publicist Peter Spivey in New York.
   The apology, made during Wednesday night's show, was directed at
the people of Pittsburgh, Spivey said.
   ``It was poor judgment,'' Letterman said. ``My heartfelt
apologies to them.''
   Rooney, who died Aug. 25 at age 87, built the Steelers into a
National Football League powerhouse during the 1970s and was
beloved in Pittsburgh.
   NBC affiliate WPXI-TV said it received calls complaining about
the joke. During the station's newscast Wednesday, offended viewers
were told to call NBC headquarters in New York.
