<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0425 09-01 0882</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Attacks Dukakis On Environmental Issues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Bush today, editing to tighten; pick up
6th graf pvs bgng ``Dukakis sought...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today staged a quick
campaign raid into Michael Dukakis' home state in a bid to raise
doubts about the Democratic presidential candidate's environmental
record, accusing him of delay while the Boston harbor got ``dirtier
and dirtier.''
   ``Two hundreds years ago tea was spilled in the Boston harbor in
the name of liberty,'' he said in a statement prepared for delivery
after a boat tour of the polluted harbor. ``If tea were spilled in
the Boston harbor today it would dissolve in the residue of my
opponent's neglect and delay.''
   Bush was greeted in the harbor by about 70 Dukakis supporters
who chanted ``Where was George?'' _ a refrain from the Democratic
convention.
   Bush said Dukakis as governor had ``twice fought to avoid making
it cleaner.'' He asserted that Dukakis had sought permission from
former Environmental Protection Agency administrator William
Ruckelshaus to delay a ban on dumping wastes in the harbor.
   Dukakis in his first term drafted papers seeking the delay but
it was his succesor, Ed King, who actually filed the delay request
to Ruckelshaus in 1979.
   ``The stealth candidate is at it again, making promises on one
hand but hiding his secret record on the other,'' Bush said.
   The vice president noted that Dukakis has visited the New Jersey
coast and spoken of his concern over the pollution along the shore.
``What he didn't tell them is this. The Dukakis administration had
applied in 1985 for a permit to dump Massachusetts sewage sludge
off the New Jersey coast,'' he said.
   In December 1985, Dukakis sought temporary permission from EPA
to dump sludge at a site 106 miles off the New Jersey coast, where
New Jersey and New York already were dumping sludge. A compromise
allowed Massachusetts to dump it farther away, at a deep-water site
beyond the continental shelf.
   Today was the second of a three-day campaign swing devoted to
the environment.
   ``Our land, water and soil support a remarkable range of human
activities,'' the vice president said Wednesday in a speech in
Michigan that aides said was designed to demonstrate a greater
commitment to environmental cleanup than the Reagan administration
has exhibited. ``But they can only take so much. We must remember
to treat them not as a given, but as a gift.''
   Bush pledged in a visit to a park on the shores of Lake Erie
that he would support establishment of a ``set timetable'' for
reduction of acid rain pollution, with the details to be worked out
with Congress. He also said he would convene an international
conference during his first year in the White House for a
discussion of the ``greenhouse effect'' that threatens a change in
the earth's climate because of gradually rising temperatures.
   Dukakis sought to tout his own record on environmental matters
earlier this summer when he broke ground for a cleanup effort of
the harbor, but his critics complained he should have recognized
the problem years ago.
   Bush drew a few critics of his own on Wednesday with his
environmental speech.
   Taking Bush to task for calling himself an environmentalist,
Blake Early of the Sierra Club said, ``We haven't seen it in his
record, so it comes as a revelation to us.''
   ``For George Bush to come here and present himself as an
environmentalist, it's like Bonnie and Clyde coming out for gun
control,'' former U.S. Sen. Paul Tsongas of Massachusetts said.
   But Bush had the stage all to himself in Michigan on Wednesday,
first making his environmental speech and later paying a visit to
the Michigan State Fair in Detroit.
   Earlier, in his visit to the park on the shore of Lake Erie,
Bush said, ``I am an environmentalist, always have been, from my
earliest days growing up and then as a congressman. ... And I
always will be, to my last days as president of this great and
beautiful country.''
   He did not mention President Reagan by name, but aides said his
call for tougher steps against acid rain was designed to illustrate
a tougher approach than the current administration.
   ``On the question of acid rain, the time for study alone has
passed,'' he said.
   ``As president, I will ask for a program to cut millions of tons
of sulfur dioxide emissions by the year 2000, and to significantly
reduce nitrogen oxide emissions as well.
   ``I will work out the exact amounts and the exact methodology
with Congress,'' he said.
   The Sierra Club's Early asked, however: ``Where was George Bush
when Bill Ruckelshaus (then head of the Environmental Protection
Agency) was trying to get a 4 million ton bill ... and was shot
down by the White House?''
   Bush also said he would make greater use of the EPA's emergency
authority to clean up toxic waste dumpsites, although he said the
Superfund established for the purpose has enough money.
   ``When America moves into the '90s, I want to ensure that `zero
tolerance' is applied not only to those who poison our children's
minds with drugs, but to those who poison our water with toxic
chemicals,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
