<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ThornburghSummons     09-01 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thornburgh Summons,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Auditor Wants Thornburgh To Testify</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Richard L. Thornburgh
will not comply with an ``absurd'' summons issued in an
investigation of a contract awarded while he was governor, a
spokesman said.
   The summons was filed in state court last week by Auditor
General Don Bailey, who is seeking to question Thornburgh as part
of Bailey's investigation of a contract between Hubco Ford Truck
Sales of Allentown and the state.
   The $23 million contract for 428 trucks was awarded in 1984,
when Thornburgh was in his second term as Pennsylvania governor.
The U.S. Senate unanimously confirmed him as attorney general last
month.
   Bailey contends that the state paid too much for the trucks and
that they were underpowered, and says he has evidence of forgery,
fraud and conspiracy in the deal by various officials under
Thornburgh. No charges have been filed.
   ``It would normally be (Thornburgh's) intent to cooperate with
any legitimate questions having to do with his administration,''
said David Runkel, a Thornburgh spokesman. ``But this is absurd.
It's a lot of nonsense and Mr. Bailey knows it.''
   Runkel said the summons is politically motivated. Bailey, who is
seeking re-election, is a Democrat; Thornburgh a Republican.
   Runkel said the matter has been fully investigated by the FBI,
the state attorney general and the U.S. attorney's office and no
problems have been found.
   The summons orders Thornburgh to testify before Bailey on the
Hubco contract and on other issues under investigation by his
office.
   Bailey vowed to take the matter to court if Thornburgh does not
comply. The auditor general had submitted his allegations to the
Senate Judiciary Committee during Thornburgh's confirmation
hearings last month.
   As auditor general, Bailey is authorized to gather information
on state matters under his jurisdiction, issue summonses to compel
testimony and forward evidence of wrongdoing to the state attorney
general.
</TEXT>
