<2ND_LINE>PM-Burdick,230</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   Eds: Restransmitting to change category code
</TEXT>
<HEAD>North Dakota Senator Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Quentin Burdick, D-N.D., was released
from the hospital today after intestinal surgery and said he was
eager to get back on the campaign trail.
   Burdick left Bethesda Naval Hospital after an operation Aug. 25
to remove part of his colon as a precaution against cancer.
   ``I'm feeling great,'' he said.
   Dr. Charles Blankenship, who performed the surgery, said the
senator was on the way to complete recovery, according to one of
Burdick's aides.
   Earlier, Blankenship had said an 18-inch section of Burdick's
colon was removed during a 2{-hour operation and that the procedure
was a complete success.
   He said no cancer was apparent in the excised colon tissue.
   The 80-year-old Burdick has served in the Senate since 1960 when
he won a special election. He is running for re-election this year
to a fifth full term and faces Republican Earl Strinden in November.
   Burdick said he would spend the Labor Day weekend with his wife
Jocelyn in Washington and then go back to work when the Senate
returns next week. He said he plans to spend the following weekend
in North Dakota.
</TEXT>
