<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ShellfishRaids     09-01 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shellfish Raids,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Arrest Shellfish Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and federal agents made nine arrests in
a series of raids at homes and seafood businesses in three states
today, concluding a year-long investigation of illegal shellfish
harvesting.
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration said the
raids were in Louisiana, Florida and South Carolina by officials of
its National Marine Fisheries Service, as well as the federal Food
and Drug Administration and state agencies.
   Names of those arrested were not released by the federal agency,
which said charges would include violations of both state and
federal laws pertaining to sale of shellfish.
   According to the report, millions of dollars worth of clams and
oysters were being illegally harvested from polluted waters and
sold in interstate commerce.
   ``For more than a year undercover agents entered a world of
black market oyster and clam dealers to document illegal
activities,'' said Suzanne Montero, a Fisheries Service special
agent.
   In South Carolina alone one dealer allegedly sold more than $1
million worth of illegally obtained shellfish over a 12-month
period, she said.
   Ten search warrants were served on oyster dealers in Louisiana
and Florida and nine warrants were served on South Carolina clam
dealers, officials said.
   Involved in the series of raids were 20 NOAA agents, 9 Food and
Drug Administration investigators and 58 officers from the Florida
Department of Natural Resources Marine Patiol, South Carolina
Wildlife and Marine Resources Division and Department of Health and
Environmental Control and the Louisiana State Police.
</TEXT>
