<DOCNO> AP880901-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaCrash-Flight     09-01 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash-Flight,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Day Later, Delta Passengers Say They Feel Safe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Delta Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Bobbe in 9th graf cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Flight 1141 from Jackson took off
with its usual passenger load today, with some fliers saying the
fatal crash one day earlier of the same flight in Texas improved
their odds.
   ``I think these kinds of accidents are only one of so many,''
said passenger Gregory Haygood. ``Hopefully it will make the pilots
and the maintenance people better check everything on the plane.''
   Later in the day, after the flight arrived at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport, the plane taxied out for takeoff but was
forced to turn back, apparently because of an incorrect instrument
reading, a Delta spokesman said.
   Flight 1141 let off its passengers after returning to the
terminal at the airport.
   On Wednesday, Flight 1141, a 6:25 a.m. Salt Lake City-bound
flight that originates in Jackson, crashed and burned on takeoff at
Dallas-Fort Worth Airport. Thirteen passengers were killed and at
least 95 survived.
   Only six of the 34 passengers who boarded in Jackson had been
ticketed to travel on to Salt Lake City. None died.
   ``It's strange for them to leave with the front page stories
about the crash yesterday,'' Clotene Lathan of Pearl said as her
daughter and son-in-law boarded the plane today. ``But I've worked
here at the airport for 22 years and I'm not afraid of flying.''
   Lathan said that she'd recently retired after working 22 years
at the Jackson Municipal Airport as a flight insurance agent and
that the hundreds of policies she'd written without having to pay
benefits convinced her the couple were safe.
   Today's flight left 10 minutes late as boarding was delayed by
reporters interviewing travelers.
   Delta employees said they were told not to talk with reporters.
But one boarding agent who asked to remain anonymous said there
were 50 passengers on Flight 1141 today, which the employee said
was an average number.
   None of the passengers interviewed said they were afraid to fly.
   ``I think the odds probably increased in my favor,'' University
of Mississippi professor Chester Quarles said. Quarles and his
wife, Bobbe, were headed to visit relatives in California.
   A middle-aged man in a business suit said the greatest hazard he
faced today was getting through the half-dozen reporters and onto
the plane.
   ``This is bloody nonsense, just bloody nonsense,'' he said,
motioning at a TV cameraman and news reporters. ``This is morbid
nonsense.''
</TEXT>
