<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico 1stLd-Writethru   09-01 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0520,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De la Madrid: Economic, Political Changes Will Help Mexico Face
Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed for 1 p.m. EDT release _ time set by source.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with de la Madrid's speech. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic changes and political reforms that
led to more democratic elections are only starting points in a
process that will help Mexico face the future, President Miguel de
la Madrid said today in his final report to the nation.
   In a speech prepared for delivery to Congress today, de la
Madrid noted that on Dec. 1, 1982 he had inherited a nation near
bankruptcy and faced a crisis that ``shook the very foundations of
our social structure.''
   The composition of the new, sharply divided Congress is itself
evidence ``of the significant transformations that the country has
undergone,'' de la Madrid said.
   He said he had renegotiated a foreign debt that now stands at
$104 billion, resisted pressure for a moratorium on payments,
reduced the role of the state in the economy and opened Mexico to
foreign competition.
   He also instituted a painful austerity program that cut
Mexicans' buying power by about 50 percent.
   ``We recognize that the cost of these changes has been high for
the majority of our population,'' de la Madrid said. But Mexicans
``wisely understood that to attain lasting well-being it was
necessary to truly reform the country.''
   He said that further debt renegotiation is necessary ``on the
principle of joint responsibiility between debtors and on adjusting
debt servicing to countries' real capacity to pay,'' but gave no
details on how that might occur.
   De la Madrid called the July 6 vote, in which the long-ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, suffered reverses, ``an
electoral process of historic significance.''
   He made no direct reference to charges of massive fraud that
tainted the vote, saying ``the process was orderly, peaceful and
closely monitored.''
   The combined opposition won nearly 50 percent of the vote and
leftist candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who gained 31 percent of the
official tally, claims he beat Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the PRI
candidate due to succeed de la Madrid on Dec. 1.
   In the Chamber of Deputies, the PRI ended up with 260 seats and
a divided opposition with 240 seats _ 139 for the leftist Front and
101 for the rightist National Action Party. The left also won four
of 64 seats in the Senate _ the first time the PRI has ever lost
Senate seats.
   Protests have continued since the election, with 10,000 people
rallying in favor of Cardenas in downtown Mexico City Wednesday.
   De la Madrid called on all citizens to ``continue perfecting our
democracy '' in accordance with the law.
   ``The journey along the road to democracy is a never-ending one;
the recent elections should be seen as a further stride toward its
higher reaches,'' said de la Madrid.
   On relations with the United States, de la Madrid noted that he
met with President Reagan six times and said ``moments of
difficulty and lack of understanding are being gradually overcome.''
   He hailed the participation of the Mexican army, navy and air
forces in the fight against drug trafficking, but said the problem
could not be solved ``unless the demand for drugs is combated in
major centers of consumption.''
   De la Madrid, who has lowered Mexico's high-profile role in
Central America, said little about the conflicts there except to
note Mexico's role in efforts to achieve a regional peace.
   He said that the attempt to decentralize Mexico's economy would
help reduce pressure on Mexico City, which is one of the world's
largest and most polluted cities. Industry is being directed to
small and medium-sized cities, he said.
   He said Mexico had been badly hurt by low petroleum prices, but
other sectors such as auto manufacturing had helped compensate in
the export market. Unemployment and strikes were both down, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
