<DOCNO> AP880901-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0448 09-01 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LOS ANGELES</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Raps Bush as `Playing Hooky' on Education</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Dukakis speech, EMBARGOED for release at
4 p.m. EDT; pickup pvs 3rd graf bgng, Dukakis made.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis accused Vice President
George Bush today of ``playing hooky'' on education while the
Reagan administration has slashed teacher training and remedial
courses for poor children.
   Opening a pre-Labor Day foray into three crucial West Coast
states, the Democratic nominee boasted of a school aid program he
initiated as Massachusetts governor, and asked about his Republican
opponent:
   ``Where was George while all this was going on? Where was the
man who now says he wants to be the `education president?' He was
playing hooky. He was nowhere to be found.''
   Dukakis said in the prepared text of an Oakland speech that the
Nov. 8 presidential election offers a choice between those with a
lifetime commitment to education and ``those who see it as an
election-year strategy.''
   On his arrival in California Wednesday night, Dukakis also took
a swing at Bush's newly proclaimed interest in protecting the
environment, including steps to eliminate acid rain.
   Dukakis called Bush ``one of the charter members of the
environmental wrecking crew which went to Washington in 1981'' with
President Reagan. He said Bush had flip-flopped on offshore oil
drilling, a hot political issue in California.
   Dukakis made his remarks as the Bush campaign devoted a day of
campaigning Wednesday to environmental issues. Dukakis is touring
three West Coast states _ California, Oregon and Washington _ in an
effort to attract the conservative Democrats who voted for
President Reagan in the last two elections.
   While campaigning last June in California, Bush said he opposed
offshore drilling for oil, according to Dukakis. ``Last week in
Texas he said he was for it,'' Dukakis said.
   An aide to the Massachusetts governor later showed reporters a
Los Angeles Times story that quoted Bush as telling a Texas
audience, ``My opponent opposes offshore drilling and I support
it.''
   Dukakis said, ``We need a president who understands how
important our environment is, how important out quality of life is,
a president whose environmental policy doesn't change with the time
zones.
   ``I understand Mr. Bush was in Michigan talking about the
environment,'' Dukakis said. ``Coming from somebody who was charter
member of the environmental wrecking crew which went to Washington
in 1981, that's very strange indeed.''
   Earlier in the day, Maine Sen. George Mitchell delivered a
political pre-emptive strike designed to blunt Bush criticism of
Dukakis' record on the clean-up of Boston Harbor.
   Bush was in Boston today to tour the polluted harbor.
   The three states Dukakis is visiting have not supported a
Democrat in the last four presidential elections.
   Democrat Hubert H. Humphrey carried Washington in 1968. The last
time California and Oregon backed a Democrat for president was in
1964.
   Those three states have large numbers of Democrats who have
consistently backed Republican presidential candidates, a pattern
Dukakis hopes to break this fall.
   Referred to now as Reagan Democrats, those voters are a major
target of the Dukakis campaign.
   Top Dukakis campaign strategists are convinced Bush cannot hold
the support once reliably Democratic blue collar voters gave to
Reagan.
   ``We are not re-running the elections of 1980 or 1984,'' said
Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich. ``We are not running
against Ronald Reagan. We are running against George Bush and our
focus is very much on the future.''
   Before he left Boston, Dukakis had a joint news conference with
Mitchell, who said: ``In 1981, the Reagan-Bush administration tried
to kill the entire water pollution program. Congress resisted and
so they then settled for undermining it.''
   Republicans have blamed Dukakis for dragging his feet on efforts
to clean up the harbor.
   ``It's been polluted for hundreds of years,'' said Dukakis.
``I'm very proud of the fact that I'm the governor who's cleaning
it up.''
   Mitchell also gave his support to Dukakis' renewed questioning
of Bush's role in the sale of arms to Iran.
   A member of the Senate-House committee that investigated the
arms sale, Mitchell quoted Bush in a television interview as saying
he went along with the arms sale because ``if he erred, he erred on
the side of getting the hostages out.''
   The Maine senator said that ``in his (Bush's) own words it is
unmistakably clear that he went along with the sale of arms and
knew that it was an exchange for hostages.''
   Increasingly under attack by Bush and Reagan, Dukakis responded
this week by renewing his criticism of the arms sales.
</TEXT>
