<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CryonicsLawsuit     09-01 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cryonics Lawsuit,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man With AIDS Sues State to Allow Freezing of His Body Upon Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS patient and a cryonics laboratory
have sued the state for the right to have his body frozen after
death in the hope he can someday be revived.
   The lawsuit was filed in Superior Court on Tuesday by an
unidentified man and by Alcor Life Extension Foundation Inc. of
Riverside, which offers cryonic suspension.
   Cryonic suspension is the practice of freezing bodies after
death in the belief that eventually they may be able to be brought
back to life and cured of their illness.
   The lawsuit challenges the Health Services Department's refusal
to grant a permit so the AIDS victim can have his body frozen. The
state granted such permission until it changed its policy in June,
the suit stated.
   The suit claims the man has a constitutional right to control
the disposition of his body.
   Pete Weisser, a Health Services spokesman in Sacramento, said
Wednesday that the department had not been served with the lawsuit
and had no comment on it.
   Weisser said that there is no provision in state law for
issuance of a permit for of cryonic suspension. But Saul Kent, a
member of Alcor Life Extension Foundation, contends the law does
not forbid the issuing of such a permit.
   ``The only reason they have yet given for declaring it illegal
or saying it may be illegal is there is nothing in the law saying
you can do it,'' Kent said.
   Riverside County authorities have been investigating Alcor since
Kent's 83-year-old mother, Dora, died there Dec. 11 without a
doctor present and her head was removed and frozen.
   The coroner's office ruled Mrs. Kent's death a homicide brought
on by a lethal dose of barbiturates. Authorities have not filed any
charges, however, and Alcor won a court order barring examination
of Mrs. Kent's head.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
