<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--India-Punjab     09-01 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--India-Punjab,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Land Mine Explodes Under Police Jeep; Two Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A land mine exploded on a highway beneath
a police jeep Thursday, killing two constables and injuring three
others, police said.
   The explosion 12 miles north of Amritsar was believed to the be
work of Sikh militants, said Police Superintendent G.S. Mann.
   The jeep was on a routine patrol when the mine exploded, he said.
   It was the first reported incident of Sikh radicals using land
mines in their campaign for an independent homeland in the northern
state of Punjab.
   The militants have killed 1,825 people in the state this year.
Most have been shot and killed, but the radicals also have used
bombs and rockets.
   The militants consider moderate Sikhs opposed to their campaign
to be traitors. Sikh radicals launched a war for a separate state
in 1982, claiming discrimination by Hindus, who form 80 percent of
India's 800 million people.
   Sikhs make up only 2 percent of the population, but the
community is in a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
