<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Patrols     09-01 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Patrols,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citizen Police Force Shows Strength in Shenzhen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7,900-member citizen's security force has been
formed to combat lawlessness in Shenzhen, one of China's most
Westernized and wide-open cities.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said 1,200 uniformed citizen
guards paraded through the southern China city on Wednesday.
   The force was formed in 1984 for street guard work, and has
branched out to become crimestoppers in offices, factories and
farms.
   Some carry nightsticks and firearms, and some are equipped with
mobile radios and motorcycles.
   Since last year, the force has captured 13,864 criminals and
helped police solve 412 cases and recover stolen property worth
$600,000, Xinhua said.
   They also mediate disputes, aid in rescues and promote public
order, it said.
   Shenzhen, a special economic zone formed in 1980 to attract
foreign investors, is one of China's most free-wheeling cities
because of its contacts with foreign countries and its proximity to
Hong Kong. Recent articles in the official media have reported
serious problems there with prostitution, promiscuity, child labor
and labor unrest.
</TEXT>
