<HEAD>Government to Aid Fire Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday earmarked $35
million to aid stores, companies and workers hit by a blaze that
destroyed much of the historic Chiado shopping district a week ago.
   The Cabinet of the center-right Social Democrat government said
it would set aside $32.5 million in subsidized loans for
shopkeepers and businesses affected by the fire.
   Deputy Prime Minister Eurico de Melo said another $2.5 million
in grants would be available to cover 80 percent of the wages to
workers who lost their jobs.
   The loans to businesses would be available for up to three years
at half the normal interest rate charged by banks, he said.
   Insurers have put the damage at $300 million, but the president
of the Lisbon Shopkeepers Association, Jose Ferreira de Matos,
estimated losses at $600 million.
   The government said between 1,200 and 1,300 workers were left
unemployed by the fire, although trade unions earlier estimated
2,000 had lost their jobs.
   One person was killed and 43 were injured in the Aug. 25 fire
that swept through a 10-block area of the 200-year-old Chiado
downtown district.
