<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirShow-Belgium     09-01 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show-Belgium,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Error Caused Crash at Air Show in Belgium</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Air Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilot error apparently was to blame for
the fatal crash of the Redigo prototype training jet at an air show
in Belgium, the head of the investigating team said Thursday.
   The state-owned Valmet corporation said it is determined to
display the aircraft at this week's air show in Farnborough,
England.
   ``I have found no evidence to support banning the Redigo,'' said
Seppo Hamalainen, who investigated Sunday's accident at Kleine
Brogel. ``It is likely that the crash was caused by human error,''
he said in a radio interview.
   Pilot Ari Piippo, 44, died when the four-seater plane failed to
come out of a spin.
   The Finnish Board of Aviation is to decide Friday whether to ban
Redigo's performance at Farnborough.
   Hannu Halonen, Redigo's other test pilot who watched Piippo's
fatal accident, said he's ready to fly the six-minute program in
the Redigo II at Farnborough, one of the world's leading air shows.
   Finnish defense officials have said an order for 10 aircraft
won't be canceled, but warned Valmet the purchase was ``on
condition that the Redigo meets the requirements of the air force.''
   Valmet had high hopes of receiving substantial orders for the
plane at Farnborough.
   The managing director of Valmet's aircraft section, Heikki
Mantyla, told The Associated Press on Thursday he believes the
accident won't affect sales.
   ``We are committed to the Redigo program and will continue to
manufacture this aircraft,'' said Mantyla. ``Everyone in the
business knows that prototypes are very prone to accidents and I
firmly believe that Sunday's unfortunate accident will only
slightly slow down its sale prospects.''
</TEXT>
