<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Arrest     09-01 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Arrest,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kenya Jails Political Detainee Six Months After Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former political prisoner has been
arrested again, six months after he was freed by presidential
pardon, his relatives and police said Thursday.
   Raila Odinga, son of former Vice President Oginga Odinga, was
arrested Tuesday on a Nairobi street by plainclothes police, and he
has not been heard from since then, the elder Odinga said.
   ``I do not want to say anything more than that,'' he added.
   Police Commissioner Phillip Kilonzo confirmed Raila Odinga had
been arrested, adding: ``I cannot disclose anything at this stage.''
   Odinga, 42, was Kenya's longest-serving political prisoner
before he and eight other detainees were released Feb. 5 by
President Daniel arap Moi. Odinga had been jailed since a failed
1982 coup attempt against Moi.
   In August, Parliament amended the constitution to allow police
to detain people suspected of a capital crime for up to 14 days
without charging them or bringing them to court. Previously, police
were required to charge them within 24 hours of arrest.
   Oginga Odinga was Kenya's first vice president after the country
gained independence from Britain in 1963. He served under the late
President Jomo Kenyatta for three years before political
differences caused a split that led to the elder Odinga's
resignation.
   Moi, the last of three Kenyatta vice presidents, became leader
when Kenyatta died in 1978.
   The elder Odinga had been one of the few open critics of Moi,
but quieted his attacks since his son's release from detention.
</TEXT>
