<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Justice-Trips     09-01 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-Trips,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trip With Meese By Justice Aides Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the Justice Department officials who
went to Japan to attend a legal conference with Edwin Meese III
this week might have been barred from the trip under Attorney
General Richard L. Thornburgh's travel policy, an aide says.
   Thornburgh, sworn in to succeed Meese on Aug. 12, will pursue
the policy he had as governor of Pennsylvania, allowing trips only
when they relate directly to official duties, the aide said
Wednesday, speaking on condition he not be named.
   ``Based on his experiences in Pennsylvania, he will only permit
travel when it pertains exactly to your job,'' the aide said. He
said this policy would rule out traveling on ``people-to-people
type'' cultural exchanges.
   ``The decision in Pennsylvania was not to go on these kinds of
trips,'' he said.
   Thornburgh and his assistants discussed the five participants on
the Tokyo trip, but decided against bumping any of them because the
trip had been planned long before the attorney general assumed
control of the agency, the aide said.
   Moreover, they felt that pulling back from the four-day legal
symposium that ended today could embarrass the Japanese hosts, he
said. ``It involved a foreign government and certain commitments
had been made.''
   The seminar, entitled ``U.S.-Japan Bilateral Session: A New Era
in Legal and Economic Relations,'' ran from Aug. 29-Sept. 1,
although some of the participants went over days earlier.
   Joseph A. Morris, director of the office of liaison services and
head of the Justice delegation, submitted requests for travel per
diem for 10 days in Japan at a cost of $237 daily.
   Morris, a Reagan administration appointee as were the other
participants, has announced his resignation to join the Mid-America
Legal Foundation in Chicago on Sept. 18.
   Others on the trip were Richard Abell, assistant attorney
general at the office of justice programs; Patrick Korten, director
of the office of public affairs; Robert Bonner, U.S. attorney in
Los Angeles, and Cheryl Nolan, Morris' subordinate.
   Deborah Bustion-Wade, a Justice Department spokeswoman,
initially said that Charles Rule, assistant attorney general for
antitrust, went on the trip. Later, she said that although Rule
went to Japan, he did not attend the legal conference but was on
other business.
   But his travel as a seminar participant was approved by Harold
Christensen, the acting deputy attorney general, in a memorandum
dated Aug. 19.
   The program included seminars such as ``Creating a Crime-Free
Society,'' and ``Japan-U.S. Relations: Sharing a Common Goal.''
There were also addresses by Japanese and Americans and field trips
to prisons, Japanese companies and government offices.
   The Justice Department paid the expenses of the six U.S.
officials, but did not pick up the tab for Meese or his wife,
Ursula.
   Norman Swanson, a spokesman for People-to-People International,
the Kansas City-based sponsor of the conference, told The New York
Times the group would cover the Meeses' travel expenses.
   But William Barraclough, the head of People-to-People, a
non-profit group, said he did not know if his group had paid the
Meeses' way.
   U.S. officials from other agencies also attended the trip.
   They included Susan Liebeler and Ronald Cass, members of the
International Trade Commission, and Jim Craig, the ITC spokesman.
The ITC paid their expenses.
   But Edward Fleischman, a commissioner at the Securities and
Exchange Commission, accepted a free trip from the sponsors, SEC
attorney Paul Gonson said. The SEC, like some agencies, has the
authority to allow some people to accept gifts so long as the
purpose is to represent the commission.
   Last year, a similar conference attended by Meese and other
Justice officials was held in China. Sponsors of the trip picked up
expenses for Mrs. Meese and Deborah Morris, Morris' wife. The
Office of Government Ethics said recently that the women should not
have taken the free trips. Federal regulations prohibit relatives
of government employees from accepting gifts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
