<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfTalks 2ndLd-Writethru   09-01 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0547,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Names Swede As Envoy To Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Perez de Cuellar leaving,
Velayati's comments. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Perez de...'' DELETES
11th graf to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
today named Sweden's U.N. ambassador as his special representative
to the faltering Iran-Iraq peace talks to continue negotiations in
his absence.
   Perez de Cuellar announced his selection of Jan Eliasson, 47,
shortly before departing for Lisbon with the 8-day-old talks
deadlocked.
   The Iraqi and Iranian foreign ministers have not met
face-to-face since last Friday because of problems over formalizing
the cease-fire and agreeing on early troop withdrawal and freedom
of navigation. Negotiations have continued on a lower, technical
level.
   In the hour before his departure the U.N. chief held separate
meetings with the two ministers, Tariq Aziz of Iraq and Ali Akbar
Velayati of Iran, to introduce them to Eliasson.
   Velayati later told reporters he was very pleased with the
appointment of Eliasson and was ``glad the secretary-general will
continue his supervision and guidance of the talks.''
   Perez de Cuellar said he was prepared to return to Geneva on
Friday if necessary to continue negotiations in person.
   ``These are very difficult, complicated negotiations and it
takes time,'' the secretary-general said as he continued
last-minute efforts to arrange a joint meeting of the two
ministers. ``The problem is lack of confidece, distrust ... like
sand, you cannot build on sand.''
   But he said, ``I am persuaded that both parties honestly are
interested in finding a solution.''
   He said both ministers would remain in Geneva as long as
necessary.
   Eliasson worked for six years as special assistant to the late
Swedish Prime Minister, Olaf Palme, on the Iran-Iraq problem.
Former U.N. Secretary-General Kurt Waldheim appointed Palme as his
special representative on the Persian Gulf war.
   Eliasson was appointed by Palme shortly before the outbreak of
the war in September 1980.
   On Wednesday night, the secretary-general failed to persuade
Iranian and Iraqi envoys to meet face-to-face.
   The main issue stalling the talks centers on a 1975 treaty
making the Shatt-al-Arab waterway the southern border of the
warring nations.
   Iraq has repudiated the treaty and wants full control of the
waterway, its only outlet to the sea. It also demands that the
channel immediately be cleared of sunken ships, which have blocked
it since the beginning of the war.
   Iran maintains the 1975 treaty is valid. It refuses to clear the
waterway until a permanent cease-fire and troop withdrawals are
worked out.
   A preliminary truce took effect Aug. 20.
   Iranian leaders claimed Wednesday that Iraq had violated the
U.N.-brokered cease-fire on three occasions.
   President Ali Khamenei was quoted by Iran's official Islamic
Republic News Agency as calling for ``the massive presence of
people on the battefield'' to ``enable us to stand against any new
aggression by the enemy.'' Khameini made the statement in a speech
in the northeastern city of Mashad.
   IRNA is monitored in Cyprus.
   In Baghdad, the state-run al-Jomhuriya newspaper demanded that
Iran ``abandon once and for all its greedy intentions in Iraq and
other Arab countries and not interfere in Iraq's internal affairs.''
   International pressure appeared to be building to persuade the
countries to reach an agreement.
   Perez de Cuellar met separately Tuesday with the ambassadors of
the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ Britain,
China, France, the Soviet Union and the United States. Observers
believe he urged the five to exert pressure on Iran and Iraq to
achieve progress in the stalled talks.
   In Baghdad, the ambassadors of the five countries met President
Saddam Hussein on Wednesday. The official Iraqi News Agency said
Hussein reiterated Iraq's desire to reach a settlement with Iran.
It did not elaborate.
   The Geneva talks were preceded by Iran's acceptance in July of a
U.S. cease-fire resolution. Iraq accepted the resolution when it
was passed last year. The two sides agreed to a cease-fire followed
by the direct talks.
</TEXT>
