<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StandardsChange     09-01 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Standards Change,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bureau of Standards Becomes Technology Institute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Bureau of Standards, the agency
responsible for determing how long is a minute and how heavy is a
pound, is no more.
   That doesn't mean the United States will no longer have any
official standards, though. It's just that the name of the Commerce
Department agency
   has been changed to the National Institute of Standards and
Technology.
   The name change was instituted when President Reagan signed the
new Technology Competitiveness Act, which gives some new
responsibilities to the agency.
   In addition to setting standards for length, weight, measure,
time and sundry other things, the institute has been directed to
work with American industry to help improve product quality,
modernize manufacturing processes and generally better compete with
foreign companies.
   It will set up a series of regional centers to help spread
improvements in manufacturing technology, help make federal
techology more available, encourage commercialization of new
products and help state and local officials in setting technology
policy.
</TEXT>
