<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WanderingBulls     09-01 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wandering Bulls,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amorous Cattle Lead Owners To Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DODGEVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two amorous bulls have landed their
owner in court, facing a lawsuit charging that the pair's romantic
adventure blighted the careers of some dairy cows from a
neighboring herd.
   Judge James P. Fiedler scheduled trial for Nov. 28 to determine
how much damages should be assessed in the 1986 incident.
   Dairy farmers Michael and Paul Mieden of rural Barneveld are
seeking about $74,000, including $33,000 for reduced milk
production, from Lloyd Vivian and his insurance company. Vivian's
attorney has offered to settle for $2,500.
   The Miedens argue that Vivian failed to patch a hole in a fence,
and the bulls got into a pasture containing about 80 of their cows.
   About 30 cattle became pregnant, including some heifers that
``will never reach full potential in size and production'' because
they were so young when they became pregnant, Colleen Martin, an
appraiser hired by the Miedens, said Wednesday.
   A veterinarian hired by Vivian said that the Miedens could have
gotten abortions for the pregnant cattle for only $500.
   Fiedler said there have been similar cases, but usually
involving only a few cows.
   In a case that reached the Wisconsin Supreme Court in 1911, a
farmer objected to the social status of a ``lowly born'' bull that
trespassed in his field and courted one of his heifers, named
Martha.
   ``This plebian, having aspirations beyond his humble station in
life, wandered beyond the confines of his own pastures and sought
the society of the adolescent and unsophisticated Martha,'' Justice
John Barnes wrote.
   The resultant calf's ``sinister birth'' left it unqualified for
prizes at the county fair, the justice wrote. The court upheld a
$75 verdict against the bull's owner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
