<HEAD>Comedian Apologizes For Joke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman apologized for joking on his
late-night television show about the recent death of Pittsburgh
Steelers founder Art Rooney Sr.
   ``It's terribly sad, and there's a little controversy
surrounding this because he died during the exhibition season. So
does it count?'' the host of NBC's ``Late Night With David
Letterman'' said during Tuesday's show.
   NBC's Pittsburgh affiliate, WPXI-TV, said it received 50 calls
complaining about the joke.
   The apology, made Wednesday night on the show, was directed to
the people of Pittsburgh, Letterman publicist Peter Spivey said in
New York.
   ``It was not my intention to defame the memory of a fine man,''
Letterman said. ``It was poor judgment. My heartfelt apologies to
them.''
   Rooney, 87, died Aug. 25 from complications of a stroke.
