<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci-China,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Heads For China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci will
depart Washington on Friday for a 10-day trip to Asia, including
six days in China, the Pentagon announced Thursday.
   In China, Carlucci is expected to discuss the prospective export
of U.S. communications satellites for launching on Chinese rockets,
and arms sales also is likely to be on the agenda. He also will
visit Guam and Hong Kong.
   ``In the People's Republic of China, Secretary Carlucci will be
the guest of China's Minister of National Defense Qin Jiwei and
will meet with senior Chinese military and political leaders to
discuss a wide variety of global, regional and bilateral issues,''
the Pentagon said.
   Carlucci will arrive in China on Sept. 5 after a two-day visit
to Guam and remain there until Sept. 10, when he flies to Hong
Kong. The secretary will return to Washington on Sept. 11, the
Pentagon said.
   ``The secretary will make a one-day stop in Hong Kong, and while
there will deliver an address to the Young Presidents'
Organization,'' the Pentagon added.
   The United States has in recent years authorized the sale of
some American arms to China, but the Reagan administration is
currently locked in an internal dispute over whether to send the
high-technology communications satellites to the Chinese.
</TEXT>
