<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DallasPlane 2ndLd-Writethru a0593 09-01 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dallas Plane, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0593,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Today's Flight 1141 from Dallas to Salt Lake City Aborted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more detail on cause of problem. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Delta Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The same Salt Lake City-bound Delta
flight involved in a crash here that killed 13 Wednesday aborted
takeoff today because of an apparent loss of power in one engine,
an airline spokesman said.
   ``Based on the incident that happened yesterday, the captain was
extremely cautious and elected simply to come back to the gate and
let maintenance look at the engine,'' said Bill Berry in Atlanta.
   Flight 1141 _ like the one that crashed, a Boeing 727 _ let off
its passengers after returning to the terminal at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport. They were put on another 727 and sent on
their way about three hours late.
   The flight, which originated in Jackson, Miss., had been
scheduled to leave here at 8:31 a.m. The number of people aboard
was not immediately known.
   Berry said the captain today released the brakes and started his
takeoff roll, reaching about about 30 mph, but ``did not get the
proper readings from one of his engines. He decided to go back to
the gate.''
   ``The captain feels that he had what is called a compressor
stall. There was a crosswind blowing across the runway. That can
interrupt the smoothness of the airflow that goes into the engine,
creating a temporary loss of power. This is very likely what
happened,'' Berry said.
   The 727, like the one that crashed, had Pratt and Whitney
engines, Berry said.
   Don Burkhalter, an assistant U.S. attorney in Jackson who was
aboard the plane, said, ``It was a routine takeoff until we got
almost to the end of the runway. Then we heard what sounded like
bumps and the pilot deaccelerated. He said there was a problem with
the compressors.''
   ``The captain said, and this is a quote, `It's just one of those
things,''' Burkhalter said. ``We just laughed.''
   Burkhalter said a couple of people on today's flight said they
were among the survivors of Wednesday's crash.
</TEXT>
