<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Cuomo-PresidentialRace     09-01 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cuomo-Presidential Race,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Says Presidential Campaign Most `Superficial' He's Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUANTICO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said Thursday
that the presidential campaign between Democrat Michael Dukakis and
Republican George Bush is the most ``superficial'' he's ever seen.
   Cuomo, a Democrat, said Dukakis has attempted to discuss issues
on the campaign trail and he blamed the Republicans for being the
negative campaigners so far.
   ``What are the issues so far? Pledge of Allegiance, furloughs,
death penalty. Are you kidding?'' Cuomo said on a flight from
Albany, N.Y., to Quantico, Va. ``This is so far the most
superficial (campaign) and it is because Republicans have made it
that way. The Republicans are not talking about any big issues so
far.''
   Cuomo said the tone of the campaign was ignoring other important
issues including drugs, national defense, international affairs and
US-Soviet relations.
   ``It's a mean campaign,'' he said, but added he thought it will
become ``great fun'' once the campaign takes off in earnest after
Labor Day.
</TEXT>
