<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonCircus     09-01 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Circus,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Circus Cancels Visit To Prison After Media Barred</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Nic is cq in 4th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A traveling circus that planned to give a
show for free to prison inmates pulled out at the last minute after
prison authorities said reporters couldn't cover the event, circus
officials said.
   Officials of Circus Vargas charged that authorities at
Stateville Correctional Center reneged on their agreement by
denying media access to the shows after the company complied with
costly personnel and equipment checks.
   John Heber, Circus Vargas director of marketing, said the circus
had planned two performances in the prison recreation yard
Wednesday, but the visit was canceled hours before showtime.
   Officials at the prison declined comment, but Nic Howell,
spokesman for the Illinois Department of Corrections, said he
became aware of the dispute Tuesday afternoon.
   ``The warden told me he was concerned about security, as well he
should be, but the bottom line was that it all was more hassle than
it was worth,'' Howell said.
   In February 1987, a Stateville inmate escaped by riding a movie
crew's truck out of the maximum-security prison during the filming
of ``Weeds,'' starring Nick Nolte.
   Heber said plans for the circus' visit included extensive
discussions with prison officials.
   ``We had done everything they asked,'' he said. ``We even
previewed the show for the assistant warden.
   ``Background checks were done on the 35 performers who would go
into the prison. We gave them a list of every tool. We agreed to
have the trucks stripped and searched.''
   ``Then suddenly they came back Tuesday night and said no media
at all.''
   Heber said the company's president, Clifford Vargas, ``said it
is a free show, and all we were going to get out of it was some
publicity. He said it wasn't fair and canceled the show.''
   The prison houses 1,850 inmates.
</TEXT>
