<HEAD>Bomb Threat Forces Return of Jet Bound for L.A.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb threat prompted a Northwest
Airlines jet bound for Los Angeles to return to Detroit
Metropolitan Airport today, authorities said.
   The DC-10, carrying 255 people, landed after the pilot informed
the control tower of the threat, said Nancy Mouradian, spokeswoman
for the Wayne County Sheriff's Department.
   The plane was evacuated so it could be searched by
explosive-sniffing dogs and bomb squad officers, the spokeswoman
said.
   ``We are calling it an in-flight bomb threat,'' Mouradian said.
``The pilot phoned it in to the tower so we have to presume the
threat occurred after the plane took off.''
   Mouradian said she didn't know who made the threat or how it was
relayed to the crew.
</TEXT>
