<HEAD>Explosion Injures 15 At Pitt's Johnstown Campus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion tore through a basement
boiler room at the University of Pittsburgh's Johnstown campus,
injuring 15 men working on a swimming pool, officials said.
   A natural gas leak was one possibile cause of Wednesday's
explosion at the Zamias Aquatic Center, said Tom Shiley, fire
safety officer at the campus.
   ``You could feel the explosion,'' said student Ron Stolarski,
who helped free victims from the rubble. ``You could see things
flying in the air.''
   Eleven of the injured were hospitalized, two in critical
condition, officials said.
   Wednesday was the first day of classes, but no faculty or
students were hurt.
