<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpyConviction     09-01 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spy Conviction,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whitworth's Espionage Conviction Upheld</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today upheld former
Navy radioman Jerry Whitworth's conviction and 365-year prison
sentence for peddling communications secrets to the Soviet Union as
a member of the Walker family spy ring.
   In a 3-0 decision, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said
there was ample evidence that Whitworth, who admitted stealing
cryptographic information but denied knowing its destination, knew
the material was being sold to the Soviets.
   The court also said the sentence, which prohibits parole
consideration for 60 years, ``is not disproportionate to
Whitworth's crimes.''
   John Walker, mastermind of the spy ring, pleaded guilty in
Maryland and was sentenced to life in prison, with parole possible
in 10 years.
   The appeals court today rejected defense arguments that
Whitworth should be treated no more harshly than Walker.
   Alan Caplan, a lawyer for Whitworth, said he would appeal.
   Whitworth was convicted of espionage in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
