<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     09-01 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Department Condemns Bomb Attack In Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department condemned on Thursday the
bombing attack by Afghan-based warplanes in Pakistan, calling it
the ``latest and most extreme incident of armed intervention''
against Pakistan's terrorial integrity.
   Deputy spokesman Phyllis Oakley said the attack, which occurred
40 miles inside Pakistani territory Thursday, was a violation of
the four-month-old Geneva agreement on Afghanistan.
   ``The United States condemns this act of aggression against
Pakistan,'' she said. One person was killed and at least 18 were
wounded, she said.
   She added that the United States will raise the issue with the
United Nations and with Soviet authorities. For their part,
Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have accused Pakistan of violating
the Geneva agreement by supporting anti-communist Afghan rebels.
   Mrs. Oakley said it was not clear whether the planes were
piloted by Soviets or Afghans.
</TEXT>
