<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachMouse     09-01 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beach Mouse,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Charged With Damaging Dunes Where Endangered Mice Live</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MORGAN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who dug a beached ship out of
the sand face federal charges they damaged the home of the
endangered Alabama beach mouse.
   Thomas Bagwell and Melvin McPherson were cited with vehicle
trespass and damaging critical habitat of an endangered species,
which can net each up to a $500 fine, said Jerome Carroll, manager
of the Bon Secour National Wildlife Refuge.
   Bagwell said he checked with the sheriff's office before
removing the boat but didn't know he needed permission from the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
   He said the removal of the 38-foot vessel in June at request of
its owner actually helped protect the environment because it was
``full of oil and diesel and other debris that would have caused
one heck of a mess.''
   The mouse, which has a buff-colored back a white belly and is 4
inches from head to tail, was added to the Fish and Wildlife
Service list of endangered species in 1985. The mouse numbers in
the hundreds, Carroll said.
   The sand dunes in the refuge are designated by the government as
the ``critical habitat'' of the Alabama beach mouse.
   Bagwell described himself as an environmentalist but said his
concern stops short of rodents.
   ``How would you like to have a rat in your pocket?'' he said.
``You'd stomp it, wouldn't you?''
   Carroll said heavy machines such as a crane and four-wheel drive
vehicles were used to pull the the boat out.
</TEXT>
