<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     09-01 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Says Iran Brainwashed Iraqi Prisoners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran brainwashed Iraqi prisoners of war,
turning many into fanatical supporters of Iran, and many POWs from
both nations are afraid to return home, a U.N. report said Thursday.
   The prisoners fear interrogation about their loyalty to their
homeland becaue they surrendered, said the report by three U.N.
experts who visited Iranian and Iraqi POW camps in late July and
early August.
   Similar problems accompanied negotiations for the voluntary
return of prisoners that prolonged the Korean War for more than a
year until April 1953.
   Iran and Iraq, now under a U.N.-brokered cease-fire in their
eight-year war, are deadlocked in peace talks in Geneva over the
withdrawal of forces and rights to the Shatt-al-Arab waterway
forming their border. The talks also are supposed to arrange the
prompt repatriation of prisoners.
   The U.N. experts are Maj. Gen. Rene Bats of the Belgian army and
international law professors Wolfram Karl of the University of
Salzburg, Austria, and Torkel Opsahl of the University of Oslo,
Norway.
   ``In both countries we learned that one set of POWs was used to
influence or inform upon another,'' they said in their report.
   POW camps in Iran were dominated by Iraqi prisoners who swore
allegiance to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and denounced
Iraq's President Saddam Hussein as an atheist, the report said.
   ``Cultural Committees'' in the camps provided religious and
political instruction called ``spiritual guidance,'' it said.
   ``To us, it is indistinguishable from mental pressure,'' it said.
   ``Many POWs stated that the `guidance' took the form of
brainwashing, putting them under permanently heavy mental
pressure,'' the U.N. team said. ``The results of the treatment are
striking.
   ``In each camp we visited, there were fanatical, hysterical and
sometimes violent demonstrations by the prisoners, who were
assembled inside along the barbed-wire fences'' shouting
pro-Khomeini slogans and denouncing Hussein and the superpowers,
the report said.
   About half the camp residents joined the rallies, but the U.N.
team observed that a zealous Shiite minority of 10 or 20 percent of
the prisoners dominated the rest.
   Iranian authorities said that system developed because they
allow the Iraqi prisoners considerable autonomy in the camp.
   Any Iraqi POW who took part in anti-Hussein demonstrations might
well worry about having to explain his actions when debriefed after
repatriation, particularly if another POW informed the Iraqi
authorities.
   Iranians also are worried about repatriating Iraqi prisoners,
the report said.
   ``There is a risk that riots may break out, for example in the
moment when transfer is to take place with a view to registration
and repatriation,'' it said.
   In Iraq, the U.N. team found Iranian POWs were also worried
about going home.
   The report said Iranian POWs had divided loyalties. Some favored
the Khomeini government, some preferred the pre-revolutionary
government of the Shah of Iran, and some were loyal to the
Mujahedeen Khalq rebels fighting Khomeini.
   ``The majority, however, seemed inclined to return to Iran,
provided they were given effective guarantees that they would not
be subject to persecution on their return. In the absence of such
guarantees, however, their future looks gloomy,'' the U.N. team
said.
   The U.N. team's main criticism of Iraq's POW camps was
occasional abuse by guards. They found no proof of systematic
indoctrination.
   The U.N. investigators estimated that Iran may be holding up to
70,000 POWs, and Iraq may have about 35,000 prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
