<2ND_LINE>AM-Duck Attack,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Muscovy Duck Attack Prompts Outcry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. AUGUSTINE BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Muscovy duck's attack on a
city commissioner and his family has reeding and
education.
   ``She sees him as the light at the end of the tunnel. If she can
just get her foot into the door, she'll be OK. She gets out of this
horrible life she's been leading. To her, he's everything that she
wants to be.''
   McCarthy played opposite Ringwald in ``Pretty In Pink.'' In both
films, his character has a a wealthier background than Ringwald's.
   ``It was a big question in all our minds before we started the
film. Are people going to see this as `Pretty in Pink II'? ''
Ringwald said. ``It's stupid, I'm a good actress and he's a good
actor and we're good together. Once we dove in and started working,
`Pretty in Pink' never came up.''
   Ringwald admitted to being nervous about handling the role of
Jewel.
   ``I didn't know if I could play that character,'' she said. ``I
read `Pretty in Pink,' and I thought, `I could do this in my
sleep.' With Jewel, I wondered if it was possible for me to be
sexy.''
   Jewel's experiences are considerably different from Ringwald's.
   ``I think you have to use your imagination to a large degree,''
she said. ``I've never been raped. I didn't grow up the way she
did. I had to use research, meet people, look through pictures.
Just get a feel for it and use your imagination.
   ``Jewel is not as educated as I am, but she knows exactly what's
going on.''
   Ringwald did manage to find common emotional ground with her
character.
   ``I related to her insecurity. A lot of people don't know what I
have to be insecure about,'' the actress said. ``Anybody, when they
fall in love, is insecure. Do they think I'm attractive? Do they
think I'm smart? What affects Jewel is her insecurity.''
   Unlike most people her age, Ringwald can look back at a lengthy
career. She began acting in 1977, playing Kate in the West Coast
stage production of ``Annie.'' In 1982, she made her film debut in
Paul Mazursky's ``Tempest'' and earned a Golden Globe nomination
for best actress.
   Ringwald recently saw ``Tempest'' on television and couldn't get
over how much her acting had changed.
   ``My voice was a lot higher,'' she said. ``I was all over the
place. I wasn't always in control. I wasn't aware of what I was
doing. I was paying attention, then not paying attention. I'm a lot
more focused than I used to be.''
   What about the future? What does Molly Ringwald see herself
doing in the 1990s?
   ``Everybody worries about where they're going to be in 10 years.
I always wonder where I'm going to be. I could be married, raising
children. Anything's possible.''
   Would she still be like to be acting?
   ``It wouldn't be the worst thing.''
</TEXT>
