<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Productivity     09-01 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Productivity,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Productivity, Purchasing Power Down Despite Higher Wages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor costs rose, productivity fell and
workers, despite higher wages, lost some of their purchasing power
in the second quarter, the government said Thursday. Analysts
called the report a warning flag of inflation and more difficult
economic times.
   In revised figures for April through June, the Labor Department
said the efficiency of non-farm businesses in churning out goods
and services dropped at an annual rate of 1.4 percent, its first
quarterly decline since 1986.
   Labor costs, meanwhile, shot up at an annual rate of 5.7 percent
_ the biggest increase since 1986 _ reflecting the productivity
declines and wage and benefit increases averaging 4.2 percent
annually.
   Charles Renfro of Alaphametrics, an economic forecasting firm in
Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said the figures indicate that an ``inflationary
head of steam is building.''
   ``Some rise in unit labor costs and a decrease in productivity
is a reflection of an economy that is beginning to battle itself,''
he said. ``The question really is what's going to hit first: a
recession or an inflationary period followed by recession.''
   The Labor Department had earlier put the productivity decline
among non-farm businesses responsible for three-fourths of the
nation's economic activity at a worse 1.7 percent.
   However, that was before the government last week revised
economic growth figures for the second quarter upward from 3.1
percent to 3.3 percent annually.
   With the higher growth, output of goods and service by non-farm
businesses in the private sector increased 5.2 percent instead of
the 4.7 percent estimated earlier.
   But to achieve that increased output, businesses had to raise
the number of hours worked by their employees by 6.6 percent.
   Analysts said the increase in hours and conseqent decrease in
productivty reflects a hiring boom in which employers at a time of
decade-low unemployment are having to use less-skilled workers more.
   ``If the marginal labor is less skilled, the result is going to
be some productivity declines,'' said Renfro. ``We may have moved
to a point where we have absorbed all of labor's skilled capacity.
That is one of the things that usually characterizes an
inflationary period.''
   Roger Brinner of Data Resources Inc. in Lexington, Mass., said
employers were ``overzealous'' in hiring last spring, predicting a
slight increase in the unemployment rate the second half of this
year.
   ``There will not be any decrease in employment; there just won't
be the large increases there have been,'' he said. ``The cyclical
boost to productivity is over and we need to run the economy at
idle speed for a while rather than at the fast pace we did in
1987.''
   Despite the second-quarter decline, businesses are still 1.6
percent more efficient than they were a year ago, according to the
Labor Department numbers, and labor costs over the 12 months are up
just 2.9 percent.
   ``Essentially, productivity is still moving upward, although the
trend is becoming somewhat discouraging,'' said Larry Chimerine of
the WEFA Group, another Bala Cynwyd consulting group.
   ``Productivity is the number one economic issue in the country
right now because it is what determines whether living standards
improve,'' Chimerine said. ``The presidential candidates should be
debating how to improve it, but they aren't,'' he complained.
   The Labor Department said hourly wages and benefits nominally
rose at an annual rate of 4.2 percent in the second quarter. But
after taking inflation into account, the buying power of each hour
of work declined 0.6 percent, the first drop in real compensation
for workers in a year.
   The 5.7 percent increase in labor costs, compared with just a
0.1 percent rise in the first quarter, was the largest since that
last quarter of 1986, when it rose 6.1 percent.
   While businesses as a whole turned less efficient, the
rebounding manufacturing sector continued to show large
productivity gains, at an annual pace of 3.6 percent in the second
quarter atop a 3.4 percent increase in 1987.
   ``Thanks to the restructuring that took place in the 1980s,
manufacturing productivity is better than it has been in four
decades,'' said Bruce Steinberg, an economist for Merrill Lynch.
``But in the services area where most people are employed it has
been dismal, despite huge investments in computers and office
equipment.''
</TEXT>
