<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Terrorists,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Deports Woman Linked to 1972 Olympic Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French woman linked to terrorists
who killed 12 people at the 1972 Olympics in Munich was deported
soon after she arrived in South Korea, where the 1988 Olympics
begin Sept. 17, officials said Thursday.
   Officials at Kimpo International Airport said the 40-year-old
woman was suspected of ties to the Black September terrorist group.
Her name was not released.
   The woman was deported to Tokyo, from where she had arrived
Tuesday. The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, refused
to disclose other details, including when the woman was deported.
   Black September, believed to be affiliated with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, has been involved in several terrorist
attacks, including an attack at the 1972 Olympics in Munich, West
Germany.
   Black September terrorists opened fire at an Olympic housing
area in Munich, killing 11 Israelis and one West German policeman.
Fiver terrorists were killed in an exchange of fire with West
German troops.
   With almost all sports and related facilities ready, security is
emerging as one of the most serious problems for the Olympics in
Seoul opening Sept. 17.
   South Korean officials, fearing international terrorist groups
might try to disrupt the Olympics, are enforcing rigid security
measures at all ports of entry.
   Several known or suspected members of the Japanese Red Army
terrorist group have been arrested in Japan and other countries in
recent months. One of them, Osamu Maruoka, had a one-way ticket to
Seoul.
   On Friday, a Korean resident of Japan was arrested at the Kimpo
airport for trying to smuggle four pistols and 21 rounds of
ammunition concealed in a suitcase.
   Police said they were investigating whether the man, Kim
Sung-sik, 50, had any connections with domestic or international
terrorist groups trying to disrupt the Olympics.
   A few days before the 1986 Asian Games in Seoul, a bomb went off
at the Kimpo airport, killing five people. South Korea blamed North
Korea for the attack.
</TEXT>
