<2ND_LINE>PM-Zaccaro, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0616,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kunin Proposes Changes in House Arrest Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to ADD that participants find their own
housing; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Kunin defended ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Madeleine Kunin today proposed
excluding drug offenders from the house arrest program that allowed
John Zaccaro Jr. to serve his cocaine trafficking term in a
$1,500-a-month luxury apartment.
   ``We must have public confidence in the system,'' the governor
said. ``We have to send a very strong message to drug dealers.
   The move came in part from the outcry over the Corrections
Department's decision to allow the 24-year-old son of former vice
presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro to participate in the
program, which allows non-violent criminals to find their own
housing and serve their sentences outside prison under supervision.
   Zaccaro was convicted in April of selling $25 worth of cocaine
to an undercover officer. He was sentenced to four months in jail
but allowed to enter the house arrest program after less than an
hour in prison.
   Later it was learned he was serving his time in a hotel-style
luxury apartment with cable television and a linen service.
   Kunin defended the program overall, saying it provided
punishment while alleviating prison overcrowding, but proposed
changes under which drug offenders like Zaccaro would be considered
more serious criminals and thus be excluded.
   ``I think anyone who sells drugs ... is a serious offender,''
Kunin said.
   Kunin said the original guidelines for the program were drafted
in 1983, and many assumptions about drug offenses had changed since
then.
   Other changes Kunin proposed would require all offenders in the
program to spend at least 24 hours in jail.
   She said she would also ask corrections officials to address
equity in the program so that the poor would not be excluded
because they could not come up with suitable accomodations and the
rich are not favored with more luxurious conditions.
   ``Hallelujah!'' Addison County State's Attorney John Quinn said
upon learning of Kunin's proposal. Quinn prosecuted Zaccaro and
opposed allowing him him into the house arrest program.
   ``I never considered that drug dealers were non-violent
offenders,'' he said. ``I never thought they should be in the house
arrest program no matter who they are.''
</TEXT>
