<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Flood     09-01 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Flood,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>680 Dead In Months Of Flooding</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name is cq for Kushum.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORSHILLA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kushum sat motionless on the heap
of rotting straw and two corrugated tin sheets that once was her
house and stared at the floodwaters that swept away her only child.
   Her 5-year-old son, Rahim, was one of seven children who drowned
when the Ganges River, swollen with floodwaters coursing down from
the Himalayan foothills in neighboring India, inundated this
village of 500 people about 70 miles west of Dhaka.
   Since the rainy season started in June, more than 680 people
have died in Bangladesh, the New Nation and other Dhaka newspapers
said Thursday. The government, whose toll is generally considered
to be understated, puts the toll at 250.
   The government estimates the floods have displaced 25 million
people, nearly one-fourth of Bangladesh's population.
   Village elders in Borshilla said Thursday the village was
flooded Aug. 22, when Kushum's son and the other children drowned,
and the water has been rising ever since.
   For the past week Kushum has refused to move from the spot where
she last saw her son.
   Khaleque Bhiyan, one of the leaders, said many villagers fled to
stay with relatives in Pabna, 30 miles northwest of here.
   Some of those who remained were stricken with dysentery but were
recovering with the help of medicine brought by relief workers from
Pabna.
   Blackish water stood up to 4 feet deep in many parts of
Borshilla. People cried, almost in unison: ``Please send us
drinking water and cooked food! We don't want anything else!''
   In Pabna, deputy magistrate Khairul Alam said government
storehouses in the region contained enough food to feed flood
victims in the region but there were not enough boats to get it to
them.
   ``What we need most urgently are boats to rescue thousands of
people marooned in far-flung areas and to provide relief to the
flood victims,'' he said.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad issued an international appeal
for boats and grain.
   On Thursday, government officials and a reporter were flown by
helicopter to Pabna from the capital, Dhaka, 75 miles to the east.
The aircraft passed over villages where only roofs were visible.
   Occasionally, twisted railroad tracks could be seen through the
water.
   ``The flood is playing havoc with life and property in 39 of the
country's 64 districts,'' Information Minister Mahbubur Rahman said
in Pabna.
   ``We need international help in meeting the emergency,'' he
said. ``We want 2 million tons of grain either as a grant or a
loan. We are even prepared to buy some of it.''
   Bangladesh is one of the world's poorest nations. Its 109
million people _ a figure recently revised by the government from
105 million _ have a per capita income of about $150 a year.
   Floods bring annual disasters to the low-lying country, where
mighty rivers like the Ganges dwarf the fields between them.
   Last year more than 1,500 people died in the summer monsoons,
and in 1985 more than 10,000 people were killed by cyclones and
tidal waves along the Bay of Bengal.
   In Dhaka, the flooding Buriganga River has submerged one-fourth
of the city under water ranging from an inch to 5 feet. But so far
no deaths have been reported in the capital.
   The city of 4 million is virtually isolated from the rest of the
country. The Ministry of Communications said 18 highways leading
out of Dhaka were closed because of flooding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
