<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Offshore-Massachusetts     09-01 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Offshore-Massachusetts,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Won't Offer Leases if Best Areas Banned by Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department won't offer oil and
gas leases off Massachusetts in the coming fiscal year if a
congressional ban on leasing the best areas goes forward, an
official said Thursday.
   Opponents of drilling are mistaken because the Georges Bank
areas of the North Atlantic most likely contains gas, far less
environmentally damaging in an accident than crude oil, said
William Bettenberg, director of the department's Minerals
Management Service.
   Core sample drilling carried out last spring by Texas A&M
University would not be permitted under a new provision of the
congressional ban, although seismic work still could continue, he
said.
   Bettenberg told reporters that the appropriations bill approved
by a House-Senate conference committee placing waters less than
1,312 feet deep (400 meters) off-limits leaves nothing worth
offering at an auction.
   Action on the bill is expected after Congress returns next week.
Interior Secretary Donald Hodel has said he would recommend a veto,
but Bettenberg said he did not know whether President Reagan would
do so.
   The ban, if it becomes law, would expand the off-limits area to
5.5 million acres from 3.2 million in previous years' prohibitions
limited to areas less than 656 feet (200 meters) deep.
   ``At this point nobody has produced at 400 meters,'' Bettenberg
said. ``Interest beyond 400 meters lies somewhere between small and
negligible.''
   The deepest offshore well is in the Gulf of Mexico at about
1,000 feet or 300 meters.
   When the smaller moratorium was in effect in 1985, the Interior
Department held a lease auction for the area and received no bids.
   Although estimates vary, the department believes there is a 30
percent chance of finding commercially valuable oil or gas in the
moratorium area, and if any is there, the odds are 50-50 that there
is 1 trillion cubic feet of gas but only a remote chance of oil.
   ``We think of the North Atlantic as essentially a gas
province,'' Bettenberg said.
   Environmental damage from an offshore gas well would be ``even
less than oil,'' said Carolita Kallaor, assistant director for
offshore operations. Bettenberg said it would be ``virtually
none,'' although an explosion could endanger workers.
   While gas wells usually produce liquid as well as gas, ``it
evaporates,'' he said.
   Asked if opponents of Georges Bank drilling were wrong to stress
the dangers of oil spills, Bettenberg said, ``We think so.''
   Georges Bank is one of the world's most productive fishing
areas, and fishing interests, strongly backed by environmental
groups and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential nominee, for years have vigorously opposed drilling.
   Congress has responded with a series of year-long bans on
leasing, frequently coupled with prohibitions covering parts of the
waters off Florida and California as in this year's bill.
   In an effort to head off another ban, Hodel earlier had
announced a delay in North Atlantic lease offering of about six
months from February 1989.
   Bettenberg said Texas A&M was under contract to oil companies
for its core sampling and any findings, while made available to the
department, were proprietary and could not be made public.
   Previous congressional action has not mentioned core sampling
and seismic exploration, Bettenberg said, and the new bill would
specifically permit seismic work while banning core drilling in the
moratorium areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
