<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-PlaneCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0596 09-01 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Plane Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0596,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Survivors In Mexican Commuter Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with rescue workers reaching wreckage;
all 20 passengers died in the crash. No pickup.
^By JAMES ANDERSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue crews reached the wreckage of a
commuter plane that crashed in a remote section of the western
Sierra Madre and said all 20 people aboard died, a military
official said today.
   Bad weather had hampered the search for the twin-engine plane.
   A helicopter owned by the Federal Electricity Commission spotted
the wreckage at 9 p.m. Wednesday about 210 miles southwest of
Mexico City.
   Helicopters were unable to fly in the area again until late this
morning and army and civilian rescuers hiked to the rugged
mountainside site.
   ``They found the plane. They have located the bodies and the
parts (of both) are dispersed in an area with a radius of about 50
meters (yards),'' Gen. Carmelo Teran, chief of staff of the 21st
military zone, said.
   ``They have found no survivors,'' he said. He spoke by telephone
from Morelia, capital of Michoacan state where the crash occurred.
   The flight left Uruapan on Wednesday morning for the 100-mile
flight to Lazaro Cardenas, said Adalberto Mandes, director of the
Uruapan airport. He said most of the 17 passengers and three crew
members were from Uruapan.
   The plane was a Brazilian-made Badeirante belonging to the small
Mexican airline Aerofederal, a federal aviation inspector contacted
at the airline in Mexico City said.
   Rescuers left Arteaga, 40 miles north of Lazaro Cardenas, at 7
a.m. on what was estimated to be a six-hour trip, most of it on
foot, to the crash site on heavily forested El Calero Hill,
spokesmen in the mayors offices of Arteaga and Lazaro Cardenas said.
   ``It's 15 kilometers (nine miles) to where they leave the
vehicles. Then they climb the hill. There are lots of rocks. You
can't walk well,'' said Jesus Gutierrez, an assistant to the
Arteaga mayor.
   He said weather conditions improved enough this morning for
helicopters to take off from Arteaga.
   Francisco Javier Flores, Lazaro Cardenas city secretary, said
the area had been lashed by Hurricane Kristy for the past two days
and it had been raining for about four days.
   ``Yesterday (Wednesday) morning there were strong winds in
Lazaro Cardenas but I don't know if they were strong where the
accident occurred,'' he said.
   The inspector in Mexico City, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said land and helicopter crews from the government Civil
Aeronatics Department were among those heading for the site.
   About 100 soldiers backed by helicopters were moving into the
area, 10 miles south of the town of Arteaga, Teran said.
   ``We only have information from people who live in the area.
Some say they heard noise. Some saw the plane pass,'' Teran said.
   Ricardo Alvarez, a worker with the Electricity Commission in
Lazaro Cardenas, said Wednesday that people in El Tahuazal, a
nearby village, had reported a loud explosion, and Mandes said
Federal Highway Police and army troops then began a search.
   Mandes said the Lazaro Cardenas airport had no radar or air
communications facilities that could have helped controllers track
the plane.
   Aerofederal is a government-owned, cargo transport airline that
also services regional passenger routes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
