<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Offshore-California     09-01 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Offshore-California,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interior Official Sees Oil Production Doubled by 1992</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil production from federal waters off
California should double by 1992, an Interior Department official
said Thursday.
   William Bettenberg, director of the department's Minerals
Management Service, said production from platforms for which
permits already had been granted should bring the total to 200,000
to 225,000 barrels a day.
   Current California production is about 100,000 barrels a day,
nearly twice the 53,700 barrels a day in 1981 and almost quadruple
the 27,900 barrels a day in 1980.
   Federal waters currently hold 16 producing platforms, and 22
should be in operation in 1992 after additions and retirements,
officials said.
   Almost all production is from the Santa Barbara Channel and the
Santa Maria Basin.
   In a meeting with reporters, Bettenberg said the Interior
Department expects new proposals in about four weeks from other
parties in negotiations attempting to resolve a 9-year-old lawsuit
by the state of California challenging the adequacy of air
pollution regulations for offshore rigs.
   Those negotiations, now almost two years old, involve industry,
environmental groups and others.
   Bettenberg said the federal government proposed a new set of
regulations in June to its negotiating partners and warned that it
would adopt them if there were no agreement.
   He said the others put up a counterproposal, ``one we thought
there was a serious possibility'' the government could accept, but
last week groups that ``had not been terribly active in the
negotiations indicated they had some problems with it,'' and the
government agreed to grant four weeks for another counterproposal.
   ``In June, I thought chances for an agreement were slim. In
July, they looked really great. They don't look quite so good
now,'' Bettenberg said.
   He declined to give specifics because all parties have agreed to
keep their proposals secret until the talks are over.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
