<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-01 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Refuses Interim Government; Proceeds With Referendum
Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Maung Maung on Thursday refused
to bow to massive protests demanding an interim government, but he
said his government would proceed with plans that could end 26
years of one-party rule.
   Tens of thousands of people staged pro-democracy demonstrations
in the capital, but a mass rally called by striking government
employees fizzled. A strike by airport workers grounded all
international flights.
   Maung Maung, Burma's first civilian president since 1962, said
in a speech on state-run radio and television that he called an
emergency meeting of the ruling party for Sept. 12 to consider a
referendum on ending single-party rule. An emergency Parliament
session is scheduled for the next day in a process the government
says could lead to a multiparty general election.
   ``There is no constitutional provision to form the (interim)
government,'' said Maung Maung, speaking slowly and calmly without
visible emotion.
   ``The government will proceed with the constitutional process of
holding the referendum, after obtaining the approval of the ...
Burma Socialist Program Party and the emergency Parliament.
   ``We cannot violate these fundamental provisions,'' he said.
``We cannot hand over to the future generation an inheritance of
the example of easily breaking discipline,'' he said.
   In a conciliatory gesture to protest leaders, Maung Maung said
the government will permit student unions and will rebuild the
Rangoon University student union building. The military blew up the
building in July 1962 while suppressing student dissent after Gen.
Ne Win led the coup that ended democracy in Burma.
   Students met on the campus Sunday to form a union, one of
several illegal associations recently announced in defiance of the
Constitution.
   Maung Maung urged government employees who have been staging
crippling pro-democracy strikes to return to work. He asked the
army, Buddhist monks and other religious leader to help the
government ease the crisis.
   Union Burma Airways suspended domestic and international service
on Aug. 26, but until Thursday flights by other carriers continued
from Bangladesh, Nepal and Thailand. Union Burma Airways also
managed a flight to Bangkok, Thailand, and back on Wednesday.
   Employees of more than 120 government departments and
state-owned corporations who formed a general strike committee this
week called for 1 million people to rally Thursday at Bandoola
Gardens, Rangoon's largest park.
   Tens of thousands of people rallied in the streets Thursday, and
several thousand striking government employees and students
gathered outside the park. The gates to the park were shut, but not
locked, and the obviously poorly organized crowd made no attempt to
enter.
   An hour later, all but a few hundred demonstrators had
peacefully dispersed. Small rallies outside the nearby U.S. Embassy
and near a government building also broke up.
   The government said Wednesday it would take action against
demonstrators who illegally occupied government buildings and
facilities. Protesters in several towns have taken over and
sometimes destroyed government and party offices.
   Government troops, who have watched from afar since five days of
bloody riots forced hard-line President Sein Lwin to resign Aug.
12, took over local government offices Wednesday in the Bahan and
Sanchaung areas of the capital and began repairing them.
   Members of former strongman Ne Win's entourage went Wednesday to
the Foreign Trade Bank and tried to transfer $3 million to a bank
in London, a senior bank official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said junior
bank employees heard about the request and demanded that the bank
refuse because Ne Win no long has authority to order such transfers.
   As word of the transfer request spread, a crowd gathered around
the bank and senior bank officials eventually rejected it, the
official said. He declined to identify the people who sought the
transfer or the bank in London.
   Ne Win resigned July 23, taking indirect responsibility for
bloody, student-led riots in March and June. He called for a
referendum on single-party rule, but the party rejected this and
picked Sein Lwin to succeed him.
   Nationwide anti-government demonstrations followed, and troops
fired on unarmed crowds. By official count, 112 people were killed
in Rangoon alone before Sein Lwin resigned Aug. 12. Peaceful
pro-democracy demonstrations have continued.
</TEXT>
