<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     09-01 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daryl Hall feels so strongly about
keeping a dump out of his town he's donating the proceeds from a
concert with John Oates on Friday to the fight against the siting.
   Hall owns a farm in Washington, N.Y., a proposed site for the
dump.
   Ellen Zoe Golden, a publicist for the duo, said Hall attended
several town meetings on the dump.
   The town is one of five possible sites for a landfill, according
to Joanne Grimes, a spokeswoman for the Dutchess County Resource
Recovery Council. The landfill would hold ash and other residue
from the county's resource recovery plant, she said.
   ``I am totally opposed to the proposed siting. The whole concept
is idiotic,'' Hall said in a statement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bobby Joe Ryman, an obscure country
western singer who does impersonations of stars such as Elvis, will
be cutting an album in the Soviet Union.
   Ryman, who plays for tourists in a Nashville restaurant, and a
dozen backup singers and musicians leave Saturday for a recording
session in Moscow for the Soviet record label Melodyia. Officials
said Ryman will be the only American singer on the label.
   ``They told me I'd be making a little history,'' he said
Wednesday.
   Ryman caught the eye of Melodyia officials in January when he
performed at a music industry convention in Cannes, France. He
signed a Melodyian contract in July.
   On the album, he will sing Elvis Presley's ``She's Not You,''
Marty Robbins' ``Singin' the Blues,'' Fats Domino's ``I'm
Walkin','' and Conway Twitty's ``Tight Fittin' Jeans.''
   He also will perform a new song _ ``Country Boy Moscow.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American rock star Prince needs a new place to play
in Rome.
   The Italian Culture Ministry on Thursday refused permission for
Prince to use Rome's Stadio Dei Marmi _ Marble Stadium _ for his
scheduled concert next Monday. It also won't allow a Sept. 12
concert by the group Deep Purple.
   Culture Minister Vincenza Bono Parrino said the 20,000-seat
stadium and national monument is in ``a fairly advanced state of
decay'' and should not be further threatened by the staging of a
rock concert.
   The stadium, adorned with 60 colossal statues of athletes, is
part of the Foro Italico complex, a sports center built under the
Fascist regime in the 1930s.
   Thousands of tickets, priced at $28 and $39, had already been
sold for Monday's concert.
   Prince, who is on a European-wide ``Lovesexy'' tour, has refused
to perform at other Rome stadiums in the past. There was no
immediate word on whether Monday's concert would be re-scheduled.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir John Tooley, the longtime boss of the Royal
Opera House, has retired.
   Tooley was general director for the last 18 years. The opera
house has had only two chiefs since World War II.
   Despite barbs from some London critics, Tooley, 64, said in an
interview before leaving: ``I've had the best job in the world.''
   With 1,000 staff and performers, The Royal Opera House costs $51
million a year to run. Its government subsidy last year was $21
million.
   Critics say it spends too much on badly conceived productions
and that taxpayers shouldn't subsidize wealthy opera-goers.
   Tooley said: ``Forty years ago we had no opera and precious
little ballet because there were no permanent companies. Now, with
our opera and ballet companies ... our productivity is colossal
compared with other European houses, and it's done on significantly
less money.''
   The new director will be Jeremy Isaacs, who ran commercial
television's Channel 4 network.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer-director Steven Spielberg says
he and actress wife Amy Irving are just homebodies from Malibu, and
like to spend as much time as possible with their 3-year-old son,
Max.
   ``We'll probably have another child in time, but right now we're
enjoying Max so much that we're selfish about him,'' Spielberg told
the Hollywood Reporter at a recent movie screening.
   Spielberg, who's completing his third ``Indiana Jones'' movie,
said he and Miss Irving aren't ``social animals.''
</TEXT>
