<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1921EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BBC     09-01 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BBC,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Last, `BBC World Service' Calling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said Thursday it is
adopting a new title by which it is already known to millions of
its overseas listeners: the BBC World Service.
   Out goes BBC External Services, a name that managing director
John Tusa says has increasingly ``sat in a clumsy and uncomfortable
way on our shoulders.''
   It is the fourth time the BBC has changed the name of its
broadcasts that reach an estimated 120 million people around the
world.
   ``As far as everyone else is concerned, we have always been the
BBC World Service,'' Tusa said. ``So we have decided to adopt that
title. It is familiar, intelligible, universal and clearly reflects
our global role.''
   The term World Service long has applied to the BBC's 24-hour
broadcasts in English, but not to the 36 foreign language services
it transmits.
   The BBC first began international broadcasts in 1932 under the
banner BBC Empire Service. That was changed to BBC Overseas
Services in 1938 when foreign language transmissions were added. By
1952, BBC External Services was the in-vogue phrase meant to
embrace all overseas output, English included.
   ``We have now recognized we were wrong about External Services
and everyone else was right,'' Tusa said.
</TEXT>
