<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VideoPirates     09-01 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Video Pirates,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrests Begin In Campaign Against Video Pirates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have begun making arrests and
seizing equipment in a crackdown on video pirates who peddle
satellite devices used for free viewing of pay TV programs, the
Federal Communications Commission said Thursday.
   FCC official Richard Smith estimated that nearly half of the one
million satellite dishes used to receive pay TV programs have
illegal devices that unscramble the picture, and let the viewer
watch for free.
   Smith, chief of the field operations bureau, said the FCC and
the Justice Department have decided to target manufacturers and
distributors of the equipment rather than individual users.
   But he cautioned home viewers with the devices that they are
acting illegally and subject to criminal and civil penalties if
caught.
   The illegal devices are clones of authorized computer chips
which unscramble the television picture beamed to satellite dish
antennas.
   ``If unchecked,'' said FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick, the
growth of the illegal chips threaten ``the viability of the
satellite-to-home program market.''
   Patrick has said the devices not only steal from those who
created the programming, but from viewers who pay for the service
and may lose it if the problem is not brought under control.
   Criminal penalties for those convicted of distributing or
selling the equipment face up to $500,000 in fines and five years
in prison. Individuals convicted of using the devices could be
sentenced to a maximum $100,000 fine and up to a year's
imprisonment.
   Smith said that John R. Ross Jr., of Cartersville, Ga. was
arrested last week on charges of marketing unauthorized satellite
descrambling equipment.
   In Ocala, Fla. a firm, V.C. Bytes, was charged with selling the
devices, he said.
   Descrambling equipment was seized from Satellite Television
Center in Palestine, Texas, and from United Satellite of America,
in Las Vegas, Nev., although no charges have been filed in either
case.
</TEXT>
