<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialDebates     09-01 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Debates,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Over Presidential Debates Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate over presidential debates remained
unresolved Thursday as campaign managers for Democrat Michael
Dukakis and Republican George Bush failed to agree on how many
face-to-face encounters the candidates should have.
   Neither side has budged from positions taken earlier this week
when Bush campaign manager James A. Baker III offered two televised
presidential debates and Dukakis manager Paul Brountas held out for
three.
   However, the Bush campaign appeared to nudge the schedule back
by a few days and pushed for an open format as opposed to sticking
to specific topics.
   Unlike the earlier meeting, which was conducted in person in
Washington, Thursday's negotiating session was on the telephone.
The two sides did agree to talk to each other again on the phone on
Tuesday.
   In statements issued after the phone call, both sides said time
was running short, with the election just two months away and
television schedules already crowded with the major league baseball
playoffs and the Olympics.
   ``The American people should have an opportunity to view the
presidential candidates discussing the important issues concerning
America's future in full,'' Brountas said. ``They should not have
to choose between watching the nominees debate world events and
watching the World Series.''
   Baker said Vice President Bush is willing to debate Dukakis any
time between Sept. 25 and Oct. 17. On Tuesday, Baker said that the
first debate could be held as early as Sept. 22.
   ``Our campaign hopes to resolve a debate schedule soon,'' Baker
said in his statement Thursday. ``Our schedule cannot be kept open
for this full 23 days forever, and we hope the Democratic campaign
will see fit to come to an agreement on a debate schedule as soon
as possible.''
   The Dukakis campaign wanted the first debate to be on foreign
policy and national security issues, but that was rejected by the
Bush campaign on Tuesday. After the Thursday session, Baker said
the debates should be on the ``broad range of issues being
discussed in the campaign rather than being subject specific.''
   The two campaigns have agreed that the vice presidential running
mates, Republican Dan Quayle and Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, would meet
for one televised debate.
</TEXT>
