<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Bus     09-01 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Bus,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Plunge Kills 31</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JABLANICA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus swerved to avoid bricks
tumbling off an oncoming truck and plunged into a reservoir,
killing 31 people, officials said Thursday.
   The bus, which crashed Wednesday night about 150 miles west of
Belgrade, was hoisted from the water Thursday with three bodies
still inside.
   The state news agency Tanjug quoted officials at the scene as
saying they believed they accounted for all the passengers, but
divers continued to search the muddy bottom of the reservoir.
   Tanjug said 14 people survived the 50-yard plunge off a cliff
into the water and were hospitalized.
   Most of the passengers were workers from the Branko Krsmanovic
knitwear factory in Paracin, about 75 miles southeast of Belgrade,
and their families on their way home from a vacation at the
Adriatic resort of Gradac.
   Tanjug said at least eight children were among the dead.
   Yugoslav television said the driver of the truck left the scene
of the accident and that police detained him about 1 a.m. in a
nearby town. He was identified as Mirsad Muminivic.
   The bus plunged into the reservoir that supplies the Gabrovica
hydroelectric power plant about 9 p.m. Wednesday.
   ``I was asleep when I felt a terrible crash and fell between the
seats,'' said Zoran Dencic, one of the survivors. ``I saw light and
managed to swim to the surface.''
   Another passenger, Svetlana Mosovski, said she also was sleeping
when the bus crashed into the water.
   ``I do not remember how I swam to the surface,'' she said. She
said she sat on one of the bus' tires, but then the bus began to
sink. ``I do not recall who brought me to shore.''
   The water was 60 feet deep where the bus fell, and divers said
it was cold and the visibility poor, complicating rescue
operations. The level of the reservoir was reduced by 15 feet to
aid rescue operations, Tanjug said.
   The road was closed briefly while cranes lifted the bus from the
water, Yugoslav media said.
   The Paracin factory said it would grant the families of dead
workers $66, Belgrade radio reported.
</TEXT>
