<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfTalks-Profile     09-01 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks-Profile,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mediator In Iran-Iran Talks Has Extensive Experience</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan Eliasson, appointed Thursday as the U.N.
chief's special representative in the Iran-Iraq talks, is a Swedish
career diplomat with extensive experience in dealing with the war
as a formal U.N. mediator.
   Eliasson, 47, has been Sweden's ambassador to the United Nations
in New York since March.
   From 1980 to 1986, he was a special aide on Iran and Iraq to
former Prime Minister Olof Palme and traveled to the region a dozen
times.
   Palme was appointed special U.N. mediator in the Iran-Iraq war
by then-Secretary-General Kurt Waldheim in November 1980, just
after the conflict broke out. He was assassinated in Stockholm on
Feb. 28, 1986.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, announcing Eliasson's
appointment, praised the diplomat as an experienced negotiator and
U.N. delegate who was ``the right hand of Mr. Palme'' in the prime
minister's ``remarkable efforts'' to end the Persian Gulf war.
   ``I therefore think it is to the benefit of our common cause
that I have now Mr. Eliasson as my special representative,'' he
said. ``We are going to work together very closely. He has my full
confidence and I am sure he will follow the same tactics I have.''
   Eliasson told reporters he was ``very gratified to be asked by
the secretary-general to perform this important function,'' which
he described as ``a difficult one.''
   He said he was grateful that the United Nations had the
confidence of Iran and Iraq, ``which is necessary in this conflict
which goes so deep.''
   ``The gulf distrust has been very wide (and) we hope it will be
becoming a little bit smaller,'' he said. ``I hope very much in
this work to have the strong support of the parties and the
continued confidence of the parties.'' Eliasson was born in
Goteborg, Sweden, on Sept. 17, 1940, and entered the foreign
service in 1965. Aside from numerous foreign policy posts in
Stockholm, including department head for Asian and African affairs,
he has served in the Swedish embassies in Bonn and Washington.
   Eliasson is married and has two daughters and a son.
</TEXT>
