<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Philadelphia-Pollution     09-01 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philadelphia-Pollution,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Charges Philadelphia In Pollution Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department on Thursday charged the
city of Philadelphia with violating the Clean Water Act by dumping
excessive amounts of pollutants and sludge into the Delaware River.
   The department's lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in
Philadelphia, represents the fourth civil action brought against
the city in the past 10 years for alleged violations at its three
sewage treatment plants. Assistant Attorney General Roger J.
Marzulla noted the city has received $575 million in federal grants
over the years to upgrade the system.
   The latest suit charges ``numerous'' violations at the city's
Southwest sewage treatment plant, some of which, it says, began in
1984 and have continued since. The purported unlawful discharges
include several oxygen-depleting pollutants, suspended solids,
fecal coliform and the heavy metals copper and cadmium.
   In addition, the department charged that the city's water
treatment plants illegally discharged sludge that interfered with
the operations of the sewage plant, or passed through it.
   In four counts, the complaint asked the court to impose a civil
penalty of up to $10,000 for each day of each violation occurring
before Feb. 4, 1987, and a penalty of up to $25,000 daily for each
violation since. Although it did not specify the number of alleged
violations, leaving that for future proceedings, the total
potential fine conceivably could range in the millions of dollars.
   The city also was charged with failure to provide the
Environmental Protection Agency with pollutant sampling
information, and sought a penalty of $25,000 for each day of each
violation on or after Feb. 4, 1987.
   Marzulla noted the action was the latest in a series of
complaints brought under EPA policies requiring municipalities to
comply with the Clean Water Act. Earlier lawsuits were filed
against San Diego, Calif., Boston, Los Angeles, St. Louis, Denver,
and Minneapolis.
   ``The Justice Department and EPA are determined that all
municipalities in the nation meet the act's requirements,''
Marzulla said. ``We will continue to bring enforcement actions
until there is full compliance.'' The EPA recently estimated that
87 percent of the publicly owned water and sewage plants around the
nation are in compliance.
   The department's earlier complaints against Philadelphia
included a 1978 suit that charged construction, reporting and
pollution violations at the three sewage plants. It was resolved by
a consent decree requiring rehabilitation work at the plants.
   In 1982, the government alleged that the city failed to meet
construction deadlines and pollution limitations at the Southwest
plant. Again, the city agreed to resolve the problems and paid a
$40,000 penalty into a trust fund to finance other environmental
projects.
   In 1986, the city was sued again, this time over construction
and pollution problems at its Northeast plant. The city accepted
revised construction schedules, agreed to carry out $2.3 million
worth of other environmental projects and paid an additional
$240,000 into the trust fund for future projects.
</TEXT>
