<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India     09-01 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislators Fight Each Other in Indian Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fistfights broke out between members of
rival parties in Parliament on Thursday, and the upper and lower
houses had to adjourn twice because legislative leaders couldn't
stop the melees.
   It was the first time legislators came to blows in the normally
sedate Parliament, the reports said.
   Opposition party members were upset after police wielding batons
and throwing tear gas charged a group of legislators outside Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi's residence earlier in the day. Nine
policemen and seven legislators suffered minor injuries and 162
legislators were arrested on charges of rioting.
   Opposition parties issued a strong protest with the ruling
Congress Party and then walked out of Parliament, the strongest
form of protest allowed in parliamentary procedure, the reports
said.
   The opposition members also decided to boycott the rest of the
current session of the Lok Sabha, the lower house, news agencies
said. Parliament is scheduled to recess Sept. 5.
   A doctor was called to the Lok Sabha to treat one legislator,
Telegu Desam party member C. Sambu, who was injured in a fight with
several members of the Congress Party, Press Trust of India news
agency said.
   Sambu had rushed toward Deputy Home Minister P. Chidambaram, to
snatch a statement he was reading to the house, but was stopped by
Congress Party members, news reports said.
   The trouble began early Thursday when a group of about 300
Telegu Desam Party members tried to walk to Gandhi's house to hand
him a memorandum regarding the federal government's relations with
opposition-ruled states, Chidambaram said in a statement to the Lok
Sabha.
   Police in the high-security area around the prime minister's
residence refused to allow them to enter. When the legislators
persisted, police used tear gas and batons to disperse them,
Chidambaram said.
   When Parliament met for the day, the opposition parties demanded
an apology from Gandhi, who was not present, news agencies said.
   Leaders of both houses refused the request, and chaos resulted.
</TEXT>
