<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Nuclear     09-01 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Nuclear,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Building Stopped at Nuclear Power Plant in Lithuania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities halted construction at a nuclear power
station in Lithuania after learning it might not be safe during an
earthquake, it was reported Thursday.
   The government has spent $412 million has already been expended
on the third reactor at the Ignalinskoy nuclear power plant alone,
the government newspaper Izvestia reported. Reactors No. 1 and No.
2 have already been built.
   Although the Soviet scientific establishment repeatedly has
assured the nation that nuclear power is safe, and also necessary
for the country's economic development, the 1986 accident at the
Chernobyl power plant in the Ukraine has made many Soviets warier
of the atom.
   The Council of Ministers of the Soviet republic of Lithuania met
recently to consider ecological and safety questions raised by the
construction of the Ignalinskoy power station, Izvestia said,
without giving the date of the session.
   The power plant was built to withstand seismic shocks that
measure 6 on the scale used in the Soviet Union, although an
earthquake rated at 7 on the same scale shook that area of the
Baltic republic at the turn of the century, Izvestia said.
   The first deputy secretary of the Lithuanian state environmental
committee, Y. Sabalyauskas, told the Council of Ministers a whole
range of safety violations was committed during construction of the
plant's first reactor, and that the safety breaches were repeated
during the building of the third unit.
   As a result of the meeting, Lithuanian authorities and the
Moscow-based ministries of atomic energy and medium-machine
building decided to freeze work on the third reactor pending ``full
answers to all questions of safety.''
   The officials also asked the Soviet Council of Ministers to
create a government commission to study problems raised by the
nuclear plant's construction, the Izvestia report said.
</TEXT>
