<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GayDemonstration     09-01 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Demonstration,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Attorney General Files Charges Against Senate Court Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state filed civil rights charges Thursday
against three state Senate court officers, accusing them of using
excessive force and abusive language in removing gay rights
demonstrators from the Senate gallery in January.
   ``The commonwealth seeks to insure that the defendants do not
further assault or harass persons because of their sexual
orientation, race, color, or national origin,'' said Attorney
General James Shannon's complaint, filed in Suffolk Superior Court.
   The state also seeks to guarantee that the officers ``do not use
excessive force, illegally detain or illegally arrest persons who
are participating in the expression of their political views,'' the
complaint said.
   The complaint stems from a Jan. 4 demonstration over Senate
delays in passing a gay rights bill. It was brought against court
officers Conrad Bailey, Thomas Sheehan and William Marcelonis.
   Shannon's complaint seeks a permanent injunction prohibiting the
three from policing any demonstration until they receive
appropriate training in police techniques.
   ``This is a message that needs to be sent over and over again
until everyone finally learns it, that in Massachusetts you cannot
harass people nor can you beat people up because of their sexual
orientation,'' said Kevin Cathcart, executive director of the Gay
and Lesbian Political Caucus.
   Fourteen to 20 demonstrators participated in the protest inside
the Senate chamber questioning a Senate committee's refusal to
release a gay rights bill _ supported by Shannon _ to ban
discrimination in employment, housing, credit and public
accommodations based on a person's sexual orientation.
   During the protest, some demonstrators shouted down to the
senators, urging them to pass the bill. Others handcuffed
themselves together.
   Court officers, who have sole police jurisdiction in the Senate,
removed 14 demonstrators and turned them over to Capitol Police.
The demonstrators were charged with trespassing. In March, six were
found innocent and charges against the others were later dismissed.
   Shannon's complaint alleges that Bailey threw one demonstrator
into a gallery chair when the man started to speak to the Senate,
yanked another by his tie until it ripped, grabbed another
demonstrator by his hair, dragged another over a chair and struck
others with a rolled-up newspaper.
   Marcelonis allegedly grabbed the shirt of another demonstrator
and pushed his hand into the man's face. Sheehan was accused of
repeatedly kicking one demonstrator while the man was carried from
the gallery.
   All three allegedly used anti-gay epithets, the complaint said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
