<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hollywood-Teamsters     09-01 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollywood-Teamsters,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters and Producers Open Talks to Avert Possible Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract talks between Teamsters drivers and
Hollywood producers convened Thursday, one day after the union
overwhelmingly rejected the producers' last offer.
   The Teamsters, who have been working for more than a month
without a contract, voted against the proposed contract by more
than a 95 percent margin, according to Earl Bush,
secretary-treasurer for the Teamsters Local 399.
   The tally, announced early Thursday, was 1,409 to 67 against the
offer, Bush said.
   A walkout by the Teamsters, representing 2,200 film and
television drivers, could hobble Hollywood production, which
returned to work only recently following a five-month
scriptwriters' strike.
   Bush said the producers' contract proposal would require about
half the members of Local 399 to take $2.61-per-hour pay cuts,
lowering their pay to $14 per hour.
   ``We'll negotiate as long as there's meaningful negotiations
going on,'' Bush said.
   The negotiations were expected to last throughout the day, and
there was no immediate news of any progress.
   The Teamsters contract expired July 30, but the powerful union
has continued to work by day-to-day extensions.
   Meanwhile, officials of Plasterers Local 755 and of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 40 have
announced that their members have also rejected management's offer
by overwhelming votes.
   The Teamsters, like the plasterers and electricians, are also
unhappy with a new overtime formula suggested by the producers.
Under the new plan, union members would be paid overtime for
Saturday and Sunday work only if more than five days had been
worked in a row. Teamsters normally collect overtime pay for any
weekend work regardless of the circumstances.
   The producers have said that union concessions are necessary to
keep costs down and prevent ``runaway'' productions, where film and
televison crews move to non-union work sites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
