<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Crawford,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opera Singer to Replace Michael Crawford in `Phantom of the Opera'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Crawford turns in his mask and cape as
``The Phantom of the Opera'' on Oct. 8 and will be replaced in the
hit Broadway musical by opera singer Timothy Nolen.
   Crawford, who won a Tony Award as the deformed composer in the
lavish Andrew Lloyd Webber musical, has played the role in London
and New York and may star in the Los Angeles company which opens
next spring.
   Nolen, who takes over as the phantom Oct. 10, made his operatic
debut in 1968 with the San Francisco Opera. He played the title
role in the Houston Grand Opera's world premiere of ``Willie
Stark,'' which later was televised on PBS. He also starred in
``Sweeney Todd'' for the Houston company as well as for the New
York City Opera.
   Nolen also appeared on Broadway in 1985 in ``Grind,'' a
short-lived musical set in a Chicago burlesque house.
</TEXT>
