<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CleanAir     09-01 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clean Air,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Confident They'll Meet Smog Standards _ 20 Years Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern California smog-control
officials say they'll meet federal clean-air standards _ maybe 20
years late, but they'll do it.
   ``By the year 2010, air quality will be at least as good as in
the San Francisco area, probably better,'' said Carolyn Green of
the South Coast Air Quality Management District, the clean-air
agency for the four-county Los Angeles basin.
   On Wednesday, an Environmental Protection Agency ban took effect
preventing the construction of big factories in the region. The ban
is expected to have little impact since no large factories or
industrial projects are planned for the Los Angeles basin.
   The area, which has the nation's worst smog, failed to meet the
Dec. 31, 1987, deadline for achieving minimum smog standards set by
the federal Clean Air Act.
   But Norton Younglove, chairman of the South Coast air-quality
board, said the agency had cracked down recently on some of the
area's biggest polluters and now requires employers to encourage
ride-sharing.
   ``We now have public support solidly behind us in our fight to
clean up the air. And I do see it as a fight,'' Younglove said.
   He said the district is to adopt in December a plan to meet U.S.
smog standards by 2007. The plan calls for greater use of
clean-fuel or electric-powered vehicles; tighter controls on
emissions from cars, trucks, trains and airplanes; and developing
non-polluting paints and solvents.
</TEXT>
