<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Kurds     09-01 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Kurds,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Kurds Flee From Iraq; U.S. Concerned About Reported Chemical
Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Iraqi Kurds have fled to Iran
after government bombardments and chemical attacks, an official
Iranian report said Thursday.
   Also Thursday, Iran's Parliament Speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani,
suggested Turkey close its pipelines to Iraqi oil.
   The United States expressed concern about reports Iraq used
chemical weapons in its latest assault on Kurdish rebel strongholds
in the mountainous northeastern part of the country.
   Diplomats in Baghdad say Iraq has taken advantage of the Aug. 20
cease-fire in the nearly 8-year-old war with Iran to intensify
operations against the autonomy-seeking Kurds, who sided with the
Iranians.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said 900 Kurdish
families arrived in northwestern Iran. The agency quoted a senior
Iranian official as telling a visiting Turkish envoy that Iraq was
planning to ``exterminate'' its Kurdish population.
   Turkey says it has allowed 20,000 Kurdish refugees into the
country and the number is expected to rise.
   The refugees in Iran _ elderly men, women and children _ were
being settled temporarily in the towns of Piranshahr and Orumieh in
West Azarbaijan province, said IRNA, monitored in Cyprus.
   The report said 300 of the families arrived via Turkey while the
rest came directly from Iraq, fleeing shelling and chemical
weapons. It did not specify the number of people involved.
   An official of the Kurdish Democratic Party, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said Wednesday that Iraq's offensive began
Monday with at least 60,000 troops backed by ``tanks, aircraft,
helicopter gunships, artillery and chemical weapons.''
   The reports could not be independently confirmed.
   Rafsanjani, who spoke in an interview on Iranian television that
was monitored in Cyprus, said there was ``nothing'' Iran could do
to prevent Iraqi attacks on Kurdish rebels or civilians.
   ``The only help we can offer is to protect the refugees who come
to Iran,'' he said. ``Of course, the world can stop (the attacks)
by putting Iraq under pressure.
   ``For instance, if Turkey closed its pipelines to Iraq to stop
it from exporting its oil, as well as other actions by other
countries, then this criminal regime will be forced to stop its
criminal acts.''
   The two pipelines, which take oil to Mediterranean ports, were
built to help Iraq export its oil during the war when the Persian
Gulf was closed to Iraqi shipping.
   In Washington, the State Department expressed concern about
reports of Iraqi chemical attacks.
   ``If the reports are accurate, this is a grave violation of
international human rights standards,'' said deputy spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley, noting that use of chemical weapons was condemned
in a U.N. Security Council resolution approved last week.
   She commended the Turkish government for offering temporary
shelter to Kurdish refugees.
   In Geneva, U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said Wednesday the
world body was taking no action following allegations of the
chemical attacks, saying there was no independent confirmation.
U.N.-appointed experts say Iraq has used the weapons against Iran
and the United Nations has condemned their use during the war.
   IRNA quoted Deputy Prime Minister for Political Affairs Alireza
Moayyeri as saying ``the Iraqi regime aims to exterminate its
Kurdish population.''
   It said he made the comment during a meeting with Nuzhei
Kandemir, an undersecretary in Turkey's Foreign Ministry, in Tehran
on an official visit.
</TEXT>
