<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Sullivan     09-01 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Sullivan,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Missouri Congresswoman Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonor K. Sullivan, a 12-term member of the
U.S. House and the only woman ever elected to Congress from
Missouri, died Thursday of heart failure. She was 86.
   Sullivan died at St. Anthony's Medical Center, where she had
been admitted Aug. 21, her 86th birthday, said hospital spokesman
Bill Feustel. She had heart and respiratory problems in recent
years.
   Sullivan began her political career after she married U.S. Rep.
John B. Sullivan in 1941. For the next 10 years she aided him in
his work serving the 3rd Congressional District, which includes
south St. Louis. Her husband died in 1951.
   A year later, the Democrat was elected to her husband's former
U.S. House seat. She held her seat until she stepped down in 1976.
Sullivan was succeeded by Rep. Richard Gephardt, who remains the
3rd District representative.
   ``She was a distinguished and an effective legislator, much
loved by the people of St. Louis,'' Gephardt said. `Her
contributions to our community and the nation will have
long-lasting effects.''
   During her years in Congress, Sullivan became a noted
environmentalist and consumer advocate. She pushed for preservation
of environmental resources and improved employment conditions, as
well as consumer protection laws for foods, drugs and cosmetics. In
1954, she was an author of legislation creating the food-stamp
program.
   Sullivan is survived by three sisters. Arrangments for her
funeral were pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
