<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeaponsProtest     09-01 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weapons Protest,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests Mar Service Marking First Anniversary Of Train Mishap</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial service on Thursday, marking
the anniversary of S. Brian Willson's failed bid to halt a Navy
munitions train, was marred by blaring horns, obscene chants and
signs mocking Willson, who lost his legs when the train struck him.
   ``We came to protest these crazy people,'' said Jack Withrow,
65, of Sacramento, a World War II veteran and one of about 15
people who appeared at the Concord Naval Weapons Station to oppose
the service.
   He carried a sign which read, ``You supply legs, we'll supply
arms.''
   Willson, a 47-year-old Vietnam veteran who has become a martyr
to the anti-war movement since he was injured last Sept. 1, seemed
more saddened than angry at the demonstrators.
   ``It's not going to stop people blocking the trains,'' he said.
``If they want to murder people, I suggest they sign up and go to
Central America and do it. Don't ask somebody else to do it.''
   The service took place on the tracks where Willson and others
tried to halt the train as part of a protest opposing U.S.
involvement in Central America. The others managed to scramble off
the tracks, but Willson was hit.
   The train, whose crew had been ordered not to stop to avoid
allowing demonstrators to climb on board, severed one leg and the
other was amputated later.
   Eight white crosses stood Thursday between the rails near where
the tracks enter the base, the target of daily demonstrations since
Willson was injured. A rainbow of crepe paper rose near the
chainlink fence which guards the area near the gate.
   ``I am celebrating personally having survived 365 days and I'm
very thankful I'm alive and you're alive here today,'' Willson told
the crowd of about 100 people gathered to mark the incident.
   ``I encourage all of us to continue asking, `How much do we want
peace?'''
   During the service, trucks and cars passed with horns and radios
blaring as passengers shouted obscene slogans in an effort to drown
out the proceedings. Some passed out a package that included an
organ donor card and a copy of a last will and testament.
   The Navy has said it is concerned about the safe transportation
of explosives across a 200-foot intersection near the demonstration
site and wants to build a $10 million overpass to take vehicles
over the highway.
   About 325 arrests have been made over the past year, but not one
person has been convicted.
   Also complaining about the on-going protests are many residents
of the neighboring town of Clyde, population 450. They contend the
rag-tag encampment of sleeping bags, lawn chairs, picket signs and
American flags is an unkempt eyesore.
   If the protesters asked, said Willson, he would tell them that
he is ``speaking the truth of my heart.''

</TEXT>
