<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     09-01 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court-Martial Proceedings Continue In Navy Recruit's Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead planned after closing arguments; time uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The court-martial for the former head of
a rescue-swimmer school neared its conclusion Thursday, one of two
court-martial proceedings under way in the death of a recruit.
   A panel of four officers was to hear closing arguments Thursday
afternoon in the dereliction-of-duty court-martial of Lt. Thomas A.
Torchia, the officer in charge of the Navy Rescue Swimmer School
when Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, died March 2.
   Mirecki, of Appleton, Wis., had a phobia about being pulled
under water and suffered a fear-induced attack before drowning, a
Navy pathologist testified in the Torchia trial.
   Instructors had thrown the panic-striken recruit into a swimming
pool after he climbed out and shouted he wanted to quit the
voluntary training, witnesses have said.
   Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael W. Combe, 28, of Tempe, Ariz.,
also faces a court-martial in the case and attorneys argued for
dismassal of the charges before a military judge on Thursday. Combe
is accused of holding Mirecki's head under the water.
   He is charged with involuntary manslaughter, battery and
conspiracy to commit battery. If convicted, he could get up to a
three-year prison term on the manslaughter count.
   The maximum punishment Torchia faces is a fine of two months
pay, a reprimand and loss of seniority for promotion, but a defense
lawyer says that is enough to put his career on the line. Torchia,
32, is from Princeton, Ill.
   In their dismissal motion, Combe's lawyers have alleged that
Vice Adm. N.R. Thunman, chief of naval education and training, was
unqualified to convene the general court-martial because he had a
personal interest in the case and had been influenced by others
against the defendant.
   The military judge, Cmdr. Newell D. Krogmann, had rejected the
same motion last week in Torchia's case.
   Thunman denied the allegations in testimony Wednesday. The
admiral's lawyer, Capt. Robert Vander Lugt, took the witness stand
Thursday to support Thunman's testimony.
   The pretrial hearing was recessed Thursday until prosecution and
defense lawyers could make legal arguments on the issue.
   In his testimony Wednesday, Thunman revealed that an
investigation initially resulted in a recommendation for no
disciplinary action. He said charges weren't filed until it was
reopened with a different officer leading the probe.
   ``I felt we had to go a lot further,'' Thunman said.
   Thunman earlier denied reports that the Navy failed to fully
investigate until pressured by the press and Mirecki's family and
congressman.
   In addition to the two court-martial cases, the investigation
also led to non-judicial punishment for five other Navy men,
including a letter of reprimand to Torchia's former boss,
now-retired Capt. C.L. Lavinder who had headed the Naval Aviation
Schools Command.
</TEXT>
