<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietLake     09-01 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Lake,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shrinking Sea Could Prompt Soviets To Divert Siberian Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shrinking of the Aral Sea, formerly the
world's fourth-largest lake, could prompt the Soviet Union to
revive a plan to divert water into the sea from Siberian rivers, a
U.S. analyst concludes.
   ``The campaign has already begun,'' wrote Philip P. Micklin,
professor in the geography department at Western Michigan
University, in a survey of the Aral's problems in this week's issue
of Science magazine, dated Friday.
   As rivers feeding it were diverted for irrigation, the Aral,
about 250 miles east of the Caspian Sea, shrank 40 percent from its
1960 size of 26,000 square miles (as big as West Virginia or
Ireland). It is now the sixth-largest lake.
   If current trends continue _ there was zero inflow in 1986 _ the
lake could reach 9,000 square miles in 2000, Soviet scientists have
estimated.
   In the 1970s and 1980s, the National Water Management Design
Institute drew plans for a huge diversion of the Ob and Irtysh
rivers in western Siberia, for both irrigation and to help the
Aral, 1,550 miles away.
   These plans were attacked by scientists and others ``who foresaw
severe ecological, economic and cultural damage occurring in
northern regions of water export.''
   Final engineering designs for the first stage of 22 million
acre-feet of water per year, a flow as big as the Wabash River in
Indiana, were being drafted in 1985 when Mikhail Gorbachev became
leader of the Communist Party.
   In August 1986 the project was halted.
   Gorbachev and his advisers ``see north-south water transfer
projects as a poor investment of scarce resources and believe less
costly, more effective local means of solving water supply
problems'' can be used in dry areas, Micklin wrote.
   A special commission last year reported on plans to preserve one
river delta and safeguard drinking water, but ``the government has
taken no concrete measures to improve the condition of the Aral,''
Micklin said.
   Though party and government officials in the Uzbekistan and
Kazakhstan republics have been silent recently, ``scientists,
writers and journalists from the region continue to plead angrily
and sometimes eloquently, in the regional as well as national
press, for action to save the Aral,'' he said.
   ``As the situation worsens, those living around the sea will put
great pressure on the national government to resurrect the Siberian
diversion plan in order to provide minimum inflow to the Aral while
maintaining irrigation.''
   In March, the president of the Uzbeck Academy of Sciences said
publicly the Aral problem could not be solved without the Siberian
diversion.
   Irrigation planners foresaw the reduction in the Aral, and ``a
number of experts saw this as a worthwhile tradeoff: a cubic meter
of river water used for irrigation would bring far more value than
the same cubic meter diverted to the Aral Sea.''
   Warnings to the contrary were not heeded. The unprecedented
changes for such a large body of water have led some Soviet experts
to call it ``one of the very greatest ecological problems of our
century.''
   Today, 47 million tons of salts are blown from the lake bottom
onto 58,000 square miles of adjacent land each year; commercial
fishing has been all but killed, costing an estimated 60,000 jobs;
river delta ecosystems have dried up with major damage to livestock
producers and native game, and summers have become warmer and
winters colder up to 180 miles away.
   Reduction of irrigation by 24 million acre-feet per year could
halt the shrinkage, but Micklin noted ``irrigation is the economic
mainstay of the Aral Sea basin where over 90 percent of the harvest
comes from irrigated lands.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0195 </DOCNO>
