<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NEA-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0630 09-01 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NEA-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0630,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEA Says Bush Turned In Assignment on School Issues A Year Late</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Bush responses and Futrell comment;
picks up 5th graf pvs, Futrell, whose.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a year late, but the National Education
Association said Thursday that Vice President George Bush has
finally turned in the assignment that all presidential contenders
were given last summer: a detailed questionnaire about schools and
other issues.
   ``We need to spend more on education,'' Bush wrote. ``Providing
an excellent education is an investment in America's future _ and
it is one of the most basic roles of government.''
   ``The tone is much more positive than we had anticipated,'' said
NEA President Mary Hatwood Futrell. But she gave the Republican
presidential nominee an ``Incomplete'' for not answering all the
questions.
   Bush reiterated his campaign promises to expand Head Start and
create a new $500 million ``Merit School'' program to help
disadvantaged children. He also opposed laws that would declare
English the official U.S. language.
   He did not respond directly to some of the 20 questions the NEA
asked on issues ranging from education to Social Security to a
nuclear freeze, but reiterated his support for tuition tax credits
and merit pay, which the NEA opposes.
   Bush, who has said repeatedly that he wants to be ``the
education president,'' ignored the teachers' questionnaire when it
was sent to him last summer.
   Asked why she thought he responded now, Futrell said, ``I think
he filled it out because he finally realizes the NEA is a powerful
political entity in this country.''
   Nearly one-third of the NEA's 1.9 million members are
Republicans, Futrell said, and ``you just don't blow your nose or
fan your hand at 600,000 votes.''
   Futrell, whose union is expected to endorse Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis next Thursday, also defended the Massachusetts
governor's veto of a 1977 bill requiring teachers to recite the
Pledge of Allegiance.
   ``We believe that the Pledge of Allegiance is very critical and
very important as part of the whole effort to teach patriotism in
America. We do not believe that it should be mandated. You cannot
mandate patriotism,'' Futrell told a back-to-school news conference
at the National Press Club.
   Bush has made a campaign issue of Dukakis' 1977 veto of the
mandatory Pledge of Allegiance bill, which the state's highest
court had advised him beforehand was unconstitutional. The
legislature passed it over Dukakis' veto.
   The Massachusetts law would penalize teachers who refuse to lead
daily recitations of the pledge, but Futrell said it is not being
enforced there or in other states with similar laws.
   She said the pledge should not be mandatory for either teachers
or students.
   ``I have sometimes difficulty dealing with people who dont''
stand up to recite the pledge, Futrell said, ``but I respect their
right not to do that. This is a democracy.''
   The NEA has been camped in the corner of the Democrats in the
past three elections, and it is expected to be there again Sept. 8
when it announces the results of a presidential preference poll of
8,400 union activists. It fielded 300 delegates to the Democratic
convention in Atlanta, compared with about 25 at the GOP convention
in New Orleans.
   Futrell said she would like to see the next president gradually
increase the $21 billion Department of Education budget by at least
$5 billion to $9 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
