<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-GdanskScene     09-01 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Gdansk Scene,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>End of Strike Has Mood of Victory Parade</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flowers and cheers greeted shipyard
workers as they ended an 11-day strike Thursday and marched from
the yard to church in what seemed like a victory parade, holding a
cross and Solidarity banners aloft.
   They acted, with some reluctance, on the advice of their leader
Lech Walesa. Supporters chanting ``We thank you'' lined their path
to a nearby Roman Catholic church that has functioned as the
national strike-central.
   The departure had an air of victory even though the more than
3,000 men went through the gate with no guarantee that their main
demand would be met. The government has agreed only to discuss
making the outlawed Solidarity union legal again.
   Strikers massed behind the main gate of the Lenin shipyard in
the early afternoon under brilliant skies. About 2,000 supporters
waited outside in welcome.
   Delegations from three other shipyards joined them for the
formal end of the labor action, agreed upon Thursday morning after
Walesa spoke to them, then they marched out.
   Before the gates opened, the waiting crowd shouted approval for
the strike: ``We will win! We will win! Every Pole is with us!''
   As the men emerged, the chant ``We thank you, we thank you''
arose and the strikers answered, ``We also you, we also you.''
   Someone had used black paint on the main sign to rename the
Lenin shipyard the Solidarity yard.
   A worker began singing the national anthem, ``Poland has not yet
perished while we still live ...'' and the crowd became a sea of
hands making the ``V'' sign of Solidarity. Marchers and onlookers
joined the song.
   The line of marchers stretched hundreds of yards, behind a cross
seven feet high and beneath bobbing Solidarity banners.
   There was little police interference, but some in the crowd were
touchy. When several young officers politely but firmly cleared a
corner, moving about 50 bystanders across the street, they got an
earful from women old enough to be their grandmothers.
   ``Reconciliation? So this is the reconciliation?'' the women
shouted, borrowing a favorite word of the government.
   ``Kiszczak should come here to see this,'' one woman said,
referring to Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak, who met with
Walesa the day before.
   Some people handed bouquets of flowers to marching workers on
the road to St. Brygida's church, which became the nerve center of
the nationwide wave of strikes that began Aug. 16.
   In the long file were men carrying bedding on their backs.
Polish strikers occupy their plants rather than leaving them, and
remain inside 24 hours a day.
   Onlookers and marchers struck up a sort of yodel usually heard
in the stands at soccer games, but one old man in a suit and black
beret continued chanting ``Solidarity, Solidarity,'' with a hand
raised in the ``V'' salute.
   When the procession reached the church for a welcoming ceremony
and a Mass celebrated by Bishop Tadeusz Goclowski of Gdansk, people
began a rhythmic clapping that lasted about 10 minutes until the
church was filled.
   Wooden crosses carried by delegations from the four shipyards
were brought to the front along with placards for various groups of
Solidarity activists.
   Among the first in the church was Alojzy Szablewski, a
62-year-old engineer who led the strike committee in the Lenin
shipyard. He walked to the altar and knelt in silent prayer.
   Bishop Goclowski said at the outset of the service: ``I thank
you for your wisdom, you sons of a 1,000-year-old nation which has
always been connected with the church. During this Mass we will
pray not for ourselves, but for our country.''
</TEXT>
