<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-S&LTalks     09-01 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Talks,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Extended Extra Day On S& L Rescue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulators on Thursday extended by a day their
talks with the Robert M. Bass Group of Fort Worth, Texas, on a
federal rescue of American Savings and Loan Association of
Stockton, Calif.
   In a statement released late in the day, M. Danny Wall, chairman
of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, described the negotiations as
``intensive'' and said any announcement would be delayed by 24
hours.
   According to industry sources, the proposal involves a
contribution of about $500 million from the Bass Group and up to $2
billion in promissory notes from the bank board, which would make
it the largest rescue ever of a single S&L. The largest-to-date is
the $1.3 billion infusion into Vernon Savings and Loan Association
in Texas.
   American is owned by the Irvine, Calif.-based Financial Corp. of
America, the second-largest thrift holding holding company in the
nation with $30.2 billion in assets as of June 30.
   Karl Hoyle, a spokesman for the bank board, would not say what
was holding up a resolution of the talks.
   The bank board on April 21 granted Bass exclusive negotiating
rights on American and had twice given one-month extensions of the
deadline, originally set for July 5. The one-day delay was the
third extension.
   Financial Corp., which first came under regulatory scrutiny in
1984 when it suffered a run on deposits, lost $223.7 million in the
first six months of this year.
   Congressional leaders and executives of First Nationwide Savings
of San Francisco, a Ford Motor Co. subsidiary, which earlier sought
to acquire American, have complained about Bass's exclusive
arrangement.
   Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I., criticized the bank board in
a letter this week, saying ``It would seem a matter of a sound
negotiating posture to maximize competition whenever possible.''
   ``It is essential that there be no appearance of exclusion or
suggestion that any alternative was overlooked,'' St Germain wrote.
   Wall, in his statement Thursday, noted that the failed
negotiations with First Nationwide were longer than the talks with
Bass.
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich., who is expected to become
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee next year, wrote to Wall
on Wednesday, saying he was concerned about the bank board's plan
to allow American to remain under a state charter when Bass assumes
ownership.
   He said it was ``unprecedented'' for regulators to allow a
rescued thrift institution to remain under a state charter which he
said permitted ``extremely liberal powers.''
   One factor that had delayed a deal in the past appears to be
cleared up. The Bass Group was concerned that the federal
assistance would be subject to California's 11 percent corporate
income tax. That risk would be eliminated by a bill that cleared
the California legislature Tuesday and awaits the governor's
signature.
</TEXT>
