<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-HomeWoes 1stLd-Writethru a0648 09-01 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Home Woes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis At Home: Widespread Discontent With the Governor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Dukakis comment, SUB 7th graf pvs, Dukakis
aides...such talk, with two grafs, picking up 8th graf pvs, ``We're
going...presidential nominee; note language in 8th graf pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than two years after he won re-election in a
historic landslide, Michael Dukakis finds himself in an
embarrassing position at home with a new poll showing him even with
George Bush in Massachusetts and widespread unhappiness with his
recent performance as governor.
   While aides to the Democratic presidential nominee scoffed at
the poll results and predicted Dukakis would defeat Bush handily in
Massachusetts, political observers from both parties were nearly
unanimous in blaming Dukakis' slide on a recent spate of problems
and protests related to the governor's handling of a state budget
crisis.
   Ironically, the presidential poll showing Dukakis and Bush each
with 42 percent support among Massachusetts voters was published
Thursday, a day when the Republican nominee was campaigning behind
enemy lines in Massachusetts and Dukakis was on the West Coast.
   ``I can't believe it _ in Massachusetts?'' a pleased Bush
responded when shown the headline on the story in The Boston
Herald, which commissioned the poll.
   The telephone survey of 400 likely voters was conducted
Wednesday by KRC Research and had a margin of error of five
percentage points. Fifteen percent of the respondents said they
were undecided.
   ``We're out to win here,'' said Republican state Sen. Argeo Paul
Cellucci, the Massachusetts chairman of the Bush campaign.
``Michael Dukakis is in trouble here in Massachusetts.''
   Dukakis said ``no'' when asked whether he was worried about
carrying his home state. Dukakis aides and Democratic political
consultants dismiss talk about Dukakis being threatened in his home
state.
   ``We're very confident Michael Dukakis will carry
Massachusetts,'' said press secretary Dayton Duncan. ``We're also
confident he will carry George Bush's other home states _ Maine,
Texas, Washington, D.C., and any others he claims.''
   ``We're going to do to George Bush in Massachusetts what he said
he did to Geraldine Ferarro in 1984,'' said Jack Corrigan, director
of operations for the Dukakis campaign, a reference to Bush's
statement that he ``kicked a little ass'' in a debate with Ferraro,
the 1984 Democratic vice presidential nominee.
   ``Yea, George Bush should target Massachusetts, that's my advice
to him,'' said Corrigan.
   Corrigan declined to speculate on factors that allowed Bush to
pull even with Dukakis in Massachusetts only two months after a
poll showed the governor with a 14-point cushion.
   But Democratic political consultant Michael Goldman, reflecting
a consensus among political observers in both parties, said the
reasons behind the poll numbers ``are really very simple.
   ``He has been under intense pressure to balance his
responsibilities as governor and candidate at a time when Michael
has run into some real bumps on the Massachusetts road,'' said
Goldman.
   Those much-publicized ``bumps'' include repeated outcry from
interest groups and legislators, mostly Republicans, related to the
plan Dukakis pushed through the legislature to balance the 1988 and
1989 state budgets by canceling more than $500 million in planned
program expansions and by trimming state aid to cities and towns by
$91 million. Dukakis also supported several narrowly focused tax
measures.
   Since securing the Democratic presidential nomination Dukakis
also has been a frequent target of protests and complaints on
issues ranging from crime in the city of Boston to his plans to
locate a prison in a rural central Massachusetts town. Dukakis has
spent six days in the last three weeks touring different regions of
the state and was met by demonstrators at virtually every stop.
   There also have been complaints from GOP legislators about the
amount of time Dukakis spends out of state, a concern that,
according to the KRC poll, appears to be shared by voters.
   The survey found that 56 percent of the respondents considered
Dukakis' performance as governor during his presidential campaign
``not effective'' while 33 percent rated him ``effective'' and 11
percent said they didn't know whether he had been effective.
   Nearly half of the respondents, 49 percent, said Dukakis should
remain in office during the presidential campaign while 40 percent
said he should resign and 11 percent had no definite opinion on the
question. Dukakis campaign aides have said repeatedly that he will
not resign before the election.
   ``People in Massachusetts are obviously disappointed in the way
their governor is running the state and they're taking it out on
him,'' said KRC pollster Gerry Chervinsky.
   While Republicans delighted in the results, Dukakis partisans
said they viewed the numbers more as a referendum on his handling
of recent state troubles than a fair assessment of his strength
against Bush in the presidential contest.
   Corrigan said Dukakis' state operation has just begun its
grass-roots organizing, an effort being led by many of those who
helped Dukakis win nearly 70 percent of the vote in his 1986
re-election bid. ``I'm not worried one bit,'' he said.
   ``Momma said there'd be days like this,'' said Goldman. ``Any
attempt to take this and make a relation between how November is
going to come out is ridiculous. But it is a nice way of sending
the message to dad that he better as hell spend some time looking
at the kid back home.''
</TEXT>
