<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-PlaneCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0720 09-01 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Plane Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>21 People Reported Dead After Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE death toll, CORRECT spelling of
Bandeirante, ADD details, no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ARTEAGA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 21 people aboard a twin-engine
commuter airplane were killed when it crashed in the mountains of
the western Sierra Madre range, rescuers at the scene said Thursday.
   Rain and clouds caused by Hurricane Kristy delayed the trek
through the rocky, heavily forested terrain.
   ``There are no survivors,'' said a federal aviation inspector in
Mexico City of Wednesday's crash. He was quoting officials at the
airport in the Pacific coast port of Lazaro Cardenas.
   The inspector, who asked that his name not be used, said the
plane carried 21 people _ three crew members and 18 passengers, not
17 as reported earlier in the day.
   Gen. Carmelo Teran, chief of staff of the 21st military zone,
said the wreckage and bodies were found within a radius of about 50
yards. He spoke by telephone from Morelia, capital of Michoacan
state.
   Aviation officials said the Brazilian-made Bandeirante aircraft
of the Aerofederal line disappeared after leaving Uruapan, 185
miles west of Mexico City, on the 100-mile flight to Lazaro
Cardenas.
   Aerofederal is a government-owned operation that carries cargo
and also serves regional passenger routes.
   Most of the passengers were from Uruapan. The crash site was
about 80 miles south of the city and near Arteaga, a town in
Michoacan about 210 miles southwest of Mexico City.
   A helicopter of the Federal Electricity Commission spotted the
wreckage at 9 p.m. Wednesday, but helicopters could not get into
the area again until late Thursday morning.
   Gen. Teran, who sent in a company of about 100 soldiers, said
the plane apparently crashed at the juncture of two mountains, La
Calera y El Fraile.
   ``Helicopters cannot land because of the forest,'' he said.
``They are clearing trees so they can land.''
   He said the site was three to four miles from the road and the
climb took between two and three hours.
   It is about 9 miles from Arteaga ``to where they leave the
vehicles, then they climb the hill,'' said Jesus Gutierrez, an
assistant to Arteaga's mayor. ``There are lots of rocks.''
   Francisco Javier Flores, city secretary of Lazaro Cardenas, said
Kristy lashed the area for two days and rain had fallen for about
four days.
   Adalberto Mandes, director of the Uruapan airport, said the
Lazaro Cardenas airport had no radar or communications facilities
that could have helped controllers track the plane.
</TEXT>
