<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Barricade     09-01 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barricade,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Use Battering Ram and Stun Gun to Remove Armed 65-Year-Old
Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took tear gas, a SWAT team, a battering
ram and a electric stun gun Thursday to remove a 65-year-old woman
from her home, where she had been holed up for three days, shooting
at police and slightly wounding the chief's brother.
   ``I think they had to do this because the old lady had a gun.
It's terrible,'' said neighbor Bang Lee, looking at a gaping hole
left in the neat house by the battering ram.
   The woman, Barbara Maxson, had lived in the house on the city's
south side for more than 20 years. She barricaded herself inside
Monday afternoon after arguing with her daughter.
   She began shooting when officers entered her house about 4 a.m.
Thursday after firing tear gas inside, said police spokesman Lt.
Fred Nixon.
   She was found in a bathtub, clutching a pistol and holding a
blanket over her head to block the tear gas fumes, Nixon said.
   Officers shot her with a Taser stun gun, which shoots a dart
that emits an electrical charge, temporarily disabling the person,
Nixon said. She was taken to Torrance Memorial Medical Center for
psychiatric observation, he said.
   The brother of Police Chief Daryl Gates, Capt. Stephen Gates,
was treated at another hospital after a bullet grazed his head as
he approached the house Wednesday to talk to Mrs. Maxson, Nixon
said.
   ``It does underscore that when someone is armed and decides for
whatever reasons to make an armed stand, their age and sex doesn't
matter. Whatever makes them dangerous is their escape from reality
or their disregard for human life,'' said Cmdr. William Booth, the
chief's spokesman.
   The standoff began Monday when the woman's daughter tried to
coax Mrs. Maxson, who reportedly had a history of psychiatric
problems, from the house for psychiatric care, Nixon and neighbors
said.
   Mrs. Maxson allegedly pointed a gun at her daughter, who called
police. Police watched the house, then decided to take action
Wednesday after being warned by Mrs. Maxson's husband that there
were several weapons inside.
   The police department's special weapons and tactics team was
called in, then the department's armored car equipped with a
battering ram, which is usually used against the heavily fortified
homes of drug dealers.
   ``We used the ram because the house had fortified bars on the
window and furniture piled in front of the windows. There was no
other safe way for our officers to make safe entry,'' Nixon said.
   The woman fired at the battering ram, he said.
   The ram damaged the front of the green-and-brown, one-story
house, strewing a refrigerator and household items in the driveway.
</TEXT>
