<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AluminumHoax     09-01 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aluminum Hoax,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Janitor Collects Thousands of Can Tabs, But All In Vain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Arvin gathered thousands of pull
tabs from aluminum cans to help people suffering from kidney
failure, only to learn what other would-be do-gooders have learned
before: that the tabs are worthless.
   The 53-year-old janitor broke the tabs from countless aluminum
cans and persuaded about 100 colleagues at the auto plant where he
works to do the same. He even went to Texas to get the tabs from
4,000 aluminum cans in a nephew's collection.
   He believed the tabs could be cashed in for time on a dialysis
machine for patients with kidney failure, but when he tried to
redeem them, officials of Bethany Medical Center and the National
Kidney Foundation told that no such program existed.
   ``I really wanted to help these unfortunate people,'' he said.
``I wanted to take pictures of the patients and publish them in our
company newspaper to get more people interested.
   ``But then I learned that the tabs weren't going where I thought
they were going,'' he said. ``I could have had 500 people saving
those tabs. Now I'm left wondering what to do next.''
   The stories that aluminum tabs can buy a kidney patient some
time on a dialysis machine ``are completely untrue,'' Gigi
Poliposki, communications director for the National Kidney
Foundation in New York, told The Kansas City Times. ``Hundreds of
thousands of tabs have been collected by people, and our chapters
nationwide receive hundreds of calls every day from people
wondering how they can use them to help patients.''
   ``We have tried to trace the source of the rumors but with
absolutely no luck,'' she said.
   Ms. Poliposki said bogus or misguided information about the
``tab program'' had been very specific, with posters appearing in
libraries, school classrooms and buildings where civic groups meet.
   In response to the hoax, the National Kidney Foundation and the
Reynolds Aluminum Recycling Co. have started a program called
``Keep Tabs on Your Cans.''
   Under the program, people can take aluminum cans, pie plates,
foil, frozen dinner trays or other aluminum products to a Reynolds
recycling center and request that payment go to the kidney
foundation. A company spokesman said that 38 cents was being paid
for each pound of aluminum, although that price is subject to
change.
</TEXT>
