<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel     09-01 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0881</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Official: PLO Is Palestinians' National Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Foreign Ministry official said
Thursday that Israel should accept that the Palestine Liberation
Organization represents the Palestinian people, prompting calls by
right-wing politicians for his resignation.
   Despite his colleague's comments, a Foreign Ministry spokesman
said the government still refuses to have any contact with the PLO,
which it regards as a terrorist organization.
   Avraham Tamir, director-general of the Foreign Ministry, also
suggested Israel should negotiate with PLO-backed Palestinians in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``I certainly stress that for the Palestinians this (the PLO) is
their movement, and it should be accepted as a fact,'' said Tamir,
speaking from Washington in an interview with Israel radio.
   Tamir, a senior Israeli diplomat, helped negotiate Israel's 1979
peace accord with Egypt.
   The radio quoted Tamir as saying that for the Palestinians,
there can be no substitute for the PLO.
   Tamir said rifts within the PLO will probably prevent it from
recognizing Israel and renouncing terror, two of the conditions
imposed by the United States for accepting the PLO as a partner in
the peace process.
   However, Tamir said, the PLO should give its blessing to direct
talks between Israel and Palestinian representatives from the
occupied territories.
   The PLO should ``not prevent local leaders in the territories
from discussing with us interim arrangements that will quiet down
the situation and pave way for (political) process,'' Tamir said.
   His remarks created a storm of controversy. The right-wing Likud
bloc led by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir demanded that Tamir be
immediately returned from Washington.
   Tamir is in the United States to prepare a visit of Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres later this month.
   ``No doubt, he has seriously violated the government's policy,''
said Shamir aide Yossi Ahimeir. ``We expect his superiors or
superior (Peres) to take action.''
   Ahimeir emphasized that Tamir did not speak on behalf of the
Israeli government, adding: ``There's a wide consensus in the
government and the public that there should be no negotiations with
this terror group.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said in a statement that
Israel has not changed its standing policy.
   ``Our position has been and will remain that as long as the PLO
does not recognize Israel, accept the U.N. resolutions 242 and 338
and stop terror, we shall continue to see it as a terrorist group
with which there should be no contact whatsoever,'' it said.
   The U.N. Security Council resolutions assert Israel's right to
exist within secure borders.
   Peres, leader of the left-wing Labor party, declined comment on
Tamir's statement.
   ``I'm not sure he has said it. We have to check what he said
exactly, and then we shall pass judgment,'' Peres said.
   Yuval Neeman, leader of the right-wing Tehiya Party, said
through a spokesman that Tamir should resign immediately.
   In another development, the accidental shooting of two Israeli
soldiers by a U.S.-born Jewish settler fueled a stormy debate
Thursday over the use of force by Israeli civilians in the occupied
territories.
   Left-wing legislator Ran Cohen blamed Shamir in part for the
shooting, saying the prime minister's calls for less restrictive
open-fire orders set the stage for settler vigilante acts.
   But Ronni Milo of the Likud bloc lashed out at the critics. They
are ``ready to abandon Jews to stones, firebombs and pogroms,'' the
daily Yediot Ahronot quoted Milo as saying.
   The shooting occurred Wednesday night near the West Bank
settlement of Efrat south of Jerusalem after a firebomb exploded
about 20 yards from the car of settler Gedalia Becker.
   Becker fired 11 shots from his pistol and struck two soldiers
who were also chasing the firebomb thrower. One soldier was wounded
in the stomach and lost a kidney, Israel radio said. The second
soldier was wounded in the leg.
   Becker was questioned by police and released on bail, but police
confiscated his weapon.
   On Tuesday, Shamir told settlers he supported a change in policy
to permit civilians and soldiers to open fire on Arab
stone-throwers without shooting warning rounds first.
   In other developments Thursday:
   _ About 110,000 students in the Gaza Strip returned to school
after their summer vacation, and leaflets distributed by the Moslem
fundamentalist group Islamic Jihad urged them not to stage
anti-Israeli demonstrations during class hours.
   Military government officals ordered schools in the West Bank to
remain closed for at least another month, saying they have been the
focus of anti-Israeli violence.
   _ Three Supreme Court judges toured the Ketziot detention camp
in the southern Negev Desert where 2,700 Palestinians are being
held, most of them for up to six months without charges. The visit
followed complaints by 17 detainees about prison conditions, such
as lack of water and exposure to the hot desert sun.
   _ Hundreds of Palestinian women demonstrated at the Red Cross
building in Gaza City to protest conditions at Ketziot. ``They took
my son away 75 days ago, and I don't know whether he is alive or
dead,'' said Mudheya Fauzi, the mother of a detainee. ``I am
begging authorities to close this prison.''
</TEXT>
