<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirShow 1stLd-Writethru a0706 09-01 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Grounds Planes for a Day; Rescue Work Criticized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with Italian stunt team's future
flights limited to military ceremonies</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO kept its jets out of West
German skies Thursday in memory of victims of the Ramstein air show
disaster, and an expert on treating burns said the quality of
rescue work had been ``a scandal.''
   West German officials gave the first breakdown by nationality of
the dead and injured in the fiery tragedy Sunday, when three
Italian air force jets collided and one crashed into the crowd at
the Ramstein U.S. Air Force base.
   The Bild newspaper reported that some children who died had
``such bad burns their parents couldn't even recognize them. That
happened to a boy of about 13, who died in Offenbach with his face
burned beyond recognition.''
   A badly burned man died early Thursday, raising the death count
to 49, said Juergen Dietzen, spokesman for Rhineland-Palatinate
state where Ramstein is located. He said the U.S. Air Force count
of 52 dead was ``incorrect.''
   He said 40 of the dead had been identified: 33 West Germans, two
Americans, a Dutch citizen and one from France, and the three
Italian pilots involved in the collision. He did not release any
names.
   A U.S. Air Force statement Thursday said the 9-year-old son of
an American woman who died in the tragedy also had been killed.
   It identified him as Joshua Frymyer, ``the son of Pfc. Genevieve
Riggs who also died in the accident. The child is survived by his
father, Michael D. Frymyer of Lewistown, Pa.'' The Air Force
reported the death of Mrs. Riggs, 36, on Wednesday.
   She and her husband, Sgt. Myron Riggs, were with the U.S. Army's
110th Military Police Company in Pirmasens, West Germany. Sgt.
Riggs was among the injured and has been returned to the United
States for treatment.
   Dietzen also said four of the injured had not been identified
because they were in hospitals ``unable to communicate due to the
severity of their injuries'' and 168 other people still were
hospitalized.
   His breakdown of the 168 was 144 Germans, 16 Americans, two
Britons and one each from France, Italy, Belgium, Portugal, Africa
and the Philippines. He did not name the African country.
   A leading West German expert on burns said emergency crews
delivered many victims to hospitals incapable of treating serious
fire wounds.
   ``The organizational handling of the catastrophe ... was a
scandal and an unbelievable failure of those responsible,'' said
Leo Koslowski, former director of the Tuebingen University Surgical
Clinic. He spoke to reporters in Stuttgart.
   ``I find it unimaginable that none of the victims were
immediately brought to the highly modernized treatment centers in
Aachen and Berlin,'' he said.
   Wolfgang Herbig, director of the Kaiserslautern hospital where
many victims were taken, said a day earlier he felt there were not
enough ``mobile medical teams'' available at the air show.
   Rhineland-Palatinate officials have defended the rescue efforts
and praised the cooperation between Americans and Germans.
   Hesse state radio said several people had filed criminal
complaints with local prosecutors against Defense Minister Rupert
Scholz and the air show organizers for alleged negligent
manslaughter, according to Hesse state radio.
   Offices that process financial claims for damages against NATO
forces have added personnel to deal with an expected surge, the ZDF
television network said.
   In Rome, the Italian air force said Thursday the aerobatic team
that performed at the Ramstein air show will participate only at
military ceremonies in the immediate future.
   The air force also said in a statement that the participation of
the team known as the ``Frecce Tricolori'' (Tri-color Arrows) would
be limited to traditional flyovers with the planes trailing
tri-colored smoke.
</TEXT>
