<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Blackout, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Failure Blacks Out Half of Greece</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with power partially restored and explosion causing
blackout, CORRECTS with no problems in subway, details. No pickup.
^By KERIN HOPE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power failure blacked out Athens and most of
southern Greece on Thursday night, snarling traffic in the capital
and knocking out radio and television.
   However, power was restored to parts of Athens later in the
evening.
   Industry Ministry officials said the failure was caused by an
explosion in a switch at an electricity substation near the
northern town of Larissa. The cause was not immediately known.
   The damaged switch knocked out power to three of the four cables
serving the area south of Larissa.
   The power was restored by later in the evening to outlying
districts of Athens and some areas of the city center.
   Police said there were no immediate reports of looting.
   Public Power Co. officials said it would be hours before the
power was completely restored.
   State-run radio and television went off the air at first.
However, the radio returned to the air 40 minutes later and urged
Athenians to remain calm.
   Police earlier said an undetermined number of people were
stranded on the city's subway line. However, a spokesman for the
system said later that it operates on a different power grid and
was not affected by the blackout.
   There was no immediate word on how many people might have been
trapped in elevators by the blackout, which occurred as many
Athenians were going home for dinner.
   Traffic lights in Athens were knocked out, causing huge traffic
jams in the city of 3.5 million people.
   The Athens airport operated normally throughout the blackout.
   A doctor said the city's hospitals were operating on backup
generators.
</TEXT>
