<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador     09-01 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austerity Draws Protests from Powerful Left</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS CISTERNAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protest mushroomed Thursday against
austerity measures imposed by new President Rodrigo Borja to
correct what he called ``economic chaos'' caused by the previous
government.
   Bus and taxi drivers in the capital of Quito halted work,
forcing thousands to walk to their jobs, and Ecuador's most
powerful labor federation threatened a general strike.
   Borja, a moderate leftist who took office Aug. 10, put an
economic emergency package into effect Wednesday, doubling the
price of gasoline, devaluing currency 35.5 percent and tightening
exchange controls.
   He said harsh measures were required because former President
Leon Febres Cordero, a controversial conservative, tried to
sabotage the new government by lying about key economic statistics
and purposely running up a huge deficit.
   The government also announced an increase in the minimum monthly
wage of $42. But leftist labor leaders rejected it and demanded an
increase to $77.
   ``These measures are a hard strike against the poor. They are
criminal,'' said Edgar Ponce, spokesman for the communist-led
United Front of Laborers, said of the austerity program.
   Ponce said directors of the federation may set a date next week
for a general strike. During his four-year term, Febres Cordero
faced seven nationwide strikes, which affected the majority of
Ecuador's work force of more than three million.
   Febres Cordero, a political enemy of Borja, has denied
attempting to derail the new government. Borja won the presidency
in May, defeating populist candidate Abdala Bucaram. Cordero was
not eligible to run for re-election.
   Febres Cordero said on leaving office that the 1986 collapse of
world prices for oil, Ecuador's principal export, and a devastating
earthquake a year later pitched the nation into the ``crisis of the
century.''
   Borja said the previous government spurred inflation, expected
to hit 60 percent this year, compared to 32.7 percent in 1987, by
deliberately running a spending deficit of 16 percent. He said
accurate figures on the growing $11 billion foreign debt and
declining dollar reserves were deliberately withheld.
   ``With an emergency economic program we hope to bring these
grave disorders under control within 12 months,'' Borja said in an
official communique.
   The devaluation affects the official exchange rate, which went
from 250 sucres to 390 sucres to the dollar.
</TEXT>
