<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Soviet     09-01 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Soviet,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China and Soviet Union End Cambodian Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China and the Soviet Union ended five days of
talks on the Cambodian conflict Friday but fell short of resolving
their differences, the official Xinhua News Agency reported.
   The meeting marked the first time China, the chief backer of
anti-Vietnam resistance forces in Cambodia, and the Soviet Union,
the main supporter of Vietnam, have met specifically to discuss how
to bring an end to the 9-year-old conflict.
   The meeting also has been seen as a crucial step in normalizing
long-strained relations between Beijing and Moscow and paving the
way for the first Chinese-Soviet summit in 29 years.
   On Thursday, China's Foreign Ministry spokesman Jin Guihua said
the two sides ``stood for a fair and reasonable settlement to the
Kampuchean (Cambodian) question by political means and expressed
their willingness to do their best to promote the attainment of
this goal.
   ``The meeting also shows that the two sides find common ground
as well as differences,'' he said.
   Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev and China's Deputy
Foreign Minister Tian Zengpei headed the delegations.
   Soviet officials were not immediately available for comment on
the talks.
   The brief Xinhua dispatch said little except to quote Tian as
saying the two sides had ``conducted candid discussions, done
useful work and found some common points during their working
meeting.''
   Jin, speaking at a weekly briefing, would not provide details of
the talks or the remaining differences.
   But he said the talks focused on ``how to urge Vietnam to pull
its troops out of Kampuchea as soon as possible.''
   Jin said the meeting ``enhanced mutual understanding and was
beneficial'' and ``we hope the meeting can be conducive to the
improvement of the relations between the two countries.'' But he
would not say whether it had improved the possibility for a
Chinese-Soviet summit.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev has called for a summit to end
nearly three decades of enmity between the two countries, but China
insists that the Soviet Union must first persuade Vietnam to leave
Cambodia.
   One sign that sharp differences remain on the Cambodian question
was a strongly worded commentary by Xinhua which blasted Vietnam
for stepping up the ``Vietnamization'' of Cambodia and trying to
create a puppet government in Phnom Penh.
   The commentary, appearing in major dailies Thursday, charged
that Vietnam, which has pledged to withdraw 50,000 troops this
year, has ``put tens of thousands of its troops in the uniform of
the puppet forces'' of the Hanoi-backed Hun Sen government in Phnom
Penh.
   It said, ``the Phnom Penh regime's troops have expanded to
70,000 men within a year and the militia has grown to tens of
thousands, surpassing the total number of the three Kampuchean
resistance forces.''
   The news agency claimed that Vietnam has installed ``trusted
followers'' in the Hun Sen leadership and that there are now at
least 700,000 Vietnamese migrants in Cambodia.
   It repeated that China understands concerns that the
Beijing-backed Khmer Rouge, the most powerful resistance force,
will return to power but insisted that Hun Sen's domination of a
future government is ``a more acute danger.''
   The Khmer Rouge between 1975 and 1978 killed hundreds of
thousands of people in an attempt to return Cambodia to a totally
agrarian society. Vietnam has linked its withdrawal to assurances
the Khmer Rouge will not be able to return to power.
   China says Vietnam's withdrawal must come first and supports a
four-party coalition headed by resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk and including the Hun Sen forces, the Khmer Rouge,
Sihanouk's group and a third resistance faction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
