<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--RadioFreeEurope     09-01 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Radio Free Europe,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Director for Radio Free Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A. Ross Johnson, a political scientist and
specialist in East-West relations, has been named director of Radio
Free Europe, the U.S.-financed radio system that broadcasts to
Eastern Europe, it was announced Thursday.
   Johnson, a senior political scientist of the Rand Corp., will
succeed Gregory Wierzynski at Radio Free Europe headquarters in
Munich, West Germany. Wierzynski has resigned to return to the
United States, said spokeswoman Jane Lester.
   Johnson, 49, has authored and directed many studies on Eastern
Europe and the Soviet Union, said E. Eugene Pell, president of the
radio system's parent organization, Washington-based RFE-Radio
Liberty Inc.
   From Munich, Radio Free Europe broadcasts information and news
in nine languages almost around the clock to Poland,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Bulgaria, Romania and the Soviet Republics
of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania. Radio Liberty, also financed by
U.S. congressional appropriations, broadcasts to the rest of the
Soviet Union in several Soviet languages.
</TEXT>
