<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-01 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain and More Rain for Large Sections of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell across large sections of the nation Thursday as a
slow-moving cold front brought showers and thunderstorms to the
upper Mississippi Valley and Colorado and showers moved eastward
from Kansas into Oklahoma and the Texas Panhandle.
   Rainfall of more than an inch was reported as the cold front
moved across western and central parts of Minnesota Thursday
morning.
   Showers traveled slowly from western into central Kansas and
extended across western Oklahoma into the Texas Panhandle. The
National Weather Service said Eva, Okla., in the Panhandle measured
over 3 inches of rain by Thursday morning. Amarillo, Texas, had 1{
inches in 24 hours.
   Winds became gusty along the front in Colorado, with northwest
winds reaching to near 50 mph at Colorado Springs.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued to be widespread along
coastal areas from the southern Atlantic region through the Gulf
Coast and across Florida. Over 1\ inches of rain was logged at
Apalachicola, Fla.
   Significant rainfall was also reported during the six hours
ending at 2 p.m. EDT at Gage, Okla., Charleston, S.C., Eau Claire,
Wis., Brunswick and Savannah, Ga., and Jacksonville, Fla.
   Temperatures were in the 70s and 80s across much of the nation.
Readings were in the 90s over northeast and south-central Texas and
over central Florida. Temperatures in the desert Southwest ranged
from the middle 90s to 105 degrees.
   The low in the nation early Thursday was 30 degrees at West
Yellowstone, Mont.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at Laramie, Wyo., to 110 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   For Friday, a cold front was forecast from the Great Lakes into
the central Plains scattering showers and thunderstorms from the
Great Lakes through the Ohio Valley into the middle Mississippi and
lower Missouri Valleys. Scattered showers were also expected from
the southern Atlantic coast through the Tennessee and lower
Mississippi valleys to the Gulf Coast and Florida. Showers and
thunderstorms were expected to be widespread over the southern high
Plains and from southern Mississippi through northern Georgia into
South Carolina.
   High temperatures in the 80s or 90s were predicted across much
of the nation. Highs were expected in the 70s from the northern
Plains through the upper Mississippi Valley and across much of
Maine. Highs between 100 and 110 degrees were forecast from the
desert Southwest into the valleys of California. Record-breaking
highs were anticipated from interior Oregon into southern
Washington state and the southern half of Idaho as temperatures
were expected to reach the mid 90s to near 105 degrees.
</TEXT>
