<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0656 09-01 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Defends His Record on Plant-Closing Legislation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs to report on New Republic article about Stuart
Spencer, give Quayle response.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle, saying ``I'm still
ticking,'' toured a Timex plant Thursday, courting the blue-collar
vote, and found himself defending his record on controversial
plant-closing legislation.
   In a day scheduled mostly as a series of photo opportunities,
the Republican vice presidential nominee shook hands with workers
at the watch plant, toured a day care center at a children's
hospital and then traveled to Mississippi to watch a high-school
football practice.
   At a news conference here, Quayle was asked about his opposition
to the plant-closing bill, which requires manufacturers with 100 or
more employees to give worker 60 days' notice before shutting the
facility. Quayle was a leading Senate opponent of the legislation,
which was supported by a substantial portion of the public,
according to polls.
   ``They should give notice,'' Quayle said. ``It ought to be much
more than 60 days.''
   But Quayle said he favored a voluntary plan, that would have
offered employers incentives to participate. As a matter of
principle, however, he said companies should go along with such a
program.
   ``Any CEO (chief executive officer) that doesn't give notice,
should be fired on the spot,'' Quayle said.
   The plant-closing legislation was cited by President Reagan as
the reason he vetoed a sweeping trade bill earlier this year. The
plant provision was then passed as a separate piece of legislation
that Reagan allowed to become law without his signature.
   Quayle said a legislative compromise that would have allowed
more flexibility in the bill had been agreed on by the principal
drafters of the bill, including Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, Quayle's
Democratic counterpart. But the compromise fell apart at the last
minute, Quayle said, suggesting that Bentsen was a major reason.
   ``He was part of it,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle said he was not concerned about people who say he is not
qualified to be president if the situation arose.
   ``We still have a long time in this campaign ... By Election Day
there will be no doubt.''
   Quayle toured a Timex plant, where he joked: ``Timex takes a
lickin' but keeps on ticking'. I know what John Cameron Swayze
meant.''
   ``I'm still ticking. I'm going to continue to talk about the
issues. It is an upbeat campaign,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle also toured the employee day care center at Arkansas
Children's Hospital, where he made made a pitch for George Bush's
approach to day care _ giving parents tax credits for day care but
without imposing stringent federal regulations on how day care
programs should be conducted.
   ``We don't need a massive federal bureaucracy to come in and
tell us how to run our day care,'' he said.
   Quayle was also asked about a forthcoming article in The New
Republic which said that a public relations firm run by Quayle's
campaign manager, Stuart Spencer, was paid $350,000 in 1984-85 to
lobbyist for Panamanian ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   According to advance copies of the article, the firm lobbied
against drug investigations of Noriega and defended him against
allegations of killing former president, Dr. Hugo Spadafora, in
September 1985.
   Quayle said he did not ``know about the specifics'' of the
story. He said he only met the long-time Republican strategist when
Spencer came in to handle his campaign after work in both Reagan
presidential campaigns.
   ``From my observation, Stuart Spencer is a political pro,''
Quayle said.
</TEXT>
