<HEAD>Raucous Scene in Congress As De La Madrid Delivers Final Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-10 pvs `Earlier in...parliamentary system.''' to
show that rightists did not walk out, ADD comment from them and
PRI, picks up graf 11 pvs `There were....' SUBS final graf with one
graf with television showing walkout.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto MO2</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Miguel de la Madrid's final report
to the Mexican Congress was interrupted Thursday by opposition
shouts of ``Fraud,'' demonstrations in protest of the July
elections, and a tumultuous opposition walkout.
   The raucous scene, which included physical attacks on one
opposition leader, was unprecedented in the history of the Congress.
   In his 3{-hour speech, De la Madrid sought to sum up a six-year
administration that inherited massive economic problems and a
corrupt political system. He said it was a time of necessary
sacrifice that hurt Mexicans, but that his reforms prepared Mexico
for the 21st century.
   De la Madrid spoke to a breakdown of congressmen such as no
Mexican president has faced in the 60 years the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) has held power _ one where the opposition
has nearly half the seats. Even so, the opposition claims the PRI
maintained its grip only through massive cheating.
   Near the end of the speech, Sen. Porfirio Munoz Ledo led a
walkout by leftist Democratic Front delegates amid cries of
``Traitor!'' and ``Get out, Judas!'' from PRI delegates. Munoz
Ledo, who was once head of the PRI, was kicked in the back and hit
in the neck as he left.
   ``We are walking out in protest because they refused to let the
voice of the oppositon be heard,'' he said afterwards. De la
Madrid's speech was full of ``falsehoods and inaccuracies,'' he
said.
   Earlier in the speech, de la Madrid was interrupted for at least
five minutes by delegates chanting ``Fraud, fraud.'' Delegates of
the rightist National Action Party held up remains of what they
said were partly burned and void ballots.
   PRI deputies tried to shout down the opposition, clapping and
chanting ``Mexico, Mexico.''
   National Action members did not walk out, but leader Abel
Vincenio Tovar said the ruling party had packed the gallery. He
said spectators included a large military contingent.
   ``When the ruling party doesn't have the backing of the peopl,
they have to bring their own supporters,'' he said.
   After the walkout, de la Madrid departed from his text to call
for tolerance ``even in the face of insults by our political
adversaries.''
   A presidential aide who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
protests might be new but were ``normal in any parliamentary
system,'' and Manuel Camacho Solis, general secretary of the PRI,
praised what he viewed as de la Madrid's coolness under fire.
   ``We condemn the intentions and tyrannies of the small group
that wanted to impose its anti-democratic practices on the
majority,'' Camacho Solis said in a statement.
   There were also interruptions as de la Madrid spoke of his
economic policy, which reduced government control of the economy,
encouraged domestic and foreign investment and sharply reduced
inflation.
   But Mexicans paid the price with a drastic reduction in buying
power and lifestyle as petroleum prices and the Mexican currency
collapsed.
   The austerity was needed, de la Madrid said, becase ``we had to
face and accept the fact that we would have to live within our
means.''
   ``The crisis we have lived through shook the very foundations of
our social structure,'' de la Madrid said. ``It is was though we
had run the rapids in the current of history. It was rough, but we
also made considerable progress.''
   The new Congress was the result of the political reforms
sponsored by de la Madrid, and he lashed out at opposition parties
that have criticized the electoral process and accused his
administration of abetting electoral fraud.
   ``(Political) pluralism is a vital sign of democracy,'' he said.
``and should never be a symptom of a divided or splintered nation.''
   Negotiations between the PRI and the opposition had made it
possible only two days ago to install the new Congress in time for
the de la Madrid's sixth and final state of the nation message. The
PRI holds 260 seats in the Chamber of Deputies, to 139 for the
leftist Democratic Front and 101 for the rightist National Action
Party.
   The PRI's stranglehold on power has been so strong that until
this year no opposition candidate had ever been elected to the
Senate. Now four of 64 Senators belong to the leftist opposition.
   The same fractious Congress must, in the next two months,
certify the election of De la Madrid's chosen successor, Carlos
Salinas de Gortari.
   Salinas, the PRI candidate, won barely more than 50 percent of
the popular vote. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the Democratic Front
candidate, took 31 percent in the official count, but claims he was
the actual winner.
   On other matters, de la Madrid said Mexico will continue its
fight against drug trafficking, and, in a clear reference to the
United States, added, ``we hope that everyone is doing their
part.'' Mexico, he said, cannot fight drugs successfully ``unless
the demand for drugs is combated in major centers of consumption.''
   De la Madrid said the problem of Mexico's foreign debt _ now at
$104 billion _ ``has not been resolved'' despite renegotiation and
the sale of Mexican government bonds.
   In a preview of what is expected to be Salinas' policy, de la
Madrid said Mexico must insist on ``greater joint responsibility
and understanding on the part of the creditors in order to achieve
a solution to the problem they helped to foster.''
   State-controlled Mexican television broadcast the entire speech,
illustrating passages with videotape. It at first showed protests
but no walkout, but the walkout itself was broadcast on later
programs.
</TEXT>
