<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Crash-Flight Aborted, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0762,0855</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Aborts Flight That One Day Earlier Had Ended In Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with five grafs to include aborted takeoff in Portland,
Ore., ADDS four grafs with details of Portland incident and Eastern
plane with cargo door ajar in Orlando, Fla.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for story slugged Crash-Flight 1141 on AM-News Digest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One day after Delta Flight 1141 crashed
on takeoff, the pilot of another Boeing 727 beginning the same
flight to Salt Lake City aborted takeoff because of an apparent
minor stall, officials said.
   Passengers, including six who had been among the survivors of
Wednesday's crash, were stunned when the captain brought the jet to
a halt and taxied it back to the terminal.
   ``We figured this would be the safest flight we could ever take
today,'' said passenger Louise Cox, of Baton Rouge, La., as she
waited to board another 727 for Salt Lake City. ``Evidently not.''
   In Portland, Ore., the pilot of a Delta Lockheed L-1011 aborted
takeoff Thursday at Portland International Airport after a faulty
cockpit warning light indicated an engine was overheating, an
airline spokesman said.
   The Texas flight, scheduled to depart at 8:31 a.m., finally left
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport more than two hours late.
The replacement plane landed at Salt Lake City without incident.
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said the type of problem that
apparently occurred Thursday would not have necesssarily forced a
pilot to abort the takeoff.
   The pilot, whose name was not released, was probably being extra
cautious because of the crash Wednesday that claimed 13 lives,
Berry said. Nealy 100 other passengers and crew members survived.
   Speaking from Delta's Atlanta headquarters, Berry said the pilot
believed his problem stemmed from ``what is called a compressor
stall. There was a crosswind blowing across the runway. That can
interrupt the smoothness of the airflow that goes into the engine,
creating a temporary loss of power.''
   Delta maintenance crews were unable to find anything wrong with
the aircraft, Berry said.
   Thursday's flight carried 102 passengers plus a crew of seven,
according to Delta spokesman Henry Conley in Dallas. Conley said
that to his knowledge, all on board the aborted flight got on the
replacement plane.
   Shaken passengers waiting to board that plane described their
experience.
   ``It was a routine takeoff until we got almost to the end of the
runway,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Don Burkhalter of Jackson,
Miss. ``Then we heard what sounded like bumps and the pilot
decelerated. He said there was a problem with the `compressors.'''
   ``The captain said, and this is a quote, `It's just one of those
things.' We just laughed.'' But it was nervous laughter, said
Burkhalter, who was on his way to California with his wife.
   Waiting to board Thursday's flight _ before it was aborted _ a
survivor of Wednesday's crash talked of the difficulty of getting
on Flight 1141 a day after it ended in tragedy.
   ``It's pretty hard,'' said Ronald Black, 30, of West Monroe, La.
``You've got to do it sometime. Can't live in Dallas.'' He said he
opted to continue his trip West because ``I've either got to go
home or go hunting. I've got to fly either way, so I might as well
go hunting.''
   Berry said that when the pilot decided to stop the takeoff as
the plane rolled down the runway, the plane had speeded up to
roughly 25 mph, ``which is extremely slow.''
   ``The airplanes get up to 100 knots (115 mph) before they become
airborne,'' he said. ``He did not get the proper readings from one
of his engines. He decided to go back to the gate.''
   Ordinarily, a pilot dealing with such a minor stall would
``simply increase thrust to see if everything continued to perform
right,'' Berry said. ``But based on the incident that happened
yesterday, the captain was extremely cautious and elected simply to
come back to the gate and let maintenance look at the engine.''
   He emphasized that pilots ``have got to go by their years of
experience'' and can abort flights ``if they don't like what they
feel, if they've just got a gut feeling.''
   The Delta jet in Portland, Ore., never left the runway and
braked to a stop. There were no injuries among the 190 passengers
and crew on board, said David Zielke, Delta's Portland district
marketing manager.
   Mechanics in Portland inspected the L-1011's engines and
determined they had not overheated and that the warning light was
faulty. Flight 51 originated in Atlanta and was en route to Tokyo.
   Also Thursday, in Orlando, Fla., an Eastern Airlines Boeing 727
en route to Philadelphia turned back shortly after takeoff when the
pilot felt vibration from an open cargo door, an airline spokesman
said.
   Flight 832, with 101 passengers and a crew of seven, returned
safely to Orlando International Airport, said Eastern spokesman
George Owen in Miami. No one was injured and no luggage was lost.
</TEXT>
