<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0786 09-01 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0786,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Lifts Ban on Political Exiles</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs with Isabel Allende arriving in Chile,
quotes, REVISES number of exiled affected upward, picks up graf 11
pvs `The Roman...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet announced
Thursday he has lifted a ban on the return from exile of hundreds
of leftists, including some of his fiercest Marxist critics.
   Within hours of the announcement, a formerly exiled daughter of
Marxist former President Salvador Allende, whose elected government
was ousted by Pinochet in a bloody 1973 coup, arrived in Santiago.
   Four hours after Pinochet's announcement, Isabel Allende, 44,
arrived at Santiago's international airport on a flight from Buenos
Aires. She had planned the trip days earlier as a challenge to ban
against her return, but Pinochet's announcement allowed for her
re-entry to Chile without problems.
   Asked why she returned, she told reporters at the airport:
``Because it's my legitimate right.''
   She said her mother, Hortensia Bussi, the exiled widow of
Allende, also plans to return. ``We are going to prepare a grand
entrance, through the front door, as we've always said.''
   Allende's widow Hortensia said in a telephone interview in
Mexico City after learning of Pinochet's announcement: ``I am very
happy to be returning to my country. I left in the spring and I
will return in the spring.'' Winter is now ending in the Southern
Hemisphere.
   Mrs. Allende and her daughter Carmen have lived in Mexico since
the coup.
   It was the first time she had stepped on Chilean soil since she,
her mother and other members of Allende's immediate family took
refuge in the Mexican Embassy the day of the coup, departing on a
flight specially arranged by Mexico's president at the time, Luis
Echeverria. Allende died in a siege of the government palace during
the takeover.
   Also Thursday, the leader of a 16-party opposition coalition
challenged Gen. Pinochet to a televised debate during the campaign
for the Oct. 5 referendum in which the president seeks voter
approval for another eight-year term.
   Pinochet said in announcing the measure to Chilean reporters:
``The prohibitions are lifted. All of them. I have spoken this
morning with the interior minister and have given instructions with
respect to exile that totally solves this problem.''
   It was the latest of several relaxations in political
restrictions before the ``yes or no'' presidential referendum.
Pinochet's name will be the only one on the ballot.
   Interior Ministry Subsecretary Alberto Cardemil told reporters
the lifting of exile applies to all government opponents previously
banned from returning. He said they were 430 in number.
   The Roman Catholic Church human rights agency puts the total
political exiles at 504, but its list includes Chileans who changed
nationality in order to establish foreign residence or obtain work.
   Prominent exiles affected include Luis Corvalan, a former
senator and leader of the outlawed Communist Party who lives in
Moscow; Carlos Altamirano, a former leader of Allende's Socialist
Party; Anselmo Sule, a leading figure in the International
Socialist Movement, and Volodia Teitelboim, a ranking Communist
Party official.
   After taking power, Pinochet's military government arrested
thousands of leftist opponents and exiled them. According to police
figures, more than 9,000 have been authorized to return since 1982.
   Last week, Pinochet lifted all states of emergency for the first
time, and on Tuesday he won the formal backing of fellow military
commanders as the sole candidate in the upcoming referendum.
   Patricio Aylwin, president of the centrist Chrisitian Democratic
Party, the country's largest, and spokesman for the coalition
challenged Pinochet to the televised debate.
   ``An open and free debate is indispensable,'' he said, and would
enable Pinochet ``to contrast his ideas with those of the
opposition.''
</TEXT>
