<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0627 09-01 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0863</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swede Sits in for Perez de Cuellar at Deadlocked Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with accusations of cease-fire
violations. Pickup 5th graf pvs `Foreign ministers...'; ADDS 2
grafs to UPDATE with first Iraqi tanker completing trip through
through gulf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
left the deadlocked Iran-Iraq peace talks Thursday and put a
Swedish diplomat in charge, while the two belligerents accused each
other of violating the cease-fire.
   Iran accused Iraq of taking more than 750 Iranian troops
prisoner in attacks since the U.N.-sponsored cease-fire began Aug.
20. The Iraqi government said Iran continued setting up observation
posts and bunkers, moving troops close to the border and launching
gunboats into the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway.
   U.N. observers monitoring the truce have not reported any
serious violations by either side, only ``minor problems'' that
were resolved.
   Jan Eliasson, Sweden's U.N. ambassador, arrived in the Swiss
city from New York to continue Perez de Cuellar's work of seeking a
permanent peace after eight years of war that cost up to 1 million
lives.
   Perez de Cuellar introduced Eliasson to the Iranian and Iraqi
foreign ministers in separate meetings before departing for other
U.N. duties in Lisbon. He said he could return when necessary.
   Peace talks started eight days ago but have been stalled for six
days over troop withdrawal, navigation rights and the Shatt-al-Arab
waterway, which forms the southern border between the two nations
and is Iraq's only outlet to the sea.
   Foreign ministers Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran and Tariq Aziz of
Iraq have not met directly since their last formal session Aug. 26,
the day after the talks began. Negotiations have continued at a
lower level.
   ``We are working at the experts' level, not the level of
ministers,'' Perez de Cuellar said Thursday. ``We hope to
accelerate the pace as much as possible, but at the moment we are
honest brokers. We cannot impose anything on the parties.''
   ``The main problem is lack of confidence,'' he told reporters as
he turned over responsibility to Eliasson. ``It is impossible to
deal on the basis of distrust. It is sand and you cannot build on
sand.''
   Eliasson, 47, assumed the ambassador's post in March. He is an
expert on the Iran-Iraq war and made 12 trips to the Persian Gulf
as part of Sweden's earlier efforts to help the United Nations find
a settlement.
   At the news conference, he said: ``The gulf (of) distrust has
been very wide and we hope it will be becoming a little bit
smaller.''
   The secretary-general said Eliason would try to arrange a
meeting of the foreign ministers, but added: ``It is a very
difficult, complicated negotiation and it needs time.''.
   When talks began Aug. 25, five days after the cease-fire, Perez
de Cuellar wanted to announce timetables for troop withdrawal,
prisoner exchange and the work of a commission to determine which
side started the war.
   Stalemate came the next day, however, and he has been unable to
break it.
   Perez de Cuellar said Thursday he believes both sides ``honestly
are interested in finding a solution to the problem, but it takes
time for the parties ... to see which way they can achieve, with
assistance of the U.N., a compromise.''
   He described the two direct meetings as ``very helpful'' because
each side officially listened to the other. They spoke through
translators and the secretary-general, however, not directly to
each other.
   A three-point U.N. compromise would guarantee free navigation
for both nations in the Persian Gulf, withdrawal to internationally
recognized borders and an impartial study of conflicting positions
on the Shatt-al-Arab.
   International pressure appears to be building on Iraq to accept
early troop withdrawal.
   The five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ the
United States, Soviet Union, Britain, China and France _ support
the secretary-general and their representatives met with President
Saddam Hussein of Iraq on Wednesday.
   Iraq insists on freedom of navigation and wants Iran to stop
searching vessels bound for its ports. It also wants the U.N. to
have the Shatt-al-Arab dredged before a troop withdrawal.
   A 1975 treaty between Iraq and Iran draws the border down the
middle of the waterway, but the Iraqis says the agreement was
invalidated by the 1979 revolution that overthrew the late Shah
Mohammad Reza Pahlavi. Iraq now claims the entire waterway.
   Iran says the first item of business is withdrawal by Iraq from
territory it captured in offensives just before the cease-fire,
with clearing of the Shatt and other issues to be discussed
afterward.
   In South Yemen's port of Aden, the first Iraqi tanker to sail
through the the Persian Gulf and the Strait of Hormuz since the
cease-fire docked with 17,000 tons of Iraqi crude oil, South
Yemen's official news agency reported Thursday.
   The Ain Zalah, which arrived Wednesday, set sail from the
southern Iraqi port of Basra on Aug. 20, the day the cease-fire
went into effect, and took 11 days to reach Aden, the agency said.
</TEXT>
