<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrownHospitalized     09-01 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown Hospitalized,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Formerly Homeless Woman Back In Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who successfully fought the city's
attempt to confine her for mental illness has been hospitalized for
the second time since being released from a psychiatric ward
earlier this year.
   Joyce Brown, who also has used the name Billie Boggs, was
admitted to St. Clare's Hospital in Manhattan on Monday, but
neither the hospital nor her lawyers would say what was wrong with
her.
   Linda Greenough, a hospital spokeswoman, said Ms. Brown was
admitted for observation and was resting comfortably. She was
listed in stable condition. But Greenough said she could not
divulge the condition for which Ms. Brown was being treated.
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said he has been visiting Ms. Brown nightly and
that she feels fine.
   ``She's comfortable, she's in good spirits,'' he said. ``Last
night we watched the news together.''
   Ms. Brown, 40, who moved into the Traveler's Hotel in midtown
Manhattan after she was released from Bellevue Hospital's
psychiatric ward seven months ago, entered St. Clare's for a week
in May. Published reports said she had suffered a seizure, but
Siegel said he could not confirm that.
   She was the first person picked up last fall under Mayor Edward
I. Koch's plan to hospitalize some of the mentally ill homeless.
She was released when a judge ruled that city doctors, who
contended she was psychotic, could not force her to take medication
for the condition.
   Siegel said Ms. Brown, who had been living on an Upper East Side
sidewalk, has been unable to find a regular job or her own home.
   ``She had some job offers when she was first released, but they
didn't work out,'' he said.
   Siegel said Ms. Brown still is living in what is supposed to be
a transitional residence because she has been unable to find an
apartment in Manhattan.
</TEXT>
