<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Vietnam     09-01 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Hope to Bring Children Back From Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of congressmen left Thursday for
Vietnam to evaluate the country's need for emergency food supplies
and possibilities for increased U.S. contacts with the Hanoi
government.
   They also said they hope to return with several Vietnamese
children long separated from parents living in the United States.
   The delegation was headed by Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas,
chairman of the House Select Committee on Hunger.
   ``I plan to assess severe food shortages which threaten 3
million people, 40 percent of whom are children below age 14, all
on the brink of starvation,'' he said.
   Leland and Rep. Albert Bustamante, D-Texas, said they also plan
to discuss with Vietnamese officials the unfinished matter of
accounting for Americans still listed as missing in action and the
possible opening of a U.S. interests section in some friendly
country's Hanoi embassy.
   Bustamante said the delegation also plans to raise with Hanoi
officials the issue of Vietnam's 10-year occupation of Cambodia and
``will be looking for other potential openings in relations between
Vietnam and the United States.''
   Bustamante's office said the delegation will bring back two
Vietnamese children and their aunt to their family in Houston and a
third child to rejoin parents who settled in Virginia after fleeing
their homeland in 1975.
   Leland's office indicated their release could be uncertain.
   Other members of the delegation are Reps.: Gerald Solomon,
R-N.Y.; Kweisi Mfume, D-Md.; and Solomon Ortiz, D-Texas. Rep.
Stephen Solarz, a New York Democrat who chairs the Foreign Affairs
Committee's Asian and Pacific subcommittee, might join the group in
Bangkok, Thailand, before it arrives in Vietnam.
</TEXT>
