<DOCNO> AP880901-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 2222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Books     09-01 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Books,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>800 Formerly Banned Books Go on Public Display in Moscow Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Books by former Soviet officials who fell afoul of
Josef Stalin went on public display Thursday after decades of being
banned from library shelves, an official report said.
   However, other books, including some of ``Zionist'' or
anti-Semitic content, others promoting national strife and
pornography, remained off-limits to the general reading public, a
government official said.
   A total of 800 books were exhibited at the Lenin Library, the
nation's leading library, including works by victims of the late
dictator Stalin's political purges, generals who fought against the
establishment of Soviet power, and members of the provisional
government overthrown by the Bolsheviks in 1917 October Revolution,
according to the official news agency Tass.
   Tass said the books had been ``out of the reach of general
readers for decades.'' It said they were being transferred from the
library's restricted-access stocks to general use, where they would
be accessible to the general public.
   That move was another example of the increased tolerance
fostered by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign for
``glasnost,'' or greater openness. The drive has also brought about
judicial rehabilitation of Stalin foes like Bukharin and Kamenev,
who were convicted of spying in the 1930s and killed as ``enemies
of the people.'' Their books were among those on display.
   Last year, a commission was created to determine which banned
books should be transferred to public use in Soviet libraries. Its
head, Vladimir Solodin, is an official of the government agency
Glavlit, which is charged with screening the press to prevent the
publication of state secrets. It has acted in the past as chief
government censor.
   Tass quoted Solodin as saying the review commission would
conclude its work in October, and that ``about 500'' books would
remain in the restricted-access library stocks, down from 10,000
before.
   ``The books remaining there are, first of all, those of
anti-Semitic and Zionist content,'' Solodin said. ``There are other
books which propagandize national strife as well as pornographic
editions ....''
   He gave no titles or other details.
   In addition, Solodin said all works by Stalin's arch-foe Leon
Trotsky that had been published in periodicals were now in
open-access stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     09-01 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Allows 20,000 Kurdish Refugees From Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday that 20,000
Kurdish refugees have been allowed into Turkey from northeastern
Iraq, where Kurdish rebels said Baghdad has launched its biggest
offensive.
   Premier Turgut Ozal Wednesday more Kurds may be be permitted to
cross the border in coming days but that the influx will be limited.
   Diplomats in Baghdad reported Iraq has taken advantage of the
Aug. 20 cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with Iran to intensify
operations against the autonomy-seeking Kurds, who sided with the
Iranians.
   Iraqi forces, with tanks on the ground and with jets from the
air, were bombing the Kurdish region heavily and came within a few
miles of the Turkish border, the independent Hurriyet News Agency
reported Wednesday from the border province of Hakkari.
   There was no immediate report by the Iraqi government.
   Ozal, talking to reporters after a National Security Council
meeting where the Kurdish problem was discussed, said Turkey was
taking in the refugees on humanitarian grounds.
   But, he added, ``There is a limit to how many we can admit.''
   He did not cite a figure. A spokesman for the Kurdish Democratic
Party, one of the major guerrilla groups fighting for autonomy in
northern Iraq, told The Associated Press in Nicosia in a telephone
interview that Turkey would accept 30,000.
   The spokesman said Iraq launched an ``unprecedented'' offensive
Monday against 4,000 square miles of Kurdish-claimed territory.
   ``Heavy fighting is taking place between our forces and the
Iraqi army on all fronts'' and Iraqi forces are burning villages to
the ground, the spokesman said.
   Iran also has agreed to take in the refugees from Iraq, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported from Tehran where
Nuzhet Kandemir, undersecretary of the Turkish Foreign Ministry, is
holding talks with Iranian officials.
   Kandemir visited Iraq on Monday and Tuesday and informed sources
in Baghdad said he had complained about Iraq's use of chemical
weapons near the Turkish border against Kurdish rebels.
   In Geneva, U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said Wednesday the
world body was taking no action following allegations of the
chemical attacks, saying there was no independent confirmation. The
United Nations has condemned Iraq for use of chemical weapons
during the Iran-Iraq war.
   Turkey has its own Kurdish problem, with its military fighting a
4-year-old war with guerrillas of the Kurdish Labor Party, or PKK,
a Marxist group aiming to set up a separate Kurdish state in
Turkey's southeast provinces.
   An overwhelming majority of Turkey's estimated 10 million Kurds,
however.
   Turkey's Kurdish minority is the largest one of about 20 million
Kurds who live where borders of Iran, Iraq and Turkey converge.
There are also Kurdish enclaves in Syria and the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
