<DOCNO> AP880901-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Crash-Numbers     09-01 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Numbers,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Several Factors Led To Fluctuating Casualty Counts In Delta Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines' policy of not counting infants
on its passenger list and misinformation from the chaotic scene led
to fluctuations in the number of people reported killed in
Wednesday's jet crash, officials said.
   At least one infant was among the 13 passengers who died when
the Delta 727 crashed shortly after takeoff from Dallas-Fort Worth
Airport. Ninety-four passengers and crew members survived,
officials said.
   The number of dead fluctuated throughout the day, from seven to
15, down to nine, up to 11 and finally to 13. Bill Berry, a Delta
spokesman in Atlanta, said one reason for the discrepancies was
that officials weren't sure how many children under 2 years might
be on board.
   ``An infant does not buy a ticket, and if it does not buy a
ticket, so many times you are going to have a discrepancy in your
manifest count,'' Berry said.
   He said passengers don't normally notify ticket agents that they
plan to take an infant on board, since they are not required to pay.
   ``They'll just show up with an infant knowing they don't have to
buy a ticket,'' Berry said. ``They don't have to identify that they
have an infant with them.''
   At least three infants were on the jet Wednesday, he said. One
was among the dead, but the condition of the others was not
immediately known.
   Part of the problem Wednesday, Berry said, was that emergency
personnel requested 15 body bags _ leading Delta officials to give
out an erroneous casualty figure. Later fluctuations happened
because some victims died at hospitals.
   ``As you well know, in these types of situations, the numbers
often fluctuate until you can get various hospitals contacted,''
Berry said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
