<DOCNO> AP880901-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavajoAdoption     09-01 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navajo Adoption,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-Indian Couple Awarded Permanent Custody of Navajo Child</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUBA CITY, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tribal court Wednesday awarded a
non-Indian couple permanent custody of a 13-month-old Navajo girl,
ending a lengthy dispute pitting the Navajo tribe against the
biological mother and foster parents.
   Navajo Tribal Children's Court Judge Manuel Watchman granted
permanent guardianship of Allyssa Kristian Keetso to Rick and
Cheryl Pitts of San Jose, Calif., approving an agreement reached
April 22.
   ``All over! We've got permanent custody,'' Mrs. Pitts said with
a broad smile as she left the courthouse.
   ``I guess I should introduce you to Allyssa Kristian
Keetso-Pitts,'' her husband told reporters as he held the girl,
adorned in Navajo jewelry and wearing an ankle-length aqua satin
skirt.
   Her biological mother, Patricia Keetso, said: ``I feel wonderful
that it's over. I'm just glad that we can all continue on and not
have to worry about what's going to happen in the future or what's
going to happen next.''
   She said she loves the Pittses and considers them as extended
family.
   Under terms of the agreement, Ms. Keetso will retain her
parental and visitation rights, as the Pittses had said they
wanted. Tribal family members also will be allowed visitation.
   Mrs. Pitts said Allyssa will retain her culture and receive a
Navajo census number as an official tribal member. ``We pretty much
all got what we all wanted. I'm so glad it's over. I feel really
happy that we can go home and be a normal family,'' she said, her
voice breaking.
   Visitation arrangements will be up to the Pittses, Ms. Keetso
and the child's grandparents, Susie and Howard Keetso, Mrs. Pitts
said.
   Under the agreement, the tribe will retain jurisdiction until
Allyssa is 18, when she can petition for adoption, Pitts said.
   As the Pittses spoke to reporters, Watchman stepped outside
briefly to shake Pitts' hand and wish the couple well.
   But the ruling did not come before brief uncertainty over yet
another possible delay.
   The case pitted the Navajo tribe against the Keetsos, who are
tribal members, and the Pittses, who initially had sought outright
adoption of Allyssa. The Keetsos supported that effort and
subsequently the guardianship plan.
   In April, a California court transferred the Pittses' adoption
petition to the tribal court in response to a tribal request to
intervene. The California judge said the tribe held jurisdiction in
determining the child's custody under the Indian Child Welfare Act,
a law intended to slow the exodus of Indian children to non-Indian
families.
   During a hearing Wednesday morning, a tribal social worker
initially sought an additional 90-day delay, requesting further
information about the Pitts' finances and home life and raising
questions about the child's heritage and culture and plans for
visitation by other tribal family members, said Pitts, 33, an
independent contractor.
   After testimony from Pitts, the request was withdrawn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
