<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv02   09-01 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 02,0732</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday, Sept. 2</NOTE>
<HEAD>How The Have-Nots Help The Haves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is a situation in which the fate of the haves
and the have-nots are so closely linked that what happens to the
have-nots might determine how comfortably the haves live.
   It concerns the top-heavy home real estate market, one in which
the future of high-priced housing is dependent on what happens at
the lowest end of the scale, where first-time buyers generally
enter the market.
   First-time buyers increasingly are denied access to the market
by relatively high prices, insufficient incomes and rising interest
rates that push carrying charges beyond their financial abilities.
   The link to the other end of the market is this: In recent
years, the market for higher-priced housing has been made up mainly
of existing homeowners using their equity to move upto more
expensive homes.
   That is, the primary source of down-payment money for expensive
homebuyers has been the equity accumulated in starter homes.
   Very few homebuyers have been able to accumulate downpayment
money without having owned previously. Inevitably, such buyers have
been restricted at first to the least expensive ``starter'' homes.
   Those who have sought to accumulate downpayments through savings
accounts or investments have been stymied by income taxes, by home
prices increasing faster than their incomes, and by sometimes high
costs of renting.
   Now, along with higher interest rates that may make carrying
costs unaffordable, their problems with accumulating downpayments
may be worsening.
   A study of first-time homebuyers, conducted for the National
Association of Realtors, shows that housing affordability is now
lower than it was 11 years ago. First-time buyers, it said, are
losing ground.
   The study found that in this year's second quarter, a typical
family of renters had only 79.8 percent of the income needed to
qualify for a conventional mortgage with 10 percent down on a
median-priced starter home.
   In contrast, the typical family in early 1977 had 88.9 percent
of the necessary income.
   The baby-boom had a lot to do with the situation, since it
filled the market with an overflow of potential buyers and a
relative scarcity of houses. Thus, housing had its own inflation,
apart from general consumer inflation.
   In 1977, the median price of an existing single-family home was
$42,900; it was more than double that in 1987. The median price of
a new single-family home was $48,000 in 1977; it was about double
that in 1987.
   A big demand and a limited supply helped do that. But
supply-demand also affected the job market. Glenn Crellin, Realtor
economist, observes that ``the growth in incomes of the baby-boom
generation has been held back to some extent by the same
(supply-demand) phenomenon.''
   He explains: ``There are lots of baby-boomers but not as many
mid- and upper-level jobs. The result is that incomes have not
increased as rapidly as previous generations have seen.''
   It poses this threat to housing prices: If fewer buyers can
afford starter homes, which are the primary source of downpayments
for more expensive homes in the future, a prop will have been
removed from the upper end of the market.
   There may be an offset to the situation in the demographics.
   As the population bulge works its way through the economy there
will be a somewhat reduced demand for starter homes, a reduction
that might be reflected in a slowdown of price increases.
   The bulge of baby-boomers then will be in an older age category,
one in which couples historically seek more expensive housing.
There will, therefore, be a lot more people in the expensive-home
market.
   But, unless several factors are in their favor, including better
incomes and lower interest rates _ a big question remains:
   If they can't buy starter houses now, where will the
downpayments come for the bigger, more expensive houses in the
future?
   Moreover, if prices for starter homes don't rise as fast as in
the past, a reflection of reduced demand, won't that diminish the
equity available to those seeking to move up to more expensive
homes?
   That poses another question:
   Given such factors, can the upper end of the market maintain its
high prices?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Sept. 2.</NOTE>
</DOC>
