<1ST_LINE>s p BC-SenateRaces ADV04   09-01 0951</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Senate Races, ADV04,0974</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Campaign '88: Democrats Likely To Keep Senate Grip Despite GOP
Upset Hopes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With just two months left until Election Day,
Republicans are hoping George Bush and a little bit of luck will
help them claim enough of the 33 Senate seats up for grabs this
year to oust Democrats from control.
   GOP strategists say that goal remains within reach, but concede
it will take a strong showing by their presidential nominee and a
sweep of virtually every close Senate race for them to pull it off.
   ``I can't look you in the eye and say we're going to take it
over,'' said Tom Mason, spokesman for the National Republican
Senatorial Committee. ``But with good breaks, a strong
top-of-the-ticket effort which we're getting ... and with general
good luck, we could do it.''
   That luck seems to be elusive so far. Nonpartisan analysts say
Democrats seem to be having some early success in steering the
debate to domestic issues which they charge have been neglected
during the Reagan era, such as child and health care, jobs and the
environment.
   ``There is a subtle but important shift in priorities,'' says
Charles Cook, who publishes a political newsletter in Washington.
He sees the public shifting its perception of the Democrats from
association with discredited policies of the past to emergence as
the party of the future.
   Cook says it is ironic that because of President Reagan's
successes on national security and the economy, those issues have
faded into the background.
   ``When you're not in immediate danger of losing your job and
you're not in danger of getting blown up, these other issues
percolate to the top,'' Cook said. ``They're Democratic issues that
the Republicans should also be able to take advantage of, but in a
way they (the GOP) are getting robbed.''
   Major Senate battlegrounds are scattered all across the country
_ from California, Nevada and Washington in the West to Nebraska,
Wisconsin and Minnesota in the Middle West, Florida and Mississippi
in the South and Rhode Island, New Jersey and Connecticut in the
Northeast.
   Democrats now hold a 54-46 edge in the Senate, which they won
back in 1986 after six years of GOP dominance. While the arithmetic
theoretically favors the GOP _ they are defending just 15 seats
compared with the Democrats' 18 _ neither side appears likely to
gain or lose more than two or three seats.
   Attention so far has focused on six seats being vacated by
retiring incumbents and another half-dozen or so states where
incumbents are endangered or will have to scramble to withstand
well-known and well-financed challengers.
   Most questionable for the Democrats are three seats being
vacated by senior senators _ Lawton Chiles of Florida, William
Proxmire of Wisconsin and John Stennis of Mississippi.
   Republicans also are vacating three seats. The seat held by
outgoing Sen. Paul Trible of Virginia is a solid bet to be seized
by former Democratic Gov. Charles Robb. The GOP has a better chance
of holding onto Sen. Robert Stafford's seat from Vermont, where
Republican Rep. Jim Jeffords is considered the favorite. The
Washington seat of Sen. Dan Evans is considered a tossup.
   Complicating matters for Republicans is the endangered status of
three incumbents.
   Sen. Chic Hecht in Nevada appears most likely to fall to a
strong Democratic challenge from Gov. Richard Bryan. In Nebraska,
where David Karnes was appointed to the Senate last year, popular
former Gov. Bob Kerrey is considered a good bet to defeat him. A
combination of factors has put veteran Rhode Island Sen. John
Chafee in jeopardy of being bumped off by Lt. Gov. Richard Licht.
   Thus far in the campaign, no strong national trend has emerged
in the issues that Senate candidates are running on. But polls show
that after eight years of Reagan, the public seems ready for a
change. Overall, Senate candidates are sounding less ideological
and more pragmatic than at any time in the past decade.
   Seeking to exploit this perceived public mood, the Democrats are
offering to meet a wide range of domestic needs, although
candidates usually avoid any talk of the need for higher taxes to
pay for it.
   ``They are talking about taking care of problems in their own
neighborhoods and states,'' says Bob Chlopak, executive director of
the Democrats' Senate campaign arm.
   ``It starts with shoring up the economy. That means trade in
some places, manufacturing jobs or high-tech education in others.
It is children and opportunties for the next generation ... health
care ... Social Security,'' Chlopak said. ``We've ignored those for
too long.''
   National defense and foreign policy, the issues that helped
sweep Reagan into office and win GOP control of the Senate in 1980,
seem less significant in most races even for Republicans, Chlopak
says.
   ``A signficant number of Republican Senate nominees are running
on `change' sorts of themes,'' he said. ``They are distancing
themselves from the administration and in many instances from their
own voting records.''
   He notes that in Washington state, former Sen. Slade Gorton, a
Republican, is making a comeback bid based in part on chiding the
Reagan administration for neglecting certain domestic problems.
   In Mississippi, Republican Rep. Trent Lott is running for
Stennis' Senate seat talking about college tuition assistance and
more spending for highways. Reagan vetoed a major highway
construction bill.
   Republicans aren't conceding the point, however.
   The GOP's Mason believes economic themes play well for
Republican candidates, and says the party can claim credit for an
absence of direct national security threats. ``Peace and prosperity
issues ring pretty true,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 4</NOTE>
