<1ST_LINE>s p BC-HouseRaces ADV04   09-01 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-House Races, ADV04,0811</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Campaign '88: Both Parties Predict Modest Gains in Battle for
House Seats</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Ruthe is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incumbents traditionally hold an overwhelming
advantage in House races _ good news for the majority Democrats
this year and a continuing source of frustration for the Republican
opposition.
   The Democrats, with 256 seats in the 435-member House, say they
hope to win an extra three to five slots in 1988. The Republicans,
with 177 seats, are looking for a similar gain. There are currently
two vacancies.
   House-watchers say the modest projections _ a maximum five seats
plus or minus _ signal a year of limited ambitions. But Peggy
Connolly, a spokeswoman for the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee, disagrees.
   A gain of three to five seats is ``a fairly bold prediction,''
she said in light of Democratic failures in past presidential years.
   The recent high-water mark was 1964 _ the year of the Lyndon
Johnson landslide and 37 new Democratic House seats. In 1976, the
last time the party won the White House, the gain was one seat.
Since 1960, presidential-year losses have ranged from five House
defeats in 1968 to 33 in 1980.
   With the sky-high safe rate of incumbency, the best
opportunities for both parties continue to be seats left open by
death or departure. But there are only 26 this year, compared to 41
in 1986.
   A dozen of the open seats are currently held by Democrats and 14
by Republicans. Connolly said only two of the Democratic seats _ a
Florida district represented by Dan Mica and the New Jersey
district represented by the late Jim Howard _ are vulnerable to GOP
challengers.
   By contrast, she said Democratic candidates are competitive for
almost all of the 14 open GOP districts. But Rich Galen, a
spokesman for the National Republican Congressional Committee, said
simply being competitive ``doesn't turn the tide.''
   Galen said the 14 districts coming open are traditionally
Republican and likely to send GOP successors to Congress. ``I won't
concede any of those as potential losses,'' he said.
   Despite the advantages of incumbency, which range from heavy
financial contributions to cheap satellite time, there likely will
be a handful of casualties. In 1986, eight incumbents seeking
re-election were defeated. This year, the first was Rep. Ernest
Konnyu, R-Calif., who lost a primary.
   Some of the endangered lawmakers, like Reps. David Skaggs,
D-Colo., and Richard Stallings, D-Idaho, are from swing districts
or areas normally dominated by the rival party. Others have been
touched by scandal: Rep. Patrick Swindall, R-Ga., accepted a
questionable loan from a man indicted for money laundering but
later returned the loan; Roy Dyson, D-Md., whose chief of staff
tried to limit the social life of male aides and later committed
suicide; and Bill Chappell, D-Fla., who has been implicated in the
Pentagon procurement scandal.
   Reps. John Hiler, R-Ind., John Miller, R-Wash., and Ron
Marlenee, R-Mont., are facing rematches against tough challengers.
Others considered vulnerable are Reps. Bob Lagomarsino, R-Calif.,
facing state Sen. Gary K. Hart; and Jack Davis, R-Ill., running
against former state Senate president George Sangmeister.
   The Democrats are pouring money and attention into a Georgia
match that pits attorney David Worley against Rep. Newt Gingrich,
the conservative ringleader who filed an ethics complaint against
House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas.
   Though Democrats say at this point that they do not expect to
unseat Gingrich, they hope to keep him at home and on the defensive
about his proposal to replace Social Security with a voluntary
system and his ties to his district in light of his role as a
national conservative spokesman.
   Connolly denied that there is any element of retribution in the
focus on Gingrich but added, ``We want to tie him down. He's a
Republican rabble-rouser who we would like to contain in his
congressional district.''
   Women and blacks, with 23 members each in the House, stand to
make incremental gains this year. No black incumbents appear to be
imperiled and a new black lawmaker is sure to be elected from the
Newark seat being vacated by Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J.
   In Washington, which holds a Sept. 20 primary, King County
assessor Ruthe Ridder is competing with black Seattle councilman
Norm Rice for the Democratic nomination in an open, heavily
Democratic district.
   The Democrats are fielding a number of strong women candidates
for open seats and against incumbents. Among them are consumer
activist Rosemary Pooler, trying for an upstate New York seat she
almost won in 1986 from retiring Republican George Wortley; and San
Mateo County Supervisor Anna Eshoo, battling law professor Tom
Campbell for Konnyu's seat south of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 4</NOTE>
