<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have taken control of 14
failing savings institutions in Oklahoma and pledged up to $1.9
billion in aid to restore the state's savings industry to solvency.
   M. Danny Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
said Wednesday the 14 S&Ls will be consolidated into six larger
institutions under new management and the bank board will begin
looking for buyers immediately.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines attorneys have filed an emergency
appeal of a federal judge's order as the Miami-based carrier cut
back service but kept paying 4,000 employees it says it no longer
needs.
   The company filed its appeal Wednesday in the U.S. Court of
Appeals in Washington, saying the proposed layoffs ``were an
integral part of the overall decision to undertake schedule changes
and redeploy other flights.''
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker ruled Tuesday that Eastern
could reduce its flight schedule by 12 percent to save money, but
that it could not make mass layoffs without negotiating them with
its unions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American family income edged up 1 percent last
year but the number of people living in poverty also increased, the
Census Bureau says.
   Median family income rose to $30,850 last year from $30,534 the
year before, the bureau said Wednesday.
   But it said the number of Americans living in poverty last year
totaled 32.5 million, slightly higher than the 32.4 million
reported for 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark IV Industries says it is prepared
to increase its tender offer for Armtek Corp. to an indicated $568
million if the two sides can reach a satisfactory merger agreement.
   Mark IV, which already owns nearly 15 percent of Armtek's
outstanding shares, said Wednesday it is willing to increase its
bid from $44 a share to $46 a share. Based on Armtek's 12.35
million shares outstanding, the higher offer is worth $568 million,
up from $543 million.
   An Armtek spokesman declined comment on the latest proposal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. says it has discussed a takeover
of part or all of the company with Maxwell Communications Corp.,
which has a $2.34 billion tender offer for the publishing and
information services concern.
   Macmillan previously rejected Maxwell's current $80-a-share
tender offer as inadequate. But the company said Wednesday it has
provided London-based Maxwell with information on its operations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange and some of
its traders overcharged more than 1,000 investors who lost at least
$40 million the day after the stock market collapsed, an attorney
contends in a class-action lawsuit.
   Attorney Herbert Beigel alleged Wednesday in a class-action
lawsuit that the CBOE and floor traders responsible for making
markets in certain options on the Standard & Poor's 100 stock index
violated federal law and the exchange's own rules by charging
inflated prices for options contracts last Oct. 20.
   CBOE officials were aware of the lawsuit, which consolidates
three previous class-action lawsuits, but would not comment on it,
said spokesman Warren Moulds.
</TEXT>
