<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Education Department may be paying banks
and other lenders millions of dollars each year in excess subsidies
on student loans, a congressional watchdog agency says.
   The General Accounting Office said Wednesday its auditors who
reviewed 2,038 loan accounts at 16 major lenders found 18 percent
were in error or lacked adequate documentation to support the
amount billed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cordis Corp. has pleaded guilty in federal court to
concealing defects in thousands of heart pacemakers, and four
former executives were indicted for allegedly trying to cover up
the problems.
   The problems affected thousands of pacemakers sold from 1980 to
1985, according to Wednesday's indictment, which gave no precise
figures.
   Assistant Attorney General John R. Bolton, head of the Justice
Department's civil division in Washington, and interim Miami U.S.
Attorney Dexter Lehtinen, called the case ``the most significant
felony prosecution to date'' under the 1976 Medical Device
Amendments to the FDA law.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil companies have submitted 371 bids
totaling more than $190 million in an effort to grab bargain-priced
leases on 270 tracts of government-owend offshore properties in the
western Gulf of Mexico.
   The high bids ran to more than $131 million. Sohio Petroleum Co.
had the highest bid of the day with a $7.5 million offer for a
tract in the High Island area off the Texas-Louisiana coast. The
bid came to $1,306.24 per acre.
   It was the second offering of government-owned tracts in the
western gulf and the third gulf lease sale since the Interior
Department dropped the minimum per-acre price on the property from
$150 to $25.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Labor Relations Board is widening
the door for unions to recruit millions of health care workers,
telling hospitals they no longer can lump nurses with physicians,
or lab technicians with janitors as a tactic for thwarting
organizing drives.
   In a 153-page set of proposed regulations to be published today,
the NLRB is establishing eight broad categories of hospital
employees as appropriate separate bargaining units.
   The Associated Press obtained a copy of the regulations
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal law guaranteeing customers of banks,
savings associations and credit unions timely access to money they
deposit by check takes effect today.
   Congress passed the Expedited Funds Availability Act last year
after consumer groups complained that Americans were losing
millions of dollars a year in lost interest and unjustified
overdraft charges because some financial institutions were putting
holds as long as two weeks on funds deposited by check.
</TEXT>
