<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     09-01 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished weaker in light
trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for October
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, fell 9 cents per barrel Wednesday to close at $15.18.
Other contract months also dropped.
   Near-term contracts for refined petroleum products declined.
Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline
fell 1.49 cents to finish at 46.54 cents a gallon after rising
sharply on Tuesday. Other contracts also slipped.
   Analysts attributed the drop in gasoline futures partly to a
selloff by speculators wanting lower prices in advance of the
contract's expiration. The gasoline contract for September delivery
expired Wednesday.
   ``September gasoline had been a steadying force in the market,''
said Richard Kane, a trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
``But after today's activity it turned around. It was a function of
liquidating long positions.
   Wholesale heating oil for September fell 0.19 cent to 42.95
cents a gallon while other contract months also fell.
   Analysts said there was little fresh news to stimulate the
market other than a brief spark early in the day brought on by the
weekly API report released late Tuesday.
   The statistics showed a 4.234 million-barrel drawdown in crude
oil stocks for the week ending Aug. 26.
   ``It ostensibly was a good API number for crude. It helped the
market open higher,'' said Fred Demler, an analyst at Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. ``But the collapse of the gasoline market and
the sheer weight of the crude market brought it down.''
   After the brief move upward, prices began deteriorating
steadily, led by the drop in gasoline prices. Later in the day,
trading activity slowed considerably, analysts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
