<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Delta-Reputation Bjt   09-01 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta-Reputation, Bjt,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Believe Delta Can Weather Any Storm Caused By Dallas
Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial analysts believe Delta Air Lines Inc.
has built up enough good will in 60 years to withstand any damage
to its reputation caused by its second fatal crash at Dallas in
three years.
   A Boeing 727 crashed on takeoff Wednesday from Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport, killing 13 people. On Aug. 5, 1985, a Delta
Lockheed L-1011 crashed in a thunderstorm while trying to land at
the airport, killing 137 people.
   The airline also was beset by a series of unrelated, highly
publicized and embarassing incidents last year: pilots landed at
the wrong airport or on the wrong runway; one plane plummeted
toward the ocean because the pilot mistakenly shut off the engines;
another plane was involved in a near collision over the Atlantic.
   Nevertheless, Delta has maintained its reputation in the
financial community as a sound company and among consumers as a
safe airline.
   ``I don't think the reputation is undeserved,'' and it probably
won't change, said Robert Decker, an airline industry analyst with
Duff & Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said the airline expects little
long-term damage to its reputation.
   ``The passengers who fly with us, we think they feel very
comfortable,'' Berry said Wednesday. ``The traveling public stayed
with us'' during last year's problems. ``Those passengers who know
Delta don't feel Delta is doing something wrong. If there is
anything that Delta can do, we will do it.''
   Berry noted the airline had flown 119.3 billion passenger miles
since the 1985 accident without a fatality.
   ``If you ask people in airline maintenance who they think does
the best job, Delta's almost always the name mentioned first,''
said John Pincavage, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   Delta's common stock dropped $1 when news of the crash hit, but
recovered half of that by the close to finish at $46.50 per share
in New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Analysts attributed the stock drop as much to a round of fare
reductions touched off Tuesday by Continental Airlines as to the
crash itself. In addition, transportation issues generally declined
in Big Board trading.
   Anthony Hatch, an analyst in New York with Argus Research,
called Delta ``a terrifically well-run airline.''
   He said Delta survived last year's incidents because ``it had so
much good will in the bank, (and) I don't think they really lost
it.''
   ``These things aren't good for a company, but it's hard to
measure right now'' the final impact, he said, adding that ``people
aren't going to fly Eastern all of a sudden.''
   Eastern Airlines, Delta's chief competitor, has been rocked by
safety investigations of its aircraft and by labor troubles.
Eastern has cut back its routes, although a federal judge this week
blocked its plan to lay off 4,000 employees.
   Delta originated in the South in the 1920s as Huff Daland
Dusters, the world's first cropdusting service, a division of Huff
Daland Manufacturing Co. of Ogdensburg, N.Y.
   Led by Collett Woolman, the service broke away from the parent
company in 1928 to form Delta Air Service with headquarters in
Monroe, La. The first passenger flights took place in 1929,
ironically from Dallas to Jackson, Miss.
   Woolman, who ran the company until his death in 1966, is
credited with setting the tone for Delta, including its unique
tradition of having pilots greet passengers as they disembark.
   The company changed its name in 1930 to Delta Air Corp. and
later to Delta Air Lines Inc., and moved headquarters to Atlanta in
the early '40s. The company returns to Monroe for its annual
meeting.
   Delta's growth was spurred in the early years by the addition of
routes in the South and mergers with other airlines in 1953 and
1972. The biggest step came in 1987, when Delta completed an $860
million merger with Western Airlines Inc., making it the nation's
third largest airline.
   Delta, which operates 385 aircraft and has 55,000 employees,
earned a profit of $306.83 million on $6.92 billion in revenues
during the fiscal year ended June 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Eastern     09-01 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carrier Appeals Federal Judge's Order On Layoffs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, as expected, has asked a federal
appellate court to overturn an injunction stopping it from laying
off 4,000 employees.
   Eastern, in an appeal filed Wednesday with the U.S. Court of
Appeals in Washington, said the proposed layoffs ``were an integral
part of the overall decision to undertake schedule changes and
redeploy other flights.''
   The Miami-based carrier said it was losing several million
dollars per month on employees it does not need. Eastern also noted
the order prohibits the company from transferring what it called
``surplus employees'' to where work is available.
   Spokesman Robin Matell said the 4,000 employees _ hundreds of
them in cities where Eastern sharply reduced operations or ended
all flights Wednesday _ still were being paid.
   But no decision had been made on whether to assign them new
duties while Eastern is fighting for the right to dismiss them.
   ``They are being retained on the payroll. The whole thing is
being interpreted and evaluated, and we just don't have the answers
now,'' Matell said.
   Eastern argues that a federal judge should not be able to
restrict management's ability to make cost-cutting moves it deems
necessary. U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker in Washington on
Tuesday ruled Eastern could reduce its flight schedule by 12
percent to save money but could not make mass layoffs without
negotiating them with its unions.
   Among those being retained are 1,500 non-union employees, adding
to confusion over Parker's order. He invoked the Railway Labor Act,
which prevents major changes in contract status quo.
   The opinion did not spell out what should happen to the
employees. Union attorneys suggested they could be transferred, and
leaders of Eastern's three unions said they would like to meet with
management to discuss ways to cut costs without layoffs.
   Union leaders hailed Parker's ruling but agreed it was just
another in a long series of court decisions as the cost-cutting
Texas Air Corp. management, with a carrier $2.5 billion in debt,
goes against combative unions that contend the Houston-based
corporation is cannibalizing its Eastern subsidiary.
   The company and its unions still have myriad court battles under
way, ranging from a union effort to reverse the Texas Air sale and
allow employees to buy Eastern to a company lawsuit charging the
unions have conspired to intentionally damage the airline
financially.
   Still unresolved are contract talks with the Machinists and
pilots. The Machinists, in federal mediation since January, will
vote Sept. 15 on a company call for $161 million in annual wage
concessions.
   Eastern lost $182 million in 1987 and reported $149 million in
losses for the first half of 1988.
   Eastern had announced elimination of 140 flights on July 22, so
no passengers were booked on routes cut Wednesday, including all
service from 14 cities, mostly in the Western United States and
Caribbean.
   Eastern was losing more than $50 million a year at its Kansas
City hub, where low-cost Braniff Airlines has been increasing
business. The hub was eliminated and Eastern cut its Kansas City
daily flights from 53 to six.
   In Kansas City, most of 400 Eastern employees spent Wednesday
catching up on busy work.
   ``We were averaging about 4,800 passengers a day,'' said Walt
Green, Eastern's director of airport services in Kansas City.
``We've got about 500 today.''
   The company had asked employees not to report to work Wednesday
but to take compensation time or stay home without pay while
receiving full company benefits, he said. However, Green said only
about 35 people stayed home Wednesday.
   Most employees spent the day cleaning equipment and storing
supplies, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
