<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UtilityInvestigation     09-01 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utility Investigation,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ask No Action On Georgia Power's Rate Case Pending Fed Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorney general asked the Georgia
Public Service Commission to delay action on Georgia Power Co.'s
request for a $735 million rate hike while auditors probe evidence
of possible wrongdoing by the utility.
   The commission on Wednesday ordered a special team to
investigate allegations that utility officials concealed important
information during rate hearings last year. The utility has
requested the rate hike to help finance its share of a big nuclear
generation facility, Plant Vogtle.
   Attorney General Michael Bowers said the Public Service
Commission should take no further action in settling the rate case
until investigators complete their probe.
   The allegations surfaced Tuesday when federal officials released
documents on their investigation of possible tax fraud by the
utility. The documents indicated Georgia Power's parent company,
The Southern Co., and the Big Eight accounting firm of Arthur
Andersen & Co., also are objects of federal scrutiny.
   Among the documents were transcripts of taped conversations
indicating that Georgia Power financial officers may have hidden
records from the commission during hearings the rate increase.
   At one point in the transcript, Gary Givens, Georgia Power's
corporate tax manager, said company officials had ``taken home
floppy discs and things like that related to rate case
information.''
   ``We're concerned about the statement,'' said Commissioner Billy
Lovett. ``Obviously, we don't know what ... (records may have been
taken home). We have a team of auditors and examiners that will
look into every possibility that the commission did not get
complete information in rate cases.''
   Georgia Power Chairman Robert W. Scherer said he was shocked by
the allegations and promised he would ``get to the bottom of this
matter.'' He also vowed he would ``not tolerate the coverup of
wrongdoing at Georgia Power Co.''
   A statement issued by Arthur Andersen from the company's Chicago
headquarters denied wrongdoing.
   The federal investigation, dating back to 1982, involves charges
that the companies and their accountants sought to hide about $61
million in spare parts to avoid paying $50 million in federal
taxes, interest and penalties.
   An account in the The Wall Street Journal today suggested the
federal probe has widened significantly and is focusing on Arthur
Andersen's accounting advice to clients.
   The Journal said the Agriculture Department's inspector general
has subpoenaed documents from 11 major electric cooperatives, all
of which use Arthur Andersen as their auditor.
   The newspaper quoted Bob Bergland, former agriculture secretary
and now general manager of the National Rural Electric Cooperative
Association, as saying the subpoenas were issued because of
questions surrounding Arthur Andersen's opinion on the tax
implications of certain leasing arrangements.
</TEXT>
