<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Microsoft     09-01 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Microsoft,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Microsoft To Help Develop Sound And Graphics Standard For PCs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft Corp. says it has agreed with NV
Philips of the Netherlands and Sony Corp. of Japan to add sound and
graphics to the CD ROM format developed for personal computers.
   The CD ROM format was developed by Philips and Sony. It stands
for compact disk, read-only memory. The format uses compact disks
to record vast amounts of text and pictures.
   But CD ROM's graphics ability is limited to line drawings.
   Sony and Phillips also developed another system, CD-I, for
compact disk-interactive, that has sound and much livelier
graphics. But it won't work on personal computers.
   Microsoft spokesman Collins Hemingway said the aim of the
research is to devise a standard and write PC software that allows
programmers to create sound and graphics playable on personal
computers as well as CD-I equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Brazil-Banks     09-01 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Banks,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Constitution Limits Interest Rates to 12 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has voted to fix
inflation-adjusted interest rates at 12 percent a year under the
country's new constitution, despite protests from bankers and
businessmen that the measure won't work.
   The 559-member Congress passed the limit late Wednesday in
vaguely worded legislation regarding ``real'' interest rates, which
was interpreted to mean the level of interest charged above the
inflation rate.
   Inflation in the past 12 months totaled 496 percent, but some
banks and financial institutions currently charge more than 1,000
percent annually.
   The measure was sharply criticized by the government and the
business community.
   ``The notion is archaic and obsolete,'' said Rep. Francisco
Dornelles, a former minister of finance, who voted against the
measure.
   Planning Minister Joao Batista de Abreu said Thursday, ``Of
course I didn't like it. It's an unfortunate decision and hurts the
government's monetary policy.''
   Sen. Albano Franco, a prominent businessman and also an opponent
of the measure called it ``absurd. In no other country in the world
are interest rates fixed by the constitution.''
   The financial press also expressed disapproval of the
congressional decision.
   ``Fixing of Interest Rates Creates Crisis,'' read the headline
of the Rio de Janeiro newspaper O Globo on Thursday.
   The Folha de Sao Paulo newspaper said in an editorial the
decision was a product of ``the worst in Brazilian politics:
demagogery, ignorance and unreality.''
   The two-chamber Congress has been working since February 1987 on
the new constitution, Brazil's eighth, to replace an authoritarian
charter handed down 19 years ago during the 1964-1985 military
regime. The new charter is expected to be ready this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
