<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   09-01 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poverty Rate For Black Americans Rose Last Year, Survey Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs on second-quarter productivity and July
construction spending; picks up 2nd graf pvs, The report ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The productivity of non-farm businesses fell 1.4 percent in the
second quarter, the first drop since 1986 but less than previously
estimated, the Labor Department said today.
   The government had initially put the drop at 1.7 percent, but
revised it downward after deciding that the nation's economic
output in the April-June period had been greater than previously
estimated.
   In another report, the Commerce Department said construction
spending jumped 1.2 percent in July as strength in government
building projects and offices and apartments offset declines in
single-family housing, factories and shopping centers.
   Productivity is a measure of the number of hours of labor
required to achieve a certain output of goods and services. In the
period, employees' hours rose 6.6 percent, greater than the 5.2
percent increase in output.
   Analysts said the increase in hours and conseqent decrease in
productivity reflects a hiring boom in which employers are having
to compete for less-skilled workers because of decade-low
unemployment.
   Measured in dollars, U.S. factories have outperformed the rest
of the world in the past year in reducing labor costs, partly
through the smallest wage increases of any industrial country last
year.
   On Wednesday, the Census Bureau said the proportion of black
Americans living in poverty rose last year to nearly a third. It
said the overall poverty rate was fairly steady.
   The report Wednesday said a survey based on a sample of 60,000
families found that in the nation as a whole, incomes rose 1
percent and the poverty rate edged down. The changes were not
considered statistically significant because they fell within the
survey's margin of possible error.
   The poverty rate for blacks increased to 33.1 percent from 31.1
percent in 1986, the study said, meaning the number of blacks
living in poverty rose from 8.9 million to 9.7 million.
   ``The economic recovery is leaving many poor Americans behind,''
said Robert Greenstein of the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities, a private research group.
   In the financial markets Wednesday, the stock market posted
scattered losses. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished
with a 6.58-point loss at 2,031.65.
   The dollar rose strongly, especially against the Japanese yen,
while interest rates dipped in the bond market.
   According to the Census Bureau report, median family income for
blacks fell to $18,098 from $18,247, while the median income for
white families rose to $32,274 from $31,935.
   The poverty rate for whites dipped to 10.5 percent from 11
percent. For Hispanics the poverty rate rose to 28.2 percent from
27.3 percent.
   The government defined the poverty income level as $11,611 for a
family of four in 1987, up from $11,203 the previous year.
   William P. Butz, the Census Bureau's associate director for
demographic programs, said the nation's ``economic performance, in
terms of income and poverty, has been mixed'' as usual.
   The number of Americans living in poverty last year totaled 32.5
million, slightly higher than the 32.4 million reported for 1986.
The poverty rate was 13.5 percent, down from 13.6 percent.
   It is possible for the poverty rate to decline even when more
people are poor because the size of the population is growing
faster than the number of people living in poverty.
   The study found women's incomes continue to trail those of men.
It said women receive about 65 percent of males' take-home pay, a
percentage that has remained unchanged since 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
