<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GroceryMerger     09-01 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Grocery Merger,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC OKs American Stores Buyout of Lucky Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Inc.'s $2.6 billion
acquisition of Lucky Stores Inc. was approved by federal
regulators, a combination that builds American into one of the
nation's biggest supermarket companies.
   California Attorney General John Van de Kamp, who opposed the
deal on grounds it would cut competition and boost prices,
announced he would consider a legal challenge.
   In announcing Wednesday it had won antitrust clearance from the
Federal Trade Commission, American Stores said it would sell 37
California markets to meet commission requirements aimed at keeping
the company from too much control of business in certain areas. The
stores and buyers weren't announced.
   American Stores, which recently moved its corporate headquarters
from Salt Lake City to Orange County, owns 1,600 stores, including
Alpha Beta markets in California, Acme markets on the eastern
seaboard, Skaggs, Scaggs Alpha Beta and Buttery stores in the west,
and the 27-state Osco drugstore chain.
   The addition of Dublin-based Lucky's 480 outlets will put
American's sales in the neighborhood of those at industry leader
Kroger Co. of Cincinnati, and analysts have said it's difficult to
determine which is bigger.
   Approval of the American-Lucky buyout came two days after the
FTC approved another California supermarket combination _ the
purchase of 172 Safeway stores in Southern California by the
190-store Vons chain.
   In August, Van de Kamp filed formal objections to both mergers
with the FTC, citing a statistical study by his office that found
the deals would be bad for consumers.
   American Stores officials were unavailable for comment
Wednesday, after releasing their announcement of the FTC merger
after business hours.
   El Monte-based Vons has denied its purchase would hurt
consumers, and promised to cut prices at the Safeway markets it
bought. The Vons purchase doesn't affect the business of
Oakland-based Safeway outside Southern California.
</TEXT>
