<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Tourists     09-01 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Tourists,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Number of Visitors Descend On Britain in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record 15.4 million foreign tourists visited
Britain last year, including many more Japanese, Europeans and
North Americans, the government-funded tourist authority said
Thursday.
   The tourists, an 11 percent increase from the year earlier,
spent 6.2 billion pounds, equivalent to $10.4 billion, during the
year, said the British Tourist Authority.
   While the authority did not expect another such record year in
1988 because of a drop in North American tourists, they expected
increased European visits to partly offset the fall.
   The authority said in 1987 visits by Japanese increased 45
percent from 1986, those by Greeks and Italians rose 38 percent,
and Spaniards 24 percent. Visits by Danes and Latin Americans fell
3 percent and 11 percent respectively.
   North American tourists in 1987 increased by 19 percent from the
year before, said the authority, which said Britain was the
fifth-highest tourism-earning nation in the world.
   But the North American influx fell sharply this year according
to separate figures released Wednesday by the Department of
Employment. The number of North American tourists dropped 3 percent
in the first six months of the year compared with the same period
in 1987, the department said.
   Still, tourist authority officials remained cautiously confident.
   ``The North American market is now expected to show only a small
increase on last year but visits from the rest of the world
continue to grow so that overall 1988 will be at least as good as
1987,'' said Michael Medlicott, the authority's chief executive.
   Travel from North America from January through June 1988 fell 3
percent, but Western Europeans increased their trips to Britain by
3 percent, said the employment department.
   The tourist authority said Britain remained fifth in tourism
earnings for a second consecutive year last year, after the United
States, Italy, Spain and France in that order.
</TEXT>
