<1ST_LINE>u f PM-China-Money 1stLd-Writethru   09-01 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Money, 1st Ld-Writethru,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Runs, Panic Buying Plague China's Economic Reforms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, ``In Shanghai...'' to CORRECT dollar figure to
$27 million, sted $17 million. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``People
have...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese banks are facing runs on savings deposits
as customers withdraw large amounts of money in panic buying caused
by rising prices and empty stockrooms, the Chinese press reported
today.
   In the southern province of Fujian, savings deposits in
industrial and commercial banks dropped by 57.8 million yuan ($15.6
million) between Aug. 18 and 24, the official Xinhua News Agency
said.
   In Shanghai, 100 million yuan ($27 million) was withdrawn in the
past two weeks, the English-language China Daily reported in a
front-page story Wednesday.
   ``People have formed long queues in front of many savings banks
to withdraw their deposits because they fear further devaluation in
the value of their money,'' the paper said.
   People's Bank of China officials in Shanghai called a news
conference this week to refute rumors that a limit had been imposed
on savings withdrawals and assured the public that the bank ``has a
sufficient reserve of money ... to pay off deposits, no matter how
great the amount,'' the report said.
   ``If a depositor wants to withdraw 10,000 yuan ($2,702) at once,
we will pay him immediately,'' Zhou Zhishi, vice president of the
Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of China, China's central
bank, said.
   In Fujian, one customer took out 70,000 yuan ($18,919) in one
shot, Xinhua reported.
   The average urban worker's monthly salary is about 130 yuan
($35).
   Meanwhile, the daily sales volume of household electric
appliances such as televisions, refrigerators and washing machines
has doubled or tripled in Fujian, the news agency said.
   The panic buying has caused shortages in previously overstocked
goods such as cassette recorders, electric fans, bicycles and
pressure cookers, the report said.
   The bank runs and panic buying are caused by growing alarm among
Chinese consumers over dramatic price hikes and fears of
devaluation of their money.
   In the past year, prices have increased 19 percent in a country
that once boasted zero inflation.
   The interest rate, which was raised today from 7.2 percent for
one-year deposits to 8.64 percent, still falls far short of
inflation.
   The result is ``the popular concept that buying goods is better
than depositing money,'' Xinhua reported.
   The State Council, China's cabinet, issued a statement this week
promising to slow down the pace of the reforms that have caused
run-away inflation.
   The State Council agreed to hold prices in check for the rest of
the year and decided there will be no radical reforms in prices
next year.
   In mid-August, the Communist Party Politburo called for rapid
decontrol of state-set prices that would allow the value of goods
to be determined by market forces. The State Council also suggested
that interest rates would be raised next year to meet or even
surpass the inflation rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0276 </DOCNO>
