<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher On Talk of Soviet Buying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened higher today on
the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors that the Soviet Union made
some large corn purchases overnight, analysts said.
   The Soviets were said to have purchased 1 million to 1.5 million
metric tons of U.S. corn and another 500,000 metric tons of corn
from Argentina.
   Talk of a soybean meal purchase by the Soviets gave an
additional boost to soybean futures prices.
   Analysts have been expecting a resurgence of Soviet buying on
world grain markets.
   ``All of a sudden they're out there just buying the world up,''
said Jerry Gidel, a grain market analyst in Chicago with the G.H.
Miller division of British-owned LIT America Inc. ``The excitement
about the whole thing has got the market fired up.''
   The buying rumors apparently are being fueled by anticipation of
the end of talks between Washington and Moscow about renewing a
huge grain agreement under which the Soviets would buy millions of
tons of wheat, corn, soybeans and soybean meal.
   In early trading, wheat was 2{ cents to 4{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.01{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 8 cents higher with corn at $2.91 a bushel; oats were 4{
cents to 5{ cents higher with September at $2.61\ a bushel;
soybeans were 5} cents to 15{ cents higher with September at $8.70
a bushel.
   Cattle futures were lower while pork futures were mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .28 cent lower with October at
71.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent to .70 cent lower
with September at 81.30 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to
.40 cent higher with October at 38.60 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .32 cent lower to .40 cent higher with February at 49
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
