<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AmericanAirlines-Lawsuits     09-01 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Airlines-Lawsuits,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines Files Lawsuits on Frequent Flier Program</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   FORT WORTH _ American Airlines says it hopes lawsuits it filed
in three cities against individuals and companies will help end
alleged abuses of the airline's frequent flier program.
   ``We simply cannot tolerate this situation,'' said Lowell
Duncan, a spokesman for American, the nation's second-largest
airline. He said more lawsuits may be filed.
   American's frequent flier program, called AAdvantage, stipulates
that customers earning free flights and other benefits cannot sell
their tickets to others. Members of the program may give awards to
anyone they choose, but the airline has repeatedly reminded people
that the awards can not be sold, purchased or bartered.
   Most major U.S. airlines have the same requirement in their
frequent flier programs.
   American filed the lawsuits Wednesday in Fort Worth against
Texas Traveller, in Salt Lake City against Platinum World Travel
and The Coupon Connection; and in New York against American Coupon
Exchange. The companies do major business in buying awards from
frequent fliers and selling them to others.
   In all three suits, American has asked for an injunction to stop
the defendants from purchasing, selling, bartering or brokering
AAdvantage frequent flier bonus coupons.
   American filed a similar lawsuit Tuesday in Fort Worth against
Texas Budget Flights and the travel agency's owners, Curtis R.
Sweeten and Tonya K. Sweeten, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported.
   ``We have an obligation to our AAdvantage members who do abide
by the rules and to our paying customers to put a stop to the
practice,'' Duncan said. He said the complaints allege that
millions of dollars in revenue are being lost from the sale and
barter of AAdvantage awards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
