<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-01 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Prices Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied against major currencies in
quiet European trading Thursday, a day before the release of
potentially market-moving data on U.S. employment.
   Gold prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said traders were reluctant to take a
speculative position in the dollar before the August U.S. jobless
data scheduled for release Friday morning.
   They said the data was expected to show little change from
July's 5.4 percent rate, but a surprise could have an impact on the
dollar.
   The monthly jobless figures generally are regarded as one of the
most sensitive indicators of the U.S. economy's growth. Lower
unemployment implies higher growth, hence accelerating inflation
and higher interest rates.
   Anticipation of a long holiday weekend in the United States also
made market trading thin, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar jumped 1.73 yen to a closing 136.70. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 136.60 yen.
   The British pound fell in London to $1.6730, compared with
$1.6830 Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates compared with late Wednesday included:
1.8795 West German marks, up from 1.8780; 1.5835 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5828; 6.3780 French francs, up from 6.3755; 2.1205 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1230; 1,398.50 Italian lire, up from
1,395.75; 1.2370 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $429.50 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Wednesday. Late Thursday, gold rose to $430.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $430.50, up from $429.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.65 an ounce to $432.61.
   Silver was quoted in London on Thursday at a bid price of $6.58
a troy ounce, up from $6.52 Wednesday.
</TEXT>
