<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Down on Interest Rate Worries, Weak NY Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks finished a rough session broadly lower
Thursday, dragged down by declining Wall Street prices and concerns
that British interest rates may have to rise to curb consumer
spending.
   Earlier in the day, dealers on the London Stock Exchange
reported subdued trading activity after opening selling pressure,
but late afternoon large-scale selling reemerged as sentiment
remained cautious and nervous.
   Equities have been under pressure since last week's news of a
sharply wider British trade deficit in July and a subsequent rise
in bank base lending rates to 12 percent from 11 percent.
   The Financial Times 100-share index finished down 23.1 points,
or 1.32 percent, at 1730.5.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average was off 31.65 points as London
trading subsided, with much of New York's weakness related to the
impact of computerized selling strategies. Tokyo's fall Thursday,
where the Nikkei index plunged 431.69 points to 26,934.26, unnerved
market players over the direction of interest rates.
   Several dealers said they are convinced that British interest
rates will have to go higher following the news of last week's
record 2.15 billion-pound trade deficit.
   Early news from the Far East markets merely added to the
impression that there was no reason to commit money to equities,
dealers said.
</TEXT>
