<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-01 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Higher On Russian Buying Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed higher Thursday
on the Chicago Board of Trade on persistent rumors that the Soviet
Union had purchased at least 1 million metric tons of U.S. corn.
   The Soviets also were said to have bought 500,000 metric tons of
corn from Argentina and an undetermined amount of U.S. soybean
meal, analysts said. Corn and soybean meal can both be used as
cattle feed.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans.
   Analysts have been expecting a resurgence of Soviet buying on
world grain markets.
   ``The rumors continue to be optimistic about Soviet purchases _
there's a general feeling of optimism there,'' said Jerry Gidel, an
analyst in Chicago with the G.H. Miller division of British-owned
LIT America Inc.
   Prices opened higher and remained near their opening levels
throughout the session.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.00{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 8} cents higher with September at $2.91} a bushel; oats
were 5{ cents to 6} cents higher with September at $2.62 a bushel;
soybeans were 2} cents to 17{ cents higher with September at $8.72
a bushel.
</TEXT>
