<DOCNO> AP880901-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-UtilityMerger     09-01 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Utility Merger,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego Utility Rejects $2 Billion Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Diego Gas & Electric Co. on Thursday
rejected an unsolicited $2 billion takeover offer from the parent
of Southern California Edison, saying it preferred to merge with
Tucson (Ariz.) Electric Power Co.
   Tom Paige, a senior executive of the San Diego utility, said its
long-term interests and its customers would be better served by the
Tucson deal, which would match the Tucson company's excess
generating capacity with SDG&E's burgeoning customer base.
   Paige vowed that San Diego customers, whose electric bills are
among the highest in the nation, would see rate cuts as a result of
the proposed Tucson merger.
   ``The board has decided SDG&E should remain an independent
company pursuing its strategic goals and controlling its own
destiny,'' Paige said in a news release following a meeting with
officials of SCE Corp., parent of the huge Southern California
Edison Co.
   Edison boosted its bid by $50 million just Wednesday, bringing
the value of the stock-swap proposal to approximately $2.15
billion, and Edison officals angrily denounced the rejection,
saying their offer would remain in effect.
   ``It is unbelievable that SDG&E's management and board of
directors turned down SCEcorp's offer,'' said Howard P. Allen,
chairman and chief executive officer.
   He suggested SCE would continue to press its offer when state
regulators are asked to approve the Tucson merger.
   An acquisition by Edison, which serves most of Southern
California and parts of central California, would have created the
nation's biggest electrical utility, with 4.8 million customers and
a 54,000-square-mile territory.
   Edison maintained the acquisition made more sense than the
Tucson deal because the company's service areas adjoin and because
Edison has access to vast amounts of power generated throughout the
West.
   Edison also vowed to cut SDG&E customers' rates by 10 percent.
Paige said he was skeptical that could be done.
   The Tucson deal would involve an exchange of some $1.9 billion
worth of stock and leave SDG&E the surviving company.
   SDG&E officials have said previously the deal made sense because
of Tucson Electric's excess generating capcity. SDG&E produces
relatively little power, choosing instead to buy it from other
utilities.
   SDG&E serves one of the state's fastest-growing areas, northern
San Diego County, and would provide a ready market for Tucson
Electric's power.
   Edison's latest offer would give SDG&E shareholders 1.225 shares
of stock instead of the 1.2 shares of Edison made in an offer Aug.
19 and the 1.15 shares in the initial bid.
</TEXT>
