<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Heinz,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profits Rise 13.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.J. Heinz Co. said Thursday its earnings rose
13.3 percent in the first quarter, helped by improved sales and
continuing cost-reduction efforts.
   For the three-month period ended July 27, the giant foodmaker
reported after-tax profit of $110 million, or 84 cents a share, up
from $97.2 million, or 73 cents a share, in the year-earlier period.
   ``We are encouraged by the first-quarter results. They establish
a solid base which should enable us to achieve fiscal year growth
consistent with historical trends,'' Heinz Chairman Anthony J.F.
O'Reilly said.
   The company's revenue rose 10.6 percent in the first quarter to
$1.4 billion, from $1.2 billion in the first quarter of 1987.
   Heinz said currency exchange rates and price increases
contributed to the higher sales figures.
   The company cited excellent volume increases in Italy and the
United Kingdom and noted continued strong growth in Weight Watchers
products and healthy gains in pet foods.
</TEXT>
