<DOCNO> AP880901-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Markets Bjt   09-01 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Markets, Bjt,0672</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Wall Street Sags After Japan Market Drop</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plunge in stock prices on the Tokyo market
rippled through London and New York on Thursday as investors
worried about inflation and rising global interest rates.
   The decline in Tokyo's high-flying market was the third biggest
of 1988 and contributed to a 29.34-point decline in the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks to 2,002.31.
   Drops in key market indexes amounted to 1.6 percent in Tokyo,
1.3 percent in London and 1.4 percent in New York. Meanwhile, the
dollar leveled off from its recent rise and bond prices were little
changed.
   The world's central banks have been raising interest rates to
keep their economies from overheating. The higher rates tend to
siphon money away from stocks into interest-bearing investments
such as government bonds.
   Economists are divided over whether the world economy is running
so hard that there is a risk of runaway prices.
   ``I don't see the inflation pressure and the wage pressure that
the markets are worried about,'' Aubrey H. Zaffuto, an economist at
IBJ Schroder Bank & Trust Co. in New York, said Thursday.
   The bond market is usually the canary in the coal mine when it
comes to reacting to whiffs of inflation and rising rates, but in a
switch, bonds held up fairly well while stocks were sliding.
   ``The bond market seems to be holding in like a rock, so why the
equity market is jittery I don't know,'' Ms. Zaffuto said.
   The Japanese yen fell against the dollar to its lowest point in
nine months on Wednesday after the Bank of Japan said it did not
intend to raise its discount rate, a key rate charged on loans to
banks.
   When Japanese stocks plunged Thursday, some analysts said it was
partly because investors decided after the yen's drop that the Bank
of Japan would be forced to raise the discount rate after all.
   Higher rates could prick the bubble of high Japanese stock
prices, which would be particularly unwelcome at a time when the
government is trying to ensure a high sales price for its huge
offering of shares in Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
   Japan's low inflation rate takes off pressure to raise rates.
For one thing, it means the central bank can tolerate a decline in
the yen without worrying that it will raise import prices and push
up the general price level.
   However, Japan is supposed to help keep currency rates roughly
stable as part of the agreement of the Group of Seven major
industrial democracies.
   The Bank of Japan might intervene to sell dollars or raise
domestic rates if the dollar climbs to 138 or 140 yen from its
current level of a little more than 136 yen, said David Resler,
chief financial economist of Nomura Securities International Inc.
in New York.
   ``They're not ready to use their ammunition yet,'' he said.
   U.S. officials have seemed willing to tolerate a rise in the
dollar because dollar strength helps hold down inflation and
interest rates. But in the long run _ after the November elections
_ the strength of the dollar could worsen the trade deficit by
making American products more expensive in world markets.
   Some traders and analysts expressed anxiety that the government
would report on Friday a drop in the unemployment rate, a sign that
the economy could be growing too rapidly.
   In that case, the Federal Reserve might be convinced to take the
politically unpopular step of raising rates again before the
election to cool off a ``boom stage'' economy, said Edward J.
Campbell, a senior economist for Brown Brothers Harriman & Co.
   But Ms. Zaffuto said that seemed unlikely, or at least
unjustified.
   ``I don't think rates in the United States have to go up any
more for domestic considerations,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
