<HEAD>New Chairman Named For Chrysler Operating Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul E. Wright, who was instrumental
in the merger of RCA Corp. into General Electric, was elected
chairman of Chrysler Technologies on Thursday.
   The Washington D.C.-based Chrysler Technologies, which includes
Gulfstream Aerospace and Electrospace Systems Inc., is one of three
operating units of Chrysler Corp.
   Wright, 57, served until June as president and chief operating
officer of Fairchild Industries Inc., a defense contractor. Before
that, he spent 28 years with RCA, where he was vice president and
general manager of RCA's Aerospace and Defense Group. During the
four years Wright headed the division, sales doubled from $700
million to $1.4 billion.
   He was a senior vice president responsible for strategic
planning during the merger of RCA into General Electric.
   ``We looked long and hard for the kind of person who could
manage, lead and expand our aerospace and defense businesses,''
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca said. ``Paul's experience and record
of achievement make him the perfect choice.''
</TEXT>
