Friday's report from the Labor Department on the employment
situation for August.
   There has been some hope lately that the figures would show a
moderation of job growth, thus relieving some pressure for
credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve.
   But some analysts noted fears that any surprises in the report
could upset the markets.
   Advance estimates on Wall Street generally call for an
unemployment rate of 5.4 percent, unchanged from July, and at least
a modest slowing in the growth of payroll employment.
   Losers among the blue chips Thursday included International
Business Machines, down 1\ at 110\; Exxon, down | at 45~; American
Telephone & Telegraph, down { at 24]; General Electric, down { at
39~, and General Motors, down 1 at 71~.
