<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-01 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Slightly Lower, Gold Also Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased against most key currencies
Thursday in quiet U.S. trading, reflecting reluctance by money
brokers to speculate ahead of a market-moving unemployment report
and the long Labor Day weekend.
   Gold prices fell slightly in New York after rising abroad.
Republic National Bank quoted bullion at $429.75 a troy ounce as of
4 p.m. EDT, vs. $430.30 late Wednesday.
   The dollar's mild decline in the United States came after it
steadied in Europe and rose sharply in Japan, a carryover from the
U.S. currency's large advance on Wednesday, when the Bank of Japan
suggested it would limit domestic interest rate increases. That
news had sent the Japanese yen plunging.
   Foreign exchange analysts attributed the dollar's behavior
Thursday to money traders who sold the currency to reduce their
speculative positions, given the uncertainty over the impact of a
government report scheduled for Friday on August unemployment.
   The Labor Department's monthly jobless reports are considered
sensitive signals of the U.S. economy's health. Low unemployment
implies faster growth, higher inflation and rising interest rates.
Conversely, higher unemployment implies a slowing economy, lower
inflation and eased interest rates.
   If the Labor Department's report shows an unexpected drop in
joblessness, the dollar could rally sharply, some money-market
economists suggested. But others said the fear of inflation could
hurt the dollar as well.
   Moreover, many traders were reluctant to hold speculative
positions in the dollar during the three-day Labor Day weekend. The
net result was to persuade them to avoid the dollar at least until
next Tuesday.
   ``One of the concerns in the market is staying on the
sidelines,'' said Stuart Yannalfo, senior foreign exchange trader
at Refco Inc., a New York-based commodities and currency trading
concern. ``People who are used to trading a lot are waiting for
Friday's number and waiting for the holiday.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar jumped 1.73 yen to close at 136.70. Later
in London, it was quoted at 136.60 yen. By the time trading ended
in New York, the dollar was worth 136.27 yen, slightly cheaper than
its 136.51-yen level late Wednesday.
   The British pound fell, partly because of concerns over
Britain's economy. In London sterling traded at $1.6730, compared
with $1.6830 Wednesday. In New York, sterling fetched $1.6692 vs.
$1.6860 Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with its levels
late Wednesday, included: 1.8730 West German marks, down from
1.8765; 1.5787 Swiss francs, down from 1.5848; 1.2363 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2391; 6.3670 French francs, down from 6.3740;
and 1,393.75 Italian lire, down from 1,394.50.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Wednesday
included: 1.8795 marks, up from 1.8780; 1.5835 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5828; 6.3780 French francs, up from 6.3755; 2.1205 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1230; 1,398.50 Italian lire, up from
1,395.75; 1.2370 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
fell $1.10 a troy ounce to $430.20.
   Earlier in London gold closed at $430.70 a troy ounce, up from
$429.50 late Wednesday. In Zurich, gold closed at $430.50, up from
$429.50 late Wednesday, and in in Hong Kong it rose $2.65 an ounce
to $432.61.
   Silver for current delivery rose 1.8 cents a troy ounce to
$6.574 on the New York Comex. In London, silver closed at $6.58 an
ounce, up 6 cents.
</TEXT>
