<FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FuturisticTelevision-Zenith     09-01 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Futuristic Television-Zenith,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Reveals Planned Standard For Advanced Television</HEAD>
<HEAD>With WASHINGTON-dated AM-Futuristic Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp., the last U.S.-owned
television manufacturer, on Thursday proposed a standard for
futuristic television it said would deliver the full promise of the
technology.
   Zenith engineers submitted their proposal to the Federal
Communications Commission's advisory committee on advanced
television services. The action came Thursday as the FCC took
several steps to allow work on high-definition television to
proceed.
   Zenith said its proposal meets all the criteria laid out by the
FCC. In particular, it will not spoil the signal received by people
who stick with their current models of televisions.
   Zenith, based in Glenview, Ill., has stayed in TV manufacturing
even after the market has been largely taken over by Japanese,
South Korean and European companies. The company is reportedly
mulling the sale of the business to a foreign company or a group
representing unionized employees.
   About 20 proposed standards have been submitted to the FCC, but
Zenith said its proposal is the best because it is less susceptible
to problems.
   The audio signals and low-frequency portion of the video signals
would be sent in digital form, cutting down on the amount of power
required to transmit them and thus reducing the problems of
interference.
   The format would make it possible to use channels that are now
kept empty to avoid interference from neighboring channels. It
would make available about twice as many VHF channels and six times
as many UHF channels, making it possible to offer the
magazine-quality pictures and compact disk-quality sound of the new
generation of television, Zenith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
